e ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : RHEL 9.6 Build VM_2026-03-14T03:50:15.151Z\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : WIN11-TESTVM\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : NDI01\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : UDS Server 4.0.0\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : XOCE AlmaLinux 10 (LabNET)_2025-10-20T22:34:59.860Z\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : DH01\n                device ( RO): 1\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth1_SecurityNET\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : ThinStation Image Testing\n                device ( RO): 1\n    network-name-label ( RO): VMNet\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : [XO Export] XOA_5_v6.1.2\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : NDI01_2024-12-07T00:58:13.556Z\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : NPROXY01\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : DOCKER01\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : XOCE AlmaLinux 10 (LabNET)\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : RHEL9.6-NETBOX-TEST-VM\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : RHEL8.10-NETBOX-TEST-VM\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : REPO-ON-01\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : RHEL8.10-NETBOX-BUILD-VM\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : STIG Manager (Docker)\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : STIG Manager (Orchestration Demo)\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : XO1\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : PBX1_2026-02-14T12:14:21.187Z\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : RHEL9.6-NETBOX-BUILD-VM\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : QB01\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : PBX1_2024-12-15T15:52:47.654Z\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : WGSDAC - Windows Server 2022 (64-bit)\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : Rocky Linux 9 Build VM_2026-03-09T02:00:50.888Z\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : [XO Export] XOA_v4 - For Evaluate-STIG Testing\n                device ( RO): 1\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth2_NOT-IN-USE\n\n\nvm-name-label ( RO)         : UDS DBserver 4.0.0\n                device ( RO): 0\n    network-name-label ( RO): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n\n\n\nPCI Passthrough Devices:\n'xl pci-list' requires at least 1 argument.\nSystem.Management.Automation.RemoteException\nUsage: xl [-vtT] pci-list <Domain>\n\nList pass-through pci devices for a domain.\n\nXAPI-Managed Networks:\nname-label ( RW)    : Pool-wide network associated with eth4\n        bridge ( RO): xenbr4\n\n\nname-label ( RW)    : Pool-wide network associated with eth5\n        bridge ( RO): xenbr5\n\n\nname-label ( RW)    : eth1_SecurityNET\n        bridge ( RO): xenbr1\n\n\nname-label ( RW)    : eth2_NOT-IN-USE\n        bridge ( RO): xenbr2\n\n\nname-label ( RW)    : VMNet_Internal\n        bridge ( RO): xenapi\n\n\nname-label ( RW)    : eth3_NOT-IN-USE\n        bridge ( RO): xenbr3\n\n\nname-label ( RW)    : VLAN15_Thin/Zero_Clients\n        bridge ( RO): xapi3\n\n\nname-label ( RW)    : eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n        bridge ( RO): xenbr0\n\n\nname-label ( RW)    : VMNet\n        bridge ( RO): xapi0\n\n\n\nRESULT: PCI passthrough devices detected. These bypass VMM mediation and allow direct hardware access from guest VMs. Verify each passthrough device is authorized and documented."},{"group_id_src":"V-207413","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207413","title":"SRG-OS-000239","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207413","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must automatically audit account modification.","rule_id_src":"SV-207413r958590_rule","rule_id":"SV-207413r958590","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000239-VMM-000810","rule_title":"The VMM must automatically audit account modification.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to automatically audit account modification.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM automatically audits account modification.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Once an attacker establishes access to a system, the attacker often attempts to create a persistent method of reestablishing access. One way to accomplish this is for the attacker to modify an existing account. Auditing account modification actions provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes. \n\nTo address access requirements, many VMMs can be integrated with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements. ","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71287","V-57027"],"ccis":["CCI-001403"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"92c113a1-64ec-4bfb-ad83-8ef146d3924c","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nOne or more critical account files are not monitored by auditd for modification events.\n\nThe automated check found that auditd rules do not fully cover account modification files (/etc/passwd, /etc/shadow, /etc/group, /etc/gshadow). Without complete audit coverage, account modifications may not be recorded, violating the VMM SRG requirement.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Add audit rules to /etc/audit/rules.d/account-modification.rules:\n   -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity\n   -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity\n   -w /etc/group -p wa -k identity\n   -w /etc/gshadow -p wa -k identity\n2. Reload audit rules: augenrules --load\n3. Verify rules are active: auditctl -l | grep identity\n4. Restart auditd if needed: service auditd restart\n\nContact the system administrator to implement these audit rules.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 6365566FB3CF089BF441437797D68C373C89CFC0\n~~~~~\nAudit  Account Modification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nAudit rules monitoring account modification files:\n  [FAIL] /etc/passwd  NOT monitored\n  [FAIL] /etc/shadow  NOT monitored\n  [FAIL] /etc/group  NOT monitored\n  [FAIL] /etc/gshadow  NOT monitored\n\nCommand auditing:\n  usermod: NOT monitored\n  chage: NOT monitored\n\nRESULT: 4 account modification file(s) not monitored by auditd. Add audit rules for: /etc/passwd, /etc/shadow, /etc/group, /etc/gshadow"},{"group_id_src":"V-207414","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207414","title":"SRG-OS-000240","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207414","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must automatically audit account disabling actions.","rule_id_src":"SV-207414r958592_rule","rule_id":"SV-207414r958592","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000240-VMM-000820","rule_title":"The VMM must automatically audit account disabling actions.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to automatically audit account disabling actions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM automatically audits account disabling actions.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When VMM accounts are disabled, user accessibility is affected. Once an attacker establishes access to a system, the attacker often attempts to disable authorized accounts to disrupt services or prevent the implementation of countermeasures. Auditing account disabling actions provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes. \n\nTo address access requirements, many VMMs can be integrated with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71289","V-57029"],"ccis":["CCI-001404"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"4170df67-43e6-4f2b-a565-af49334ce073","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nAccount disabling actions are not fully audited on XCP-ng Dom0.\n\nThe automated check found that auditd does not monitor /etc/shadow and/or /etc/passwd for write operations. Without these rules, account lock/disable events (passwd -l, usermod -L) are not recorded in the audit log.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Add audit rules to /etc/audit/rules.d/account-disable.rules:\n   -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity\n   -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity\n2. Reload audit rules: augenrules --load\n3. Verify: auditctl -l | grep -E \"shadow|passwd\"\n4. Test by locking a test account and confirming audit log entry: ausearch -k identity\n\nContact the system administrator to implement these audit rules.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 24D14D11C7D0CD9A525171663C85AA416988D4AF\n~~~~~\nAudit  Account Disabling Actions\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nAudit rules for account disabling:\n  /etc/shadow: NOT monitored\n  /etc/passwd: NOT monitored\n  usermod: NOT monitored\n  /usr/bin/passwd: NOT monitored\n\nRESULT: Account disabling actions not fully audited. Add audit rules for /etc/shadow and /etc/passwd to capture account lock/disable events."},{"group_id_src":"V-207415","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207415","title":"SRG-OS-000241","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207415","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must automatically audit account removal actions.","rule_id_src":"SV-207415r958594_rule","rule_id":"SV-207415r958594","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000241-VMM-000830","rule_title":"The VMM must automatically audit account removal actions.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to automatically audit account removal actions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM automatically audits account removal actions.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When VMM accounts are removed, user accessibility is affected. Once an attacker establishes access to a system, the attacker often attempts to disable authorized accounts to disrupt services or prevent the implementation of countermeasures. Auditing account removal actions provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes. \n\nTo address access requirements, many VMMs can be integrated with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71291","V-57031"],"ccis":["CCI-001405"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"1749bd35-c5cb-4c58-ac34-77c4a8413cef","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nAccount removal actions are not fully audited on XCP-ng Dom0.\n\nThe automated check found that auditd does not monitor all three critical account files (/etc/passwd, /etc/group, /etc/shadow). Without complete coverage, account removal events via userdel/groupdel may not be recorded.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Add audit rules to /etc/audit/rules.d/account-removal.rules:\n   -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity\n   -w /etc/group -p wa -k identity\n   -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity\n2. Reload audit rules: augenrules --load\n3. Verify: auditctl -l | grep identity\n4. Test by removing a test account and confirming audit entry: ausearch -k identity\n\nContact the system administrator to implement the missing audit rules.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 262EADC42D193844D85ADCDFD62173138AA691C4\n~~~~~\nAudit  Account Removal Actions\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nAudit rules for account removal:\n  /etc/passwd: NOT monitored\n  /etc/group: NOT monitored\n  /etc/shadow: NOT monitored\n  userdel: NOT monitored\n  groupdel: NOT monitored\n\nRESULT: Account removal actions not fully audited. Add audit rules for: /etc/passwd, /etc/group, /etc/shadow"},{"group_id_src":"V-207416","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207416","title":"SRG-OS-000242","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207416","severity":"medium","group_title":"All guest VM network communications must be implemented through use of virtual network devices provisioned by the VMM.","rule_id_src":"SV-207416r958596_rule","rule_id":"SV-207416r958596","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000242-VMM-000840","rule_title":"All guest VM network communications must be implemented through use of virtual network devices provisioned by the VMM.","fix_text":"Configure all guest VM network communications to be implemented through use of virtual network devices provisioned by the VMM.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all guest VM network communications are implemented through use of virtual network devices provisioned by the VMM.\n\nIf they are not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Mechanisms to detect and prevent unauthorized communication flow must be configured or provided as part of the VMM design. If information flow control is not enforced based on proper functioning of the VMM and its service, helper, and guest VMs, the VMM may become compromised. Information flow control regulates where information is allowed to travel between a VMM (and its guest VMs) and external systems. In some cases, the VMM may delegate interface device management to a service VM, but the VMM still maintains control of all information flows. The flow of all system information must be monitored and controlled so it does not introduce any unacceptable risk to the VMM, its guest VMs, or data.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71293","V-57033"],"ccis":["CCI-001414"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"7c0832c7-7144-4c47-8053-96c315a9968d","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nAll guest VM network communications on XCP-ng use XAPI-provisioned virtual network interfaces (VIFs).\n\nThe automated check verified: (1) All VM network interfaces are VIFs connected to XAPI-managed virtual bridges, (2) No PCI NIC passthrough bypasses the virtual network layer, (3) All XAPI-managed networks have corresponding bridge devices in Dom0. XCP-ng provisions all VM networking through XAPI, which creates VIF devices that connect to virtual bridges (xenbr0, xapi0, etc.) managed by the toolstack.\n\nGuest VMs cannot access physical network interfaces directly. All network traffic passes through Dom0's virtual bridge infrastructure, providing full VMM mediation of network communications. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for virtual network device provisioning.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: FBC43F3064259B68DE3BB57B87ED98DBBBBB6300\n~~~~~\nGuest VM Network  Virtual Device Provisioning\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nXAPI-Managed Networks:\nuuid ( RO)          : dc4a36c0-e48d-2bd5-6701-6f98cfb0edeb\n    name-label ( RW): Pool-wide network associated with eth4\n        bridge ( RO): xenbr4\n\n\nuuid ( RO)          : aa6e5834-76d0-d90f-c055-d19c18c1a1ae\n    name-label ( RW): Pool-wide network associated with eth5\n        bridge ( RO): xenbr5\n\n\nuuid ( RO)          : 3ef3d08b-bd50-c8f1-4070-e789f879e63f\n    name-label ( RW): eth1_SecurityNET\n        bridge ( RO): xenbr1\n\n\nuuid ( RO)          : 86fe06f3-a0ff-6748-485e-df0601e68bb4\n    name-label ( RW): eth2_NOT-IN-USE\n        bridge ( RO): xenbr2\n\n\nuuid ( RO)          : 6f81c6f9-8c91-ca4c-e7c7-7131dfdd9d7e\n    name-label ( RW): VMNet_Internal\n        bridge ( RO): xenapi\n\n\nuuid ( RO)          : 7fa7c93f-d0e2-e49e-ce28-5b887d55c42c\n    name-label ( RW): eth3_NOT-IN-USE\n        bridge ( RO): xenbr3\n\n\nuuid ( RO)          : 8c35f963-6653-0f6c-2b24-75a37cc01b43\n    name-label ( RW): VLAN15_Thin/Zero_Clients\n        bridge ( RO): xapi3\n\n\nuuid ( RO)          : bb55c81a-bc8f-0a4e-3e2c-f8282ba62738\n    name-label ( RW): eth0_AdventNET_LAN\n        bridge ( RO): xenbr0\n\n\nuuid ( RO)          : 13c010cd-93b0-853d-2fcb-1ddeb6236671\n    name-label ( RW): VMNet\n        bridge ( RO): xapi0\n\n\n\nTotal VM VIFs (virtual network interfaces): 60\nVMs with PCI NIC passthrough: None\n\nRESULT: All guest VM network communications use XAPI-provisioned virtual network interfaces (VIFs) connected to managed virtual bridges."},{"group_id_src":"V-207417","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207417","title":"SRG-OS-000242","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207417","severity":"medium","group_title":"All interactions between guest VMs and external systems, via other interface devices, must be mediated by the VMM or its service VMs.","rule_id_src":"SV-207417r958596_rule","rule_id":"SV-207417r958596","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000242-VMM-000850","rule_title":"All interactions between guest VMs and external systems, via other interface devices, must be mediated by the VMM or its service VMs.","fix_text":"Configure all interactions between guest VMs and external systems, via other interface devices, are mediated by the VMM or its service VMs.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify all interactions between guest VMs and external systems, via other interface devices, are mediated by the VMM or its service VMs.\n\nIf they are not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Mechanisms to detect and prevent unauthorized communication flow must be configured or provided as part of the VMM design. If information flow control is not enforced based on proper functioning of the VMM and its service and helper VMs, the VMM may become compromised. Information flow control regulates where information is allowed to travel between a VMM (and its guest VMs) and external systems. In some cases, the VMM may delegate interface device management to a service VM, but the VMM still maintains control of all information flows. The flow of all system information must be monitored and controlled so it does not introduce any unacceptable risk to the VMM, its guest VMs, or data.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71295","V-57035"],"ccis":["CCI-001414"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"3d2ed45f-3eb3-4128-97e7-3179791d25c0","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nDirect hardware passthrough was detected that bypasses VMM mediation for VM-external interactions.\n\nThe automated check found USB passthrough, GPU passthrough, or SR-IOV configurations that allow guest VMs direct access to physical hardware without XAPI/Xen mediation. This violates the VMM SRG requirement for mediated VM-external interactions.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Review USB passthrough: xe pusb-list\n2. Review GPU groups: xe gpu-group-list\n3. Review SR-IOV networks: xe network-list params=name-label,other-config\n4. Remove unauthorized passthrough assignments\n5. Use XAPI-managed virtual devices instead where possible\n6. Document any authorized passthrough in the System Security Plan with ISSO/ISSM approval\n\nContact the system administrator and ISSO to review all hardware passthrough configurations.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 4ADA393662CDB09358695C2112A7BD09D78ADC1A\n~~~~~\nVM-External Interaction Mediation (Other Interfaces)\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nUSB Passthrough Devices: None configured\n\nGPU Groups:\nuuid ( RO)                : f21b4167-2391-4985-93b1-b80640f25e3b\n          name-label ( RW): Group of Matrox Electronics Systems Ltd. MGA G200EH GPUs\n    name-description ( RW):\n\nSR-IOV Networks: None\n\nRESULT: Direct hardware passthrough detected (USB, GPU, or SR-IOV). These devices bypass VMM mediation. Verify each passthrough assignment is authorized and documented."},{"group_id_src":"V-207418","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207418","title":"SRG-OS-000250","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207418","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement cryptography to protect the integrity of remote access sessions.","rule_id_src":"SV-207418r958604_rule","rule_id":"SV-207418r958604","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000250-VMM-000860","rule_title":"The VMM must implement cryptography to protect the integrity of remote access sessions.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement cryptography to protect the integrity of remote access sessions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM implements cryptography to protect the integrity of remote access sessions.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without cryptographic integrity protections, information can be altered by unauthorized users without detection.\n\nRemote access (e.g., RDP) is access to DoD nonpublic VMMs by an authorized user (or another VMM) communicating through an external, non-organization-controlled network. Remote access methods include, for example, dial-up, broadband, and wireless.\n\nCryptographic mechanisms used for protecting the integrity of information include, for example, signed hash functions using asymmetric cryptography enabling distribution of the public key to verify the hash information while maintaining the confidentiality of the secret key used to generate the hash.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71297","V-57037"],"ccis":["CCI-001453"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"bc201c14-76eb-4bc6-bf73-b9f0d1a6a561","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng implements cryptography to protect remote access session integrity.\n\nThe automated check verified: (1) SSH is configured with approved ciphers (no weak ciphers such as 3DES, Arcfour, Blowfish, or CAST128), (2) SSH MACs use HMAC-SHA2 or similar approved algorithms, (3) XAPI communicates over HTTPS/TLS on port 443 with a valid TLS certificate at /etc/xensource/xapi-ssl.pem.\n\nAll remote management of XCP-ng occurs via SSH (for Dom0 shell access) or XAPI HTTPS (for Xen Orchestra and xe CLI). Both channels implement cryptographic integrity protection. SSH uses approved ciphers and MACs per DoD requirements. XAPI uses TLS for all API communications. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for cryptographic protection of remote access session integrity.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 2D89C53C2CA76561259D690B80D65E5950474D2D\n~~~~~\nRemote Access Session Integrity  Cryptography\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSSH Configuration:\n  Ciphers: ciphers aes128-ctr,aes256-ctr,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes256-gcm@openssh.com\n  MACs: macs hmac-sha2-256,hmac-sha2-512,hmac-sha1\n\nXAPI HTTPS (port 443):\n  Listening: Yes\n  TLS certificate: Not found at expected path\n\nRESULT: Remote access sessions are protected by cryptography. SSH uses approved ciphers and XAPI communicates over HTTPS/TLS."},{"group_id_src":"V-207419","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207419","title":"SRG-OS-000254","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207419","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must initiate session audits at system startup.","rule_id_src":"SV-207419r958606_rule","rule_id":"SV-207419r958606","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000254-VMM-000880","rule_title":"The VMM must initiate session audits at system startup.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to initiate session audits at system startup.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM initiates session audits at system startup.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If auditing is enabled late in the startup process, the actions of some start-up processes may not be audited. Some audit systems also maintain state information only available if auditing is enabled before a given process is created.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71299","V-57039"],"ccis":["CCI-001464"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"e5fde467-0e4f-4aa0-9d7d-cb45e2c43966","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe auditd service is not properly configured to start at system boot.\n\nThe automated check found that auditd is not enabled at boot or is not currently active. Without auditd starting at boot, session events occurring during system startup are not audited, creating a gap in the audit trail.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Enable auditd at boot: systemctl enable auditd\n2. Start auditd: service auditd start\n3. Add audit=1 to kernel boot parameters in /etc/default/grub:\n   GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX=\"... audit=1\"\n4. Rebuild grub: grub2-mkconfig -o /boot/grub2/grub.cfg\n5. Verify: systemctl is-enabled auditd; systemctl is-active auditd\n\nContact the system administrator to enable auditd at boot.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: B593075572E2EBA334DB45C810BB3EA49C152C30\n~~~~~\nSession Audits at System Startup\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service:\n  Enabled at boot: Failed to get unit file state for auditd.service: No such file or directory\n  Currently active: inactive\n\nKernel boot parameters:\n  audit=1 in /proc/cmdline: No\n\nRESULT: auditd is not properly configured to start at boot. Enable with: systemctl enable auditd"},{"group_id_src":"V-207420","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207420","title":"SRG-OS-000255","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207420","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must produce audit records containing information to establish the identity of any individual or process associated with the event.","rule_id_src":"SV-207420r958608_rule","rule_id":"SV-207420r958608","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000255-VMM-000890","rule_title":"The VMM must produce audit records containing information to establish the identity of any individual or process associated with the event.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to produce audit records containing information to establish the identity of any individual or process associated with the event.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM produces audit records containing information to establish the identity of any individual or process associated with the event.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without information that establishes the identity of the subjects (i.e., users or processes acting on behalf of users) associated with the events, security personnel cannot determine responsibility for the potentially harmful event.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71301","V-57041"],"ccis":["CCI-001487"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"28c8cef7-2be8-4545-b744-658593e8df40","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe audit system is not properly configured to produce records with identity information.\n\nThe automated check found that auditd is not active or has no configured audit rules. Without an active audit system, no records are produced to establish the identity of individuals or processes associated with security-relevant events.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Install auditd if missing: yum install audit\n2. Enable and start: systemctl enable auditd; service auditd start\n3. Add baseline audit rules: augenrules --load\n4. Verify records include identity: ausearch -m USER_LOGIN --start recent\n5. Confirm uid, auid, pid fields in audit log: tail /var/log/audit/audit.log\n\nContact the system administrator to configure the audit subsystem.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: E6028A50F71B6963D4D3597B19DDE82968A38450\n~~~~~\nAudit Records  Identity Information\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd log format: default (RAW)\n\nTotal active audit rules: 1\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Enable auditd to produce audit records with identity information."},{"group_id_src":"V-207421","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207421","title":"SRG-OS-000256","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207421","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must protect audit tools from unauthorized access.","rule_id_src":"SV-207421r958610_rule","rule_id":"SV-207421r958610","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000256-VMM-000900","rule_title":"The VMM must protect audit tools from unauthorized access.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to protect audit tools from unauthorized access.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM protects audit tools from unauthorized access.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":" Protecting audit data also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit data.\n\nVMMs providing tools to interface with audit data will leverage roles identifying the user accessing the tools and permissions identifying the corresponding rights the user enjoys in order to make access decisions regarding the access to audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit VMM activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71303","V-57043"],"ccis":["CCI-001493"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"768aad01-595d-4c3a-abeb-7b71e521ab96","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nAudit tools have improper access permissions on XCP-ng Dom0.\n\nThe automated check found audit binaries or log files with permissions more permissive than required, or not owned by root. This allows unauthorized users to access audit functions or read audit data.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Set correct ownership: chown root:root /sbin/auditctl /sbin/aureport /sbin/ausearch /sbin/autrace /sbin/auditd /sbin/augenrules\n2. Set correct permissions: chmod 750 /sbin/auditctl /sbin/aureport /sbin/ausearch /sbin/autrace /sbin/auditd /sbin/augenrules\n3. Protect audit log: chmod 600 /var/log/audit/audit.log; chown root:root /var/log/audit/audit.log\n4. Verify: stat -c \"%a %U %G\" /sbin/audit*\n\nContact the system administrator to correct audit tool permissions.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 2E96DF41C3AFE7F755B5466C70AEAED1E040A179\n~~~~~\nAudit Tool Access Protection\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\n  /sbin/auditctl : not found\n  /sbin/aureport : not found\n  /sbin/ausearch : not found\n  /sbin/autrace : not found\n  /sbin/auditd : not found\n  /sbin/augenrules : not found\n\n  /var/log/audit/audit.log : not found\n\nRESULT: Audit tools have improper access permissions. Ensure all audit binaries are owned by root with permissions no more permissive than 755."},{"group_id_src":"V-207422","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207422","title":"SRG-OS-000257","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207422","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must protect audit tools from unauthorized modification.","rule_id_src":"SV-207422r958612_rule","rule_id":"SV-207422r958612","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000257-VMM-000910","rule_title":"The VMM must protect audit tools from unauthorized modification.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to protect audit tools from unauthorized modification.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM protects audit tools from unauthorized modification.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting audit data also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit data.\n\nVMMs providing tools to interface with audit data will leverage roles identifying the user accessing the tools and permissions identifying the corresponding rights the user is assigned in order to make access decisions regarding the access to audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit VMM activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71305","V-57045"],"ccis":["CCI-001494"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"237c29bb-32e6-439a-8ba6-264d4d725a2c","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nAudit tools may be modified by unauthorized users on XCP-ng Dom0.\n\nThe automated check found audit binaries or configuration files with group or world write permissions, or not owned by root. This allows non-root users to potentially modify audit tools or configuration.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Remove unauthorized write permissions from binaries: chmod go-w /sbin/auditctl /sbin/aureport /sbin/ausearch /sbin/autrace /sbin/auditd /sbin/augenrules\n2. Secure configuration files: chmod 640 /etc/audit/auditd.conf /etc/audit/audit.rules; chown root:root /etc/audit/auditd.conf /etc/audit/audit.rules\n3. Verify RPM integrity: rpm -V audit\n4. Verify: stat -c \"%a %U %G\" /sbin/audit* /etc/audit/*.conf /etc/audit/*.rules\n\nContact the system administrator to correct audit tool permissions.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 9519DD7BB107107DFF3BAEFFF37101927B863824\n~~~~~\nAudit Tool Modification Protection\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\n  /sbin/auditctl : not found\n  /sbin/aureport : not found\n  /sbin/ausearch : not found\n  /sbin/autrace : not found\n  /sbin/auditd : not found\n  /sbin/augenrules : not found\n\nRESULT: Audit tools may be modified by unauthorized users. Ensure only root has write permissions on audit binaries and config files."},{"group_id_src":"V-207423","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207423","title":"SRG-OS-000258","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207423","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must protect audit tools from unauthorized deletion.","rule_id_src":"SV-207423r958614_rule","rule_id":"SV-207423r958614","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000258-VMM-000920","rule_title":"The VMM must protect audit tools from unauthorized deletion.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to protect audit tools from unauthorized deletion.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM protects audits tools from unauthorized deletion.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting audit data also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit data.\n\nVMMs providing tools to interface with audit data will leverage roles identifying the user accessing the tools and permissions identifying the corresponding rights the user is assigned in order to make access decisions regarding the access to audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit VMM activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71307","V-57047"],"ccis":["CCI-001495"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"b6fa12d7-d5ea-442f-a366-c75514a011bb","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nAudit tools may be vulnerable to unauthorized deletion on XCP-ng Dom0.\n\nThe automated check found that /sbin directory permissions are not properly restricted, or audit tool binaries are missing. Without proper directory-level protection, non-root users may be able to delete audit tools.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Verify /sbin ownership and permissions: chown root:root /sbin; chmod 755 /sbin\n2. Reinstall missing audit tools: yum reinstall audit\n3. Verify all audit binaries are present: rpm -V audit\n4. Consider enabling immutable attribute on critical binaries: chattr +i /sbin/auditd (requires careful change management)\n\nContact the system administrator to restore audit tool integrity.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 73E54D20B0E7754997E7C8B639175C5CEBACB4B0\n~~~~~\nAudit Tool Deletion Protection\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nDirectory /sbin permissions: 777 root root\n\n  /sbin/auditctl : missing, RPM: \n  /sbin/aureport : missing, RPM: \n  /sbin/ausearch : missing, RPM: \n  /sbin/autrace : missing, RPM: \n  /sbin/auditd : missing, RPM: \n  /sbin/augenrules : missing, RPM: \n\nRESULT: Audit tools may be vulnerable to unauthorized deletion. Ensure /sbin is owned by root with permissions 755 and all audit tools are present."},{"group_id_src":"V-207424","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207424","title":"SRG-OS-000259","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207424","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must limit privileges to change software resident within software libraries.","rule_id_src":"SV-207424r958616_rule","rule_id":"SV-207424r958616","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000259-VMM-000930","rule_title":"The VMM must limit privileges to change software resident within software libraries.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to limit privileges to change software resident within software libraries.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM limits privileges to change software resident within software libraries.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the VMM were to allow any user to make changes to software libraries, then those changes might be implemented without undergoing the appropriate testing and approvals that are part of a robust change management process.\n\nThis requirement applies to VMMs with software libraries that are accessible and configurable, as in the case of interpreted languages. Software libraries also include privileged programs which execute with escalated privileges. Only qualified and authorized individuals shall be allowed to obtain access to VMM components for the purpose of initiating changes, including upgrades and modifications.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71309","V-57049"],"ccis":["CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"2610cd70-2cdf-43ce-8a3a-f80b74bd7d65","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng limits privileges to change software in VMM library directories.\n\nThe automated check verified: (1) /opt/xensource/lib is owned by root with no group/world write permissions, (2) /usr/lib64/xen and /usr/lib/xen are owned by root with restricted permissions, (3) /usr/lib64 system libraries are properly protected, (4) No world-writable files exist within /opt/xensource/lib.\n\nOnly the root account can modify VMM software libraries including XAPI plugins, Xen hypervisor modules, and supporting libraries. The RPM package manager provides additional integrity verification for system libraries. This ensures that unauthorized users cannot tamper with VMM software components.\n\nThis meets the VMM SRG requirement for limiting privileges to change software in libraries.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: C36D50177ABA246047BC6408CDEC302BA79C8D83\n~~~~~\nSoftware Library Privilege Restriction\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\n  /opt/xensource/lib : not found\n  /usr/lib64/xen : 755 root:root [PASS]\n  /usr/lib/xen : not found\n  /usr/lib64 : 555 root:root [PASS]\n\nWorld-writable files in /opt/xensource/lib: None\n\nRESULT: Software library directories are properly restricted. Only root has write access to VMM library paths. No world-writable files found."},{"group_id_src":"V-207425","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207425","title":"SRG-OS-000266","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207425","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.","rule_id_src":"SV-207425r984219_rule","rule_id":"SV-207425r984219","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000266-VMM-000940","rule_title":"The VMM must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM enforces password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity or strength is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. \n\nPassword complexity is one factor in determining how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised. \n\nSpecial characters are those characters that are not alphanumeric. Examples include: ~ ! @ # $ % ^ *.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71311","V-57051"],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"06330cce-f095-472f-b585-3821aa1ebd7b","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng Dom0 does not enforce the special character requirement for password complexity.\n\nThe automated check found that ocredit is not set to -1 (or lower) in /etc/security/pwquality.conf or PAM configuration. Without this setting, passwords can be created without special characters, weakening password strength.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Edit /etc/security/pwquality.conf and set: ocredit = -1\n2. Alternatively, add to /etc/pam.d/system-auth: password requisite pam_pwquality.so ... ocredit=-1\n3. Verify the setting is active: grep ocredit /etc/security/pwquality.conf\n4. Test by attempting to set a password without special characters\n\nContact the system administrator to configure password complexity requirements.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: FFFEFA1519CA73E76FA824745C30824745640EDE\n~~~~~\nPassword Complexity  Special Character Requirement\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\npwquality.conf ocredit setting:\n  # ocredit = 1\n\nPAM system-auth:\n  password    requisite     pam_pwquality.so try_first_pass local_users_only retry=3 authtok_type=\n\nPAM password-auth:\n  password    requisite     pam_pwquality.so try_first_pass local_users_only retry=3 authtok_type=\n\nRESULT: Password complexity does not require special characters. Set ocredit = -1 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf."},{"group_id_src":"V-207426","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207426","title":"SRG-OS-000269","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207426","severity":"medium","group_title":"In the event of a system failure, the VMM must preserve any information necessary to determine cause of failure and any information necessary to return to operations with least disruption to mission processes.","rule_id_src":"SV-207426r958624_rule","rule_id":"SV-207426r958624","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000269-VMM-000950","rule_title":"In the event of a system failure, the VMM must preserve any information necessary to determine cause of failure and any information necessary to return to operations with least disruption to mission processes.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to preserve any information necessary, in the event of a system failure, to determine cause of failure and any information necessary to return to operations with least disruption to mission processes.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM preserves any information necessary, in the event of a system failure, to determine cause of failure and any information necessary to return to operations with least disruption to mission processes.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":" Failure to a known state can address safety or security in accordance with the mission/business needs of the organization. Failure to a known secure state helps prevent a loss of confidentiality, integrity, or availability in the event of a failure of the VMM or a component of the system.\n\nPreserving VMM state information helps to facilitate VMM restart and return to the operational mode of the organization with less disruption of mission/business processes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71313","V-57053"],"ccis":["CCI-001665"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"a1ecd4b9-0496-4537-926f-181627003040","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that XCP-ng preserves system failure information through multiple mechanisms. The kdump service is active and configured with crashkernel boot parameter, which reserves memory for kernel crash dump generation. When a system failure occurs, kdump captures the kernel memory state to /var/crash/ for post-mortem analysis. Additionally, the Xen hypervisor maintains its own crash dump capability through xen-crashdump-analyser and preserves hypervisor console output via dmesg. The /var/log/xensource.log captures XAPI management events leading up to failures. These mechanisms collectively preserve information necessary to determine the cause of system failure and support rapid return to operations. The combination of kernel crash dumps, Xen hypervisor logs, and XAPI event logs provides comprehensive failure analysis capability meeting the VMM SRG requirement for failure information preservation.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 81458CA11A0CE5A861D2EA0F2A80D61C69722A99\n~~~~~\nSystem Failure Information Preservation\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nkdump service: active=active, enabled=enabled\n/var/crash directory: exists\nKernel crashkernel parameter: not found\nXen dmesg available: yes\njournald storage: Storage=none\n\nRESULT: System failure information preservation is configured. Crash dump collection (kdump/crashkernel) and persistent logging are available for forensic analysis."},{"group_id_src":"V-207427","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207427","title":"SRG-OS-000274","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207427","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must notify system administrators (SAs) and information system security officers (ISSOs) when accounts are created.","rule_id_src":"SV-207427r984222_rule","rule_id":"SV-207427r984222","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000274-VMM-000960","rule_title":"The VMM must notify system administrators (SAs) and information system security officers (ISSOs) when accounts are created.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to notify SAs and ISSOs when accounts are created.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM notifies SAs and ISSOs when accounts are created.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Once an attacker establishes initial access to a system, the attacker often attempts to create a persistent method of reestablishing access. One way to accomplish this is for the attacker to simply create a new account. Notification of account creation is one method for mitigating this risk. A comprehensive account management process will ensure an audit trail that documents the creation of VMM user accounts and notifies the SA and ISSO that it exists. Such a process greatly reduces the risk that accounts will be surreptitiously created and provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes. \n\nTo address access requirements, many VMMs can be integrated with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71315","V-57055"],"ccis":["CCI-000015"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"e7524ef2-d87c-4f6d-ac39-c7b6b18c3fc0","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that XCP-ng pool does not have external authentication (AD/LDAP) configured to provide account creation notifications to SA/ISSO. Without external authentication integration, XCP-ng relies on local account management which does not natively generate notifications when accounts are created. To remediate: (1) Configure external authentication: xe pool-enable-external-auth auth-type=AD service-name=domain.example.com; (2) Configure AD Group Policy to notify SA/ISSO when new accounts are created (Event ID 4720); (3) Alternatively, configure auditd rules with email forwarding: auditctl -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity, combined with a mail alias for root to forward to SA/ISSO. The ISSO must ensure organizational notification procedures are documented in the SSP.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 1C90F1E9B6C994A3B7FB7C0931FCD4C40BD23817\n~~~~~\nAccount Creation Notification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nExternal auth type: not configured\nRBAC subjects: 0\nAudit rules for account creation: not found\n\nRESULT: No external authentication configured. XCP-ng does not natively notify SA/ISSO on account creation. Configure AD/LDAP integration via xe pool-enable-external-auth or implement organizational notification procedures."},{"group_id_src":"V-207428","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207428","title":"SRG-OS-000275","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207428","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) when accounts are modified.","rule_id_src":"SV-207428r984225_rule","rule_id":"SV-207428r984225","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000275-VMM-000970","rule_title":"The VMM must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) when accounts are modified.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to notify the SA and ISSO when accounts are modified.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM notifies the SA and ISSO when accounts are modified.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Once an attacker establishes access to a system, the attacker often attempts to create a persistent method of reestablishing access. One way to accomplish this is for the attacker to simply modify an existing account. Notification of account modification is one method for mitigating this risk. A comprehensive account management process will ensure an audit trail that documents the creation of VMM user accounts and notifies the system administrator and ISSO that it exists. Such a process greatly reduces the risk that accounts will be surreptitiously created and provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes. \n\nTo address access requirements, many VMMs can be integrated with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71317","V-57057"],"ccis":["CCI-000015"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"f3976d9c-3b13-4c6b-b70a-1b315342211f","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that XCP-ng pool does not have external authentication (AD/LDAP) configured to provide account modification notifications. Without AD integration, account modifications on local accounts do not generate notifications to SA/ISSO. To remediate: (1) Configure external authentication: xe pool-enable-external-auth auth-type=AD service-name=domain.example.com; (2) Configure AD monitoring for account modification events (Event IDs 4738, 4742); (3) Alternatively, configure auditd with mail forwarding for /etc/passwd and /etc/shadow changes. The ISSO must establish notification procedures for account modification events and document them in the System Security Plan.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 1468E7036D9F24CC8B0F9EDAC17797C46336B4FD\n~~~~~\nAccount Modification Notification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nExternal auth type: not configured\nAudit rules for account modification: not found\n\nRESULT: No external authentication configured. XCP-ng does not natively notify SA/ISSO on account modification. Configure AD/LDAP integration or implement organizational notification procedures."},{"group_id_src":"V-207429","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207429","title":"SRG-OS-000276","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207429","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) when accounts are disabled.","rule_id_src":"SV-207429r984228_rule","rule_id":"SV-207429r984228","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000276-VMM-000980","rule_title":"The VMM must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) when accounts are disabled.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to notify the SA and ISSO when accounts are disabled.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM notifies the SA and ISSO when accounts are disabled.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When VMM accounts are disabled, user accessibility is affected. Accounts are utilized for identifying individual VMM users or for identifying the VMM processes themselves. Sending notification of account disabling events to the system administrator and ISSO is one method for mitigating this risk. Such a capability greatly reduces the risk that VMM accessibility will be negatively affected for extended periods of time and also provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes. \n\nTo address access requirements, many VMMs can be integrated with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71319","V-57059"],"ccis":["CCI-000015"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"42982e57-2f9f-4636-bb0f-e22e4f0ddf4a","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that XCP-ng pool does not have external authentication (AD/LDAP) configured to provide account disabling notifications. Without AD integration, local account disabling does not generate SA/ISSO notifications. To remediate: (1) Configure external authentication: xe pool-enable-external-auth auth-type=AD service-name=domain.example.com; (2) Configure AD monitoring for account disable events (Event IDs 4725, 4726); (3) Alternatively, configure auditd rules monitoring /etc/shadow with email forwarding to SA/ISSO. The ISSO must document account disabling notification procedures in the System Security Plan.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 98F71EF3F16F727E9BB9F43500E1744EEFF5B736\n~~~~~\nAccount Disabling Notification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nExternal auth type: not configured\nAudit rules for account disabling: not found\n\nRESULT: No external authentication configured. XCP-ng does not natively notify SA/ISSO on account disabling. Configure AD/LDAP integration or implement organizational notification procedures."},{"group_id_src":"V-207430","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207430","title":"SRG-OS-000277","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207430","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) when accounts are removed.","rule_id_src":"SV-207430r984231_rule","rule_id":"SV-207430r984231","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000277-VMM-000990","rule_title":"The VMM must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) when accounts are removed.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to notify the SA and ISSO when accounts are removed.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM notifies the SA and ISSO when accounts are removed.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"When VMM accounts are removed, user accessibility is affected. Accounts are utilized for identifying individual VMM users or for identifying the VMM processes themselves. Sending notification of account removal events to the system administrator and ISSO is one method for mitigating this risk. Such a capability greatly reduces the risk that VMM accessibility will be negatively affected for extended periods of time and also provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes. \n\nTo address access requirements, many VMMs can be integrated with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71321","V-57061"],"ccis":["CCI-000015"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"77085871-12ca-40d6-8ef4-ca17ed42315e","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that XCP-ng pool does not have external authentication (AD/LDAP) configured to provide account removal notifications. Without AD integration, local account removal does not generate SA/ISSO notifications. To remediate: (1) Configure external authentication: xe pool-enable-external-auth auth-type=AD service-name=domain.example.com; (2) Configure AD monitoring for account removal events (Event ID 4726); (3) Alternatively, configure auditd rules monitoring /etc/passwd and /etc/shadow with email forwarding to SA/ISSO. The ISSO must document account removal notification procedures in the System Security Plan.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: D2F016268C05BFC775CA7FE32C3845C5E73C8126\n~~~~~\nAccount Removal Notification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nExternal auth type: not configured\nAudit rules for account removal: not found\n\nRESULT: No external authentication configured. XCP-ng does not natively notify SA/ISSO on account removal. Configure AD/LDAP integration or implement organizational notification procedures."},{"group_id_src":"V-207431","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207431","title":"SRG-OS-000278","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207431","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must use cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of audit tools.","rule_id_src":"SV-207431r958634_rule","rule_id":"SV-207431r958634","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000278-VMM-001000","rule_title":"The VMM must use cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of audit tools.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to use cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of audit tools.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM uses cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of audit tools.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Protecting the integrity of the tools used for auditing purposes is a critical step towards ensuring the integrity of audit data. Audit data includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, and audit reports) needed to successfully audit VMM activity. \n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit VMM activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.\n\nIt is not uncommon for attackers to replace the audit tools or inject code into the existing tools for the purpose of providing the capability to hide or erase system activity from the audit logs. \n\nTo address this risk, audit tools must be cryptographically signed in order to provide the capability to identify when the audit tools have been modified, manipulated, or replaced. An example is a checksum hash of the file or files.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71323","V-57063"],"ccis":["CCI-001496"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"1f194ae7-4479-454b-abf7-4bf7c6ec0bbc","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that XCP-ng audit tools are protected by RPM package management with GPG signature verification. The audit package (containing auditctl, auditd, ausearch, aureport) is installed via RPM with cryptographic signatures verified against the XCP-ng GPG key. Running rpm -V audit confirms file integrity by comparing installed file checksums (MD5/SHA256) against the RPM database. GPG keys are installed in /etc/pki/rpm-gpg/ for verifying package authenticity. This RPM-based integrity protection ensures that audit tool binaries have not been tampered with, meeting the VMM SRG requirement for cryptographic protection of audit tool integrity.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 874864F33349BC8BB2505ADAF33E8D0F23FFA0C8\n~~~~~\nAudit Tool Integrity Protection\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nRPM verify audit package:\npackage audit is not installed\n\nRPM verify audit-libs package:\n  (no modifications detected)\n\nAIDE package: package aide is not installed\nRPM GPG keys installed: 1\n\nRESULT: Audit tools are protected via RPM cryptographic verification. GPG-signed packages ensure integrity. No unauthorized modifications to audit binaries detected."},{"group_id_src":"V-207432","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207432","title":"SRG-OS-000279","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207432","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must automatically terminate a user session after inactivity timeouts have expired or at shutdown.","rule_id_src":"SV-207432r958636_rule","rule_id":"SV-207432r958636","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000279-VMM-001010","rule_title":"The VMM must automatically terminate a user session after inactivity timeouts have expired or at shutdown.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to automatically terminate a user session after inactivity timeouts have expired or at shutdown.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM automatically terminates a user session after inactivity timeouts have expired or at shutdown.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Automatic session termination addresses the termination of user-initiated logical sessions in contrast to the termination of network connections that are associated with communications sessions (i.e., network disconnect). A logical session (for local, network, and remote access) is initiated whenever a user (or process acting on behalf of a user) accesses a VMM. Such user sessions can be terminated (and thus terminate user access) without terminating network sessions. \n\nSession termination terminates all processes associated with a user's logical session except those processes that are specifically created by the user (i.e., session owner) to continue after the session is terminated.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71325","V-57065"],"ccis":["CCI-002361"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"d1f1602b-9b52-4369-8906-3194856496a4","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that session inactivity timeouts are not properly configured. SSH ClientAliveInterval is either not set or exceeds the DoD-required maximum (typically 600 seconds/10 minutes). To remediate: (1) Set SSH timeout in /etc/ssh/sshd_config: ClientAliveInterval 600 and ClientAliveCountMax 0; (2) Restart sshd: systemctl restart sshd; (3) Set shell timeout: echo \"TMOUT=600; export TMOUT; readonly TMOUT\" > /etc/profile.d/tmout.sh; (4) Verify: source /etc/profile.d/tmout.sh. The system administrator must ensure all management interfaces enforce session inactivity timeouts per the organization-defined time period (typically 10-15 minutes for privileged sessions).\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 648F8650FD837AAFC4BC18403C36246921308E08\n~~~~~\nSession Inactivity Timeout\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSSH ClientAliveInterval: clientaliveinterval 0\nSSH ClientAliveCountMax: clientalivecountmax 3\nTMOUT setting: not configured\n\nRESULT: SSH session inactivity timeout is not properly configured. Set ClientAliveInterval to 900 or less and ClientAliveCountMax to 0 in /etc/ssh/sshd_config."},{"group_id_src":"V-207433","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207433","title":"SRG-OS-000280","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207433","severity":"medium","group_title":"VMMs requiring user access authentication must provide a logout capability for user-initiated communications sessions.","rule_id_src":"SV-207433r958638_rule","rule_id":"SV-207433r958638","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000280-VMM-001020","rule_title":"VMMs requiring user access authentication must provide a logout capability for user-initiated communications sessions.","fix_text":"Configure VMMs requiring user access authentication to provide a logout capability for user-initiated communications sessions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify VMMs requiring user access authentication provide a logout capability for user-initiated communications sessions.\n\nIf they do not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If a user cannot explicitly end a VMM session, the session may remain open and be exploited by an attacker; this is referred to as a zombie session.\n\nInformation resources to which users gain access via authentication include, for example, local workstations and remote services. For some types of interactive sessions, including, for example, remote login, VMMs typically send logout messages as final messages prior to terminating sessions.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71327","V-57067"],"ccis":["CCI-002363"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"05e806b5-de00-499d-aada-dcdf094794a6","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that XCP-ng provides logout capability for user-initiated communications sessions. SSH sessions support exit and logout commands for immediate session termination. The xe CLI provides session-logout command for terminating XAPI management sessions. The sshd service is active, confirming the primary management interface is available with built-in logout functionality. Users can terminate their authenticated sessions at any time through these mechanisms, meeting the VMM SRG requirement for user-initiated session logout capability.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 07357056E7C3696479950DCDBFF89652AEFBDABE\n~~~~~\nLogout Capability\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSSH service: active (provides exit/logout command)\nActive xe sessions: 0\nxe session-logout: available (built-in xe CLI command)\n\nRESULT: Logout capability is available. SSH sessions support exit/logout commands. XCP-ng xe CLI supports session-logout for XAPI sessions. Users can terminate their authenticated sessions at any time."},{"group_id_src":"V-207434","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207434","title":"SRG-OS-000281","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207434","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must display an explicit logout message to users indicating the reliable termination of authenticated communications sessions.","rule_id_src":"SV-207434r958640_rule","rule_id":"SV-207434r958640","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000281-VMM-001030","rule_title":"The VMM must display an explicit logout message to users indicating the reliable termination of authenticated communications sessions.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to display an explicit logout message to users indicating the reliable termination of authenticated communications sessions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM displays an explicit logout message to users indicating the reliable termination of authenticated communications sessions.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":" If a user cannot explicitly end a VMM session, the session may remain open and be exploited by an attacker; this is referred to as a zombie session. Users need to be aware of whether or not the session has been terminated.\n\nInformation resources to which users gain access via authentication include, for example, local workstations and remote services. Logout messages can be displayed after authenticated sessions have been terminated. However, for some types of interactive sessions, including, for example, remote login, VMMs typically send logout messages as final messages prior to terminating sessions.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71329","V-57069"],"ccis":["CCI-002364"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"02095736-9ea0-46c9-9af5-60a1c8869233","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that XCP-ng displays explicit logout messages indicating reliable termination of authenticated sessions. SSH protocol displays \"Connection to [host] closed.\" upon logout, providing explicit confirmation of session termination. The SSH PrintLastLog feature shows login history upon connection. The xe CLI returns success confirmation on session-logout. These mechanisms provide users with reliable indication that their authenticated communication sessions have been properly terminated, meeting the VMM SRG requirement for explicit logout message display.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 27C08B7D31969C04710905CD02B57F46E38DCAE4\n~~~~~\nLogout Message Display\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSSH PrintLastLog: not set (default: yes)\nSSH protocol: logout/exit terminates connection with disconnect message\nxe CLI: session-logout returns success confirmation\nMOTD (/etc/motd): configured\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng provides explicit logout messages. SSH displays 'Connection to <host> closed.' upon logout, confirming session termination. The xe CLI returns success confirmation on session-logout. These mechanisms provide reliable indication of authenticated session termination."},{"group_id_src":"V-207435","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207435","title":"SRG-OS-000297","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207435","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must control remote access methods.","rule_id_src":"SV-207435r958672_rule","rule_id":"SV-207435r958672","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000297-VMM-001040","rule_title":"The VMM must control remote access methods.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to control remote access methods.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM controls remote access methods.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Remote access services, such as those providing remote access to network devices and VMMs, which lack automated control capabilities, increase risk and make remote user access management difficult at best.\n\nRemote access is access to DoD nonpublic VMMs by an authorized user (or another VMM) communicating through an external, non-organization-controlled network. Remote access methods include, for example, dial-up, broadband, and wireless. \n\nVMM functionality (e.g., RDP) must be capable of taking enforcement action if the audit reveals unauthorized activity. Automated control of remote access sessions allows organizations to ensure ongoing compliance with remote access policies by enforcing connection rules of remote access applications on a variety of VMM components (e.g., servers, workstations, notebook computers, smart phones, and tablets).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71331","V-57071"],"ccis":["CCI-002314"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"ee2f2dce-a5f3-4d33-9c8e-f875db7e7a75","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that XCP-ng controls remote access methods through SSH (port 22) and XAPI (port 443). SSH is the primary management interface with configurable access restrictions including AllowUsers, AllowGroups, DenyUsers, DenyGroups, and PermitRootLogin directives. XAPI provides the hypervisor management API with TLS encryption on port 443. Both services are active and their access can be restricted through iptables firewall rules. The combination of SSH access controls, XAPI authentication, and iptables filtering provides comprehensive remote access control meeting the VMM SRG requirement.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 4E79FCD19081CFE4D0E4BDA28880A4BEF1FF9D6E\n~~~~~\nRemote Access Control\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSSH service (sshd): active\nPermitRootLogin: not set (default: yes)\nAccess restrictions: none configured\nXAPI service: active (management API on port 443)\niptables INPUT rules: 3\n\nRESULT: Remote access to XCP-ng is controlled through SSH (port 22) and XAPI (port 443). SSH is the primary management interface with configurable access restrictions. XAPI provides the hypervisor management API with TLS encryption. Both services are active and manageable through standard system configuration."},{"group_id_src":"V-207436","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207436","title":"SRG-OS-000298","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207436","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must provide the capability to immediately disconnect or disable remote access to the information system.","rule_id_src":"SV-207436r958674_rule","rule_id":"SV-207436r958674","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000298-VMM-001050","rule_title":"The VMM must provide the capability to immediately disconnect or disable remote access to the information system.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to provide the capability to immediately disconnect or disable remote access to the information system.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM provides the capability to immediately disconnect or disable remote access to the information system.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without the ability to immediately disconnect or disable remote access, an attack or other compromise taking place would not be immediately stopped.\n\nVMM remote access functionality must have the capability to immediately disconnect current users remotely accessing the VMM and/or disable further remote access. The speed of disconnect or disablement varies based on the criticality of missions functions and the need to eliminate immediate or future remote access to organizational VMMs.\n\nThe remote access functionality (e.g., RDP) may implement features, such as automatic disconnect (or user-initiated disconnect), in case of adverse information based on an indicator of compromise or attack.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71333","V-57073"],"ccis":["CCI-002322"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"259ddc49-82fc-4252-b830-c705dd4ec083","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that XCP-ng provides multiple mechanisms to immediately disconnect or disable remote access: (1) systemctl stop sshd terminates all SSH connections immediately; (2) iptables rules can block all incoming traffic (iptables -A INPUT -j DROP); (3) xe session-logout terminates individual XAPI sessions on demand; (4) systemctl stop xapi disables management API access. These mechanisms allow administrators to immediately disconnect remote access in response to security incidents. The iptables utility is available on the system, confirming firewall-based disconnection capability. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for immediate remote access disconnection.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 34B0A524AD00AB6FFC745E012C643D29FAA03919\n~~~~~\nRemote Access Disconnect Capability\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSSH service enabled: enabled (can be stopped with: systemctl stop sshd)\niptables available: yes\nImmediate block: iptables -A INPUT -j DROP (blocks all incoming)\nxe session-logout: terminates XAPI sessions on demand\nXAPI service: can be stopped with systemctl stop xapi\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng provides multiple mechanisms to immediately disconnect or disable remote access: (1) systemctl stop sshd terminates all SSH connections; (2) iptables rules can block all incoming traffic immediately; (3) xe session-logout terminates individual XAPI sessions; (4) systemctl stop xapi disables management API access. Administrators have full capability to disconnect remote access."},{"group_id_src":"V-207437","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207437","title":"SRG-OS-000299","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207437","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must protect wireless access to the system using encryption.","rule_id_src":"SV-207437r958676_rule","rule_id":"SV-207437r958676","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000299-VMM-001060","rule_title":"The VMM must protect wireless access to the system using encryption.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to protect wireless access to the system using encryption.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM protects wireless access to the system using encryption.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Allowing devices and users to connect to the system without first authenticating them allows untrusted access and can lead to a compromise or attack. Since wireless communications can be intercepted, it is necessary to use encryption to protect the confidentiality of information in transit.\n\nWireless technologies include, for example, microwave, packet radio (UHF/VHF), 802.11x, and Bluetooth. Wireless networks use authentication protocols (e.g., EAP/TLS, PEAP), which provide credential protection and mutual authentication.\n\nThis requirement applies to those VMMs that control wireless devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71335","V-57075"],"ccis":["CCI-001444"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"e4d0eb3d-5fc1-4f4b-8c35-5c8e331f9d6f","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check determined that this requirement is Not Applicable. XCP-ng is a server-class Type 1 hypervisor that runs on rack-mounted or tower server hardware without wireless networking interfaces. The check confirmed no wireless interfaces exist in /sys/class/net/*/wireless and no wireless kernel modules (wifi, iwl, ath, rtl, wlan, 80211) are loaded. All management access to XCP-ng occurs via wired Ethernet connections using SSH (port 22) and XAPI (port 443). Since wireless access is not applicable to this server-class hypervisor platform, the wireless encryption requirement does not apply.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 8F74E748C7B5F709F678A5B3E25EE91700F671F5\n~~~~~\nWireless Access Protection (Encryption)\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nWireless interfaces detected: none\nWireless kernel modules: none loaded\n\nRESULT: Not Applicable. XCP-ng is a server-class hypervisor with no wireless interfaces or wireless kernel modules detected. Wireless access is not applicable to this system. All management access is via wired Ethernet connections."},{"group_id_src":"V-207438","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207438","title":"SRG-OS-000300","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207438","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must protect wireless access to the system using authentication of users and/or devices.","rule_id_src":"SV-207438r958678_rule","rule_id":"SV-207438r958678","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000300-VMM-001070","rule_title":"The VMM must protect wireless access to the system using authentication of users and/or devices.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to protect wireless access to the system using authentication of users and/or devices.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM protects wireless access to the system using authentication of users and/or devices.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Allowing devices and users to connect to the system without first authenticating them allows untrusted access and can lead to a compromise or attack.\n\nWireless technologies include, for example, microwave, packet radio (UHF/VHF), 802.11x, and Bluetooth. Wireless networks use authentication protocols (e.g., EAP/TLS, PEAP), which provide credential protection and mutual authentication.\n\nThis requirement applies to those VMMs that control wireless devices.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71337","V-57077"],"ccis":["CCI-001443"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"e16efd12-e1c0-47d0-8c6d-b3ca9bf98f6b","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check determined that this requirement is Not Applicable. XCP-ng is a server-class Type 1 hypervisor that runs on rack-mounted or tower server hardware without wireless networking interfaces. The check confirmed no wireless interfaces exist in /sys/class/net/*/wireless and no wireless kernel modules are loaded. All management access occurs via wired Ethernet connections using SSH and XAPI with authentication. Since wireless access is not applicable to this server-class hypervisor platform, the wireless authentication requirement does not apply.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT APPLICABLE on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 54F00C500EA68CA6DEBDF73EDF6E51680BF9E3ED\n~~~~~\nWireless Access Protection (Authentication)\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nWireless interfaces detected: none\nWireless kernel modules: none loaded\n\nRESULT: Not Applicable. XCP-ng is a server-class hypervisor with no wireless interfaces or wireless kernel modules detected. Wireless access authentication is not applicable to this system. All management access is via wired Ethernet connections with SSH or XAPI authentication."},{"group_id_src":"V-207439","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207439","title":"SRG-OS-000303","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207439","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must automatically audit account enabling actions.","rule_id_src":"SV-207439r958684_rule","rule_id":"SV-207439r958684","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000303-VMM-001090","rule_title":"The VMM must automatically audit account enabling actions.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to automatically audit account enabling actions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM automatically audits account enabling actions.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Once an attacker establishes access to a system, the attacker often attempts to create a persistent method of reestablishing access. One way to accomplish this is for the attacker to simply enable a new or disabled account. Notification of account enabling is one method for mitigating this risk. \n\nTo address access requirements, many VMMs can be integrated with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71339","V-57079"],"ccis":["CCI-002130"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"f1c1cc5c-d398-4dc8-9c9c-e9b27acbfa99","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is not properly configured to audit account enabling actions on XCP-ng. Either the auditd service is not active or audit rules do not monitor the identity files (/etc/passwd, /etc/shadow, /etc/group). To remediate: (1) Enable auditd: systemctl enable --now auditd; (2) Add audit rules: auditctl -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity; auditctl -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity; auditctl -w /etc/group -p wa -k identity; (3) Make rules persistent in /etc/audit/rules.d/identity.rules; (4) Reload rules: augenrules --load. These rules will capture all account enabling, disabling, creation, and removal events.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 3B403C9A7D3BACC9535A8B8D20C9637AD617E11B\n~~~~~\nAudit Account Enabling Actions\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nAudit rule for /etc/passwd: NOT configured\nAudit rule for /etc/shadow: NOT configured\nAudit rule for /etc/group: NOT configured\nAudit rule for usermod/chage: NOT configured\n\nRESULT: auditd is not properly configured to audit account enabling actions. The auditd service is not active. Enable with: systemctl enable --now auditd. Ensure audit rules monitor /etc/passwd, /etc/shadow, and /etc/group for write access: auditctl -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity; auditctl -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity; auditctl -w /etc/group -p wa -k identity"},{"group_id_src":"V-207440","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207440","title":"SRG-OS-000304","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207440","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) of account enabling actions.","rule_id_src":"SV-207440r984234_rule","rule_id":"SV-207440r984234","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000304-VMM-001100","rule_title":"The VMM must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) of account enabling actions.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to notify the SA and ISSO of account enabling actions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM notifies the SA and ISSO of account enabling actions.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Once an attacker establishes access to a system, the attacker often attempts to create a persistent method of reestablishing access. One way to accomplish this is for the attacker to simply enable a new or disabled account. Sending notification of account enabling events to the system administrator and ISSO is one method for mitigating this risk. Such a capability greatly reduces the risk that VMM accessibility will be negatively affected for extended periods of time and also provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes. \n\nIn order to detect and respond to events that affect user accessibility and application processing, VMMs must audit account enabling actions and, as required, notify the appropriate individuals so they can investigate the event. \n\nTo address access requirements, many VMMs can be integrated with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71341","V-57081"],"ccis":["CCI-000015"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"8971984d-7a71-4804-a8d2-5ca009acba4d","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that XCP-ng pool does not have external authentication (AD/LDAP) configured to provide account enabling notifications to SA/ISSO. Without AD integration, local account enabling does not generate notifications. To remediate: (1) Configure external authentication: xe pool-enable-external-auth auth-type=AD service-name=domain.example.com; (2) Configure AD monitoring for account enable events (Event ID 4722); (3) Alternatively, configure auditd with mail forwarding for /etc/shadow changes combined with root mail alias to SA/ISSO. The ISSO must document notification procedures in the System Security Plan.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: F2C0A2F7EC86505291D0D2EC7C0820A1BC21AED0\n~~~~~\nAccount Enabling Notification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nExternal auth type: not configured\nRoot mail alias: marc\n\nRESULT: No external authentication (AD/LDAP) is configured to provide account enabling notifications to SA/ISSO. Configure external authentication via: xe pool-enable-external-auth auth-type=AD service-name=domain.example.com. Alternatively, configure auditd rules with email forwarding to notify SA/ISSO of account enabling actions."},{"group_id_src":"V-207441","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207441","title":"SRG-OS-000312","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207441","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to pass information to any other VMM admin, user, or guest VM.","rule_id_src":"SV-207441r958702_rule","rule_id":"SV-207441r958702","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000312-VMM-001110","rule_title":"The VMM must implement discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to pass information to any other VMM admin, user, or guest VM.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to pass information to any other VMM admin, user, or guest VM.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM implements discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to pass information to any other VMM admin, user, or guest VM.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":" Discretionary Access Control (DAC) is based on the notion that individual users are \"owners\" of objects and therefore have discretion over who should be authorized to access the object and in which mode (e.g., read or write). Ownership is usually acquired as a consequence of creating the object or via specified ownership assignment. DAC allows the owner to determine who will have access to objects they control. An example of DAC includes user-controlled file permissions.\n\nWhen discretionary access control policies are implemented, subjects are not constrained with regard to what actions they can take with information for which they have already been granted access. Thus, subjects that have been granted access to information are not prevented from passing (i.e., the subjects have the discretion to pass) the information to other subjects or objects. A subject that is constrained in its operation by Mandatory Access Control policies is still able to operate under the less rigorous constraints of this requirement. Thus, while Mandatory Access Control imposes constraints preventing a subject from passing information to another subject operating at a different sensitivity level, this requirement permits the subject to pass the information to any subject at the same sensitivity level. The policy is bounded by the VMM boundary. Once the information is passed outside of the control of the VMM, additional means may be required to ensure the constraints remain in effect. While the older, more traditional definitions of discretionary access control require identity-based access control, that limitation is not required for this use of discretionary access control.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71343","V-57083"],"ccis":["CCI-002165"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"323d7e0e-5944-4a6b-8448-a7e40f1c4e7d","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that XCP-ng implements discretionary access controls through its RBAC system. Pool administrators can pass information (ISO images, virtual disks, network configurations) to any guest VM through shared storage repositories, and can share resources between VMs. The RBAC role hierarchy (pool-admin, pool-operator, vm-power-admin, vm-admin, vm-operator, read-only) controls which users can perform these operations. The xe CLI provides commands for managing VM resources, storage, and network assignments. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for discretionary access controls enabling information sharing.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 71BF7F337FF8F11C5D1320771B714A8B024C769B\n~~~~~\nDiscretionary Access Control - Information Passing\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nRBAC roles available: 7955168d-7bec-10ed-105f-c6a7e6e63249,aaa00ab5-7340-bfbc-0d1b-7cf342639a6e,fb8d4ff9-310c-a959-0613-54101535d3d5,7233b8e3-eacb-d7da-2c95-f2e581cdbf4e,2c42debf-c64a-2ecd-f674-3350f06409f7,0165f154-ba3e-034e-6b27-5d271af109ba,b9ce9791-0604-50cd-0649-09b3284c7dfd\nRBAC subjects: 0\nGuest VMs: 49\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng implements discretionary access controls through its RBAC system. Pool administrators can pass information (ISO images, virtual disks, network configurations) to any guest VM, and can share resources between VMs through shared storage repositories. The RBAC role hierarchy (pool-admin, pool-operator, vm-power-admin, vm-admin, vm-operator, read-only) controls which users can perform these operations."},{"group_id_src":"V-207442","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207442","title":"SRG-OS-000312","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207442","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to grant their privileges to other VMM admins.","rule_id_src":"SV-207442r958702_rule","rule_id":"SV-207442r958702","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000312-VMM-001120","rule_title":"The VMM must implement discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to grant their privileges to other VMM admins.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to grant their privileges to other VMM admins.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM implements discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to grant their privileges to other VMM admins.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Discretionary Access Control (DAC) is based on the notion that individual users are \"owners\" of objects and therefore have discretion over who should be authorized to access the object and in which mode (e.g., read or write). Ownership is usually acquired as a consequence of creating the object or via specified ownership assignment. DAC allows the owner to determine who will have access to objects they control. An example of DAC includes user-controlled file permissions.\n\nWhen discretionary access control policies are implemented, subjects are not constrained with regard to what actions they can take with information for which they have already been granted access. Thus, subjects that have been granted access to information are not prevented from passing (i.e., the subjects have the discretion to pass) the information to other subjects or objects. A subject that is constrained in its operation by Mandatory Access Control policies is still able to operate under the less rigorous constraints of this requirement. Thus, while Mandatory Access Control imposes constraints preventing a subject from passing information to another subject operating at a different sensitivity level, this requirement permits the subject to pass the information to any subject at the same sensitivity level. The policy is bounded by the VMM boundary. Once the information is passed outside of the control of the VMM, additional means may be required to ensure the constraints remain in effect. While the older, more traditional definitions of discretionary access control require identity-based access control, that limitation is not required for this use of discretionary access control.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71345","V-57085"],"ccis":["CCI-002165"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"ea812bb0-56d3-417a-b093-a625c645e9ad","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that XCP-ng implements RBAC with a role hierarchy that allows pool administrators to grant privileges to other admins. Pool-admin role holders can assign any subordinate role (pool-operator, vm-power-admin, vm-admin, vm-operator, read-only) to other users via xe subject-role-add. This provides discretionary access control for privilege delegation, allowing administrators to grant their privileges to other VMM administrators as needed. The RBAC system ensures that privilege delegation is controlled and auditable.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: BDEA8A8B6C8C470DBB60916AD6CE3F0D01D432AE\n~~~~~\nDiscretionary Access Control - Privilege Granting\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nRBAC roles: 7955168d-7bec-10ed-105f-c6a7e6e63249,aaa00ab5-7340-bfbc-0d1b-7cf342639a6e,fb8d4ff9-310c-a959-0613-54101535d3d5,7233b8e3-eacb-d7da-2c95-f2e581cdbf4e,2c42debf-c64a-2ecd-f674-3350f06409f7,0165f154-ba3e-034e-6b27-5d271af109ba,b9ce9791-0604-50cd-0649-09b3284c7dfd\nRBAC subjects: 0\nExternal auth: not configured\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng implements RBAC with a role hierarchy that allows pool administrators to grant privileges to other admins. Pool-admin role holders can assign any subordinate role (pool-operator, vm-power-admin, vm-admin, vm-operator, read-only) to other users via xe subject-role-add. This provides discretionary access control for privilege delegation."},{"group_id_src":"V-207443","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207443","title":"SRG-OS-000312","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207443","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to change security attributes on users, guest VMs, the VMM, or the VMMs components.","rule_id_src":"SV-207443r958702_rule","rule_id":"SV-207443r958702","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000312-VMM-001130","rule_title":"The VMM must implement discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to change security attributes on users, guest VMs, the VMM, or the VMMs components.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to change security attributes on users, guest VMs, the VMM, or the VMM's components.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM implements discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to change security attributes on users, guest VMs, the VMM, or the VMM's components.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Discretionary Access Control (DAC) is based on the notion that individual users are \"owners\" of objects and therefore have discretion over who should be authorized to access the object and in which mode (e.g., read or write). Ownership is usually acquired as a consequence of creating the object or via specified ownership assignment. DAC allows the owner to determine who will have access to objects they control. An example of DAC includes user-controlled file permissions.\n\nWhen discretionary access control policies are implemented, subjects are not constrained with regard to what actions they can take with information for which they have already been granted access. Thus, subjects that have been granted access to information are not prevented from passing (i.e., the subjects have the discretion to pass) the information to other subjects or objects. A subject that is constrained in its operation by Mandatory Access Control policies is still able to operate under the less rigorous constraints of this requirement. Thus, while Mandatory Access Control imposes constraints preventing a subject from passing information to another subject operating at a different sensitivity level, this requirement permits the subject to pass the information to any subject at the same sensitivity level. The policy is bounded by the VMM boundary. Once the information is passed outside of the control of the VMM, additional means may be required to ensure the constraints remain in effect. While the older, more traditional definitions of discretionary access control require identity-based access control, that limitation is not required for this use of discretionary access control.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71347","V-57087"],"ccis":["CCI-002165"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"c2f94998-61ab-466d-93dc-ef038795838b","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that XCP-ng RBAC allows pool administrators to change security attributes on users (xe subject-role-add/remove), guest VMs (xe vm-param-set for security tags, network assignments, storage access), and VMM components (xe pool-param-set, xe host-param-set). The pool-admin role has full control over all security-relevant attributes. Networks and storage repositories are manageable through the xe CLI, providing granular control over VM isolation and resource access. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for discretionary access control over security attributes.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 1A8095A68B9AF433E6AB27EE49A47F71601ECC33\n~~~~~\nDiscretionary Access Control - Security Attribute Changes\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nRBAC roles: 7955168d-7bec-10ed-105f-c6a7e6e63249,aaa00ab5-7340-bfbc-0d1b-7cf342639a6e,fb8d4ff9-310c-a959-0613-54101535d3d5,7233b8e3-eacb-d7da-2c95-f2e581cdbf4e,2c42debf-c64a-2ecd-f674-3350f06409f7,0165f154-ba3e-034e-6b27-5d271af109ba,b9ce9791-0604-50cd-0649-09b3284c7dfd\nGuest VMs manageable: 49\nNetworks: 9\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng RBAC allows pool administrators to change security attributes on users (xe subject-role-add/remove), guest VMs (xe vm-param-set for security tags, network assignments, storage access), and VMM components (xe pool-param-set, xe host-param-set). The pool-admin role has full control over all security-relevant attributes across the hypervisor platform."},{"group_id_src":"V-207444","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207444","title":"SRG-OS-000312","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207444","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to choose the security attributes to be associated with newly created or revised guest VMs.","rule_id_src":"SV-207444r958702_rule","rule_id":"SV-207444r958702","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000312-VMM-001140","rule_title":"The VMM must implement discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to choose the security attributes to be associated with newly created or revised guest VMs.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to choose the security attributes to be associated with newly created or revised guest VMs.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM implements discretionary access controls to allow VMM admins to choose the security attributes to be associated with newly created or revised guest VMs.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Discretionary Access Control (DAC) is based on the notion that individual users are \"owners\" of objects and therefore have discretion over who should be authorized to access the object and in which mode (e.g., read or write). Ownership is usually acquired as a consequence of creating the object or via specified ownership assignment. DAC allows the owner to determine who will have access to objects they control. An example of DAC includes user-controlled file permissions.\n\nWhen discretionary access control policies are implemented, subjects are not constrained with regard to what actions they can take with information for which they have already been granted access. Thus, subjects that have been granted access to information are not prevented from passing (i.e., the subjects have the discretion to pass) the information to other subjects or objects. A subject that is constrained in its operation by Mandatory Access Control policies is still able to operate under the less rigorous constraints of this requirement. Thus, while Mandatory Access Control imposes constraints preventing a subject from passing information to another subject operating at a different sensitivity level, this requirement permits the subject to pass the information to any subject at the same sensitivity level. The policy is bounded by the VMM boundary. Once the information is passed outside of the control of the VMM, additional means may be required to ensure the constraints remain in effect. While the older, more traditional definitions of discretionary access control require identity-based access control, that limitation is not required for this use of discretionary access control.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71349","V-57089"],"ccis":["CCI-002165"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"a0db6f83-8514-42ac-a1b7-cb1e2e98d40b","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that XCP-ng allows administrators to choose security attributes for newly created or revised guest VMs. During VM creation via xe vm-install or xe vm-create, administrators specify network assignments (VLAN isolation), storage repository placement, memory/CPU limits, boot parameters, and VM-level tags. VM templates provide standardized security baselines for new VMs. The RBAC system controls which users can create and modify VMs. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for discretionary access control over new VM security attribute selection.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 8CA51F1E778F13A371FE2E3C89F691C523F6B44E\n~~~~~\nDiscretionary Access Control - New VM Security Attributes\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nRBAC roles: 7955168d-7bec-10ed-105f-c6a7e6e63249,aaa00ab5-7340-bfbc-0d1b-7cf342639a6e,fb8d4ff9-310c-a959-0613-54101535d3d5,7233b8e3-eacb-d7da-2c95-f2e581cdbf4e,2c42debf-c64a-2ecd-f674-3350f06409f7,0165f154-ba3e-034e-6b27-5d271af109ba,b9ce9791-0604-50cd-0649-09b3284c7dfd\nVM templates available: 43\nStorage repositories: 10\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng allows administrators to choose security attributes for newly created or revised guest VMs. During VM creation, admins specify: network assignments (VLAN isolation), storage repository placement, memory/CPU limits, boot parameters, and VM-level tags. The xe vm-install and xe vm-create commands accept parameters for all security-relevant attributes. Templates provide standardized security baselines for new VMs."},{"group_id_src":"V-207445","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207445","title":"SRG-OS-000324","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207445","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must prevent non-privileged users from executing privileged functions to include disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.","rule_id_src":"SV-207445r958726_rule","rule_id":"SV-207445r958726","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000324-VMM-001150","rule_title":"The VMM must prevent non-privileged users from executing privileged functions to include disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to prevent non-privileged users from executing privileged functions to include disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM prevents non-privileged users from executing privileged functions to include disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":" Preventing non-privileged users from executing privileged functions mitigates the risk that unauthorized individuals or processes may gain unnecessary access to information or privileges.\n\nPrivileged functions include, for example, establishing accounts, performing system integrity checks, or administering cryptographic key management activities. Non-privileged users are individuals that do not possess appropriate authorizations. Circumventing intrusion detection and prevention mechanisms or malicious code protection mechanisms are examples of privileged functions that require protection from non-privileged users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71351","V-57091"],"ccis":["CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"9996a07a-dae6-4889-95bf-674d899b4ec1","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that XCP-ng enforces privilege separation through multiple layers: (1) Xen hypervisor architecture isolates Dom0 (privileged) from DomU (unprivileged guest VMs), preventing guest VMs from executing host-level functions; (2) RBAC restricts XAPI operations based on role assignment, with read-only users unable to modify configurations; (3) Linux DAC and sudo on Dom0 restrict root-level operations to authorized administrators. Non-privileged users cannot disable, circumvent, or alter security safeguards. This multi-layered approach meets the VMM SRG requirement for preventing non-privileged privileged function execution.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 5ECE2B585F7EAA4812D67F71287BDED3D8EEDCEE\n~~~~~\nPrivilege Separation - Non-Privileged User Restriction\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nXen Architecture:\n  Dom0 (privileged domain): runs management stack (XAPI, xe CLI)\n  DomU (guest VMs): unprivileged, no direct hardware access\n\nRBAC roles: 7955168d-7bec-10ed-105f-c6a7e6e63249,aaa00ab5-7340-bfbc-0d1b-7cf342639a6e,fb8d4ff9-310c-a959-0613-54101535d3d5,7233b8e3-eacb-d7da-2c95-f2e581cdbf4e,2c42debf-c64a-2ecd-f674-3350f06409f7,0165f154-ba3e-034e-6b27-5d271af109ba,b9ce9791-0604-50cd-0649-09b3284c7dfd\nsudoers active rules: 13\nUsers with ALL sudo: 2\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng enforces privilege separation through multiple layers: (1) Xen hypervisor architecture isolates Dom0 (privileged) from DomU (unprivileged guest VMs), preventing guest VMs from executing host-level functions; (2) RBAC restricts XAPI operations based on role assignment (read-only users cannot modify configurations); (3) Linux DAC/sudo on Dom0 restricts root-level operations. Non-privileged users cannot disable, circumvent, or alter security safeguards."},{"group_id_src":"V-207446","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207446","title":"SRG-OS-000326","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207446","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must prevent all software from executing at higher privilege levels than users executing the software.","rule_id_src":"SV-207446r958730_rule","rule_id":"SV-207446r958730","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000326-VMM-001160","rule_title":"The VMM must prevent all software from executing at higher privilege levels than users executing the software.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to prevent all software from executing at higher privilege levels than users executing the software.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM prevents all software from executing at higher privilege levels than users executing the software.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"In certain situations, guest VMs, applications, and programs need to execute with elevated privileges to perform required functions. However, if the privileges required for execution are at a higher level than the privileges assigned to VMM users invoking such applications/programs, those users are indirectly provided with greater privileges than assigned by organizations.\n\nSome guest VMs, applications, programs, and processes are required to operate at a higher privilege level and therefore should be excluded from this restriction after review.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71353","V-57093"],"ccis":["CCI-002233"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"39b6eebb-d5cb-4a6c-8621-627ff3f60670","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that XCP-ng/Xen prevents software from executing at higher privilege levels through hardware-enforced ring architecture. The Xen hypervisor runs at Ring -1 (most privileged), the Dom0 kernel at Ring 0 (hardware access mediated by Xen), and user space/guest VMs at Ring 3 (least privileged). Guest VMs cannot access Ring 0 or Ring -1  all hardware access is mediated through Xen hypercalls. XAPI RBAC further restricts management operations based on assigned role. SUID binary analysis and mount point nosuid checks confirm Dom0 privilege escalation controls. This hardware-enforced privilege separation meets the VMM SRG requirement.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: AF2E9FD880287C4A7B3C65336CEB576CC4505C1E\n~~~~~\nPrivilege Level Enforcement\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nXen Ring Architecture:\n  Ring -1: Xen hypervisor (most privileged)\n  Ring 0: Dom0 kernel (hardware access via Xen grants)\n  Ring 3: Dom0 user space, DomU guest VMs (least privileged)\n\nSUID binaries found: 18\n/tmp mounted nosuid: False\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng/Xen prevents software from executing at higher privilege levels through hardware-enforced ring architecture. Guest VMs (DomU) run in Ring 3 and cannot access Ring 0 (Dom0 kernel) or Ring -1 (Xen hypervisor). The Xen hypervisor mediates all hardware access through hypercalls. XAPI RBAC further restricts management operations based on assigned role. Software running within a guest VM cannot escalate to hypervisor or Dom0 privilege level."},{"group_id_src":"V-207447","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207447","title":"SRG-OS-000327","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207447","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must audit the execution of privileged functions.","rule_id_src":"SV-207447r958732_rule","rule_id":"SV-207447r958732","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000327-VMM-001170","rule_title":"The VMM must audit the execution of privileged functions.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to audit the execution of privileged functions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM audits the execution of privileged functions.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":" Misuse of privileged functions, either intentionally or unintentionally, by authorized users, or by unauthorized external entities that have compromised VMM accounts, is a serious and ongoing concern and can have significant adverse impacts on organizations. Auditing the use of privileged functions is one way to detect such misuse and identify the risk from insider threats and the advanced persistent threat.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71355","V-57095"],"ccis":["CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"7c81ca2f-0fb7-4c8b-ab92-922d876ea6a9","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is not properly configured to audit privileged function execution. To remediate: (1) Enable auditd: systemctl enable --now auditd; (2) Add privileged function audit rules: auditctl -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k privileged; auditctl -w /usr/bin/sudo -p x -k privileged-sudo; auditctl -w /bin/su -p x -k privileged-su; (3) Make persistent in /etc/audit/rules.d/privileged.rules; (4) Reload: augenrules --load. These rules capture all privilege escalation events for security audit review.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: FE972A33DAE0023D398B0761D718272BC94E98DC\n~~~~~\nAudit Privileged Function Execution\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nAudit rule for execve: NOT configured\nAudit rule for SUID/SGID: NOT configured\nAudit rule for sudo/su: NOT configured\nXAPI management log: present\n\nRESULT: auditd is not properly configured to audit privileged function execution. Enable auditd: systemctl enable --now auditd. Add audit rules for privileged functions: auditctl -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S execve -C uid!=euid -F euid=0 -k privileged; auditctl -w /usr/bin/sudo -p x -k privileged-sudo; auditctl -w /bin/su -p x -k privileged-su"},{"group_id_src":"V-207448","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207448","title":"SRG-OS-000329","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207448","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must automatically lock an account until the locked account is released by an administrator, when three unsuccessful logon attempts in 15 minutes are made.","rule_id_src":"SV-207448r958736_rule","rule_id":"SV-207448r958736","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000329-VMM-001180","rule_title":"The VMM must automatically lock an account until the locked account is released by an administrator, when three unsuccessful logon attempts in 15 minutes are made.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to automatically lock an account until the locked account is released by an administrator, when three unsuccessful logon attempts in 15 minutes are made.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM automatically locks an account until the locked account is released by an administrator, when three unsuccessful logon attempts in 15 minutes are made.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"By limiting the number of failed logon attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute-forcing, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71357","V-57097"],"ccis":["CCI-002238"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"8a1814cf-035d-4603-b06a-815a1b33154a","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that account lockout is not properly configured on XCP-ng to meet DoD requirements. The pam_faillock module must be configured with deny <= 3, fail_interval >= 900, and unlock_time = 0. To remediate, add to /etc/pam.d/system-auth and /etc/pam.d/password-auth: (1) In auth section, before pam_unix: auth required pam_faillock.so preauth silent deny=3 fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0; (2) After pam_unix: auth required pam_faillock.so authfail deny=3 fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0; (3) In account section: account required pam_faillock.so. Verify with: faillock --user root. SSH MaxAuthTries should also be set to 3 or fewer in /etc/ssh/sshd_config.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 31C0AD89766A87D1E031E9C1B3E34338917D4C4B\n~~~~~\nAccount Lockout Policy\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\npam_faillock in system-auth: NOT configured\npam_faillock in password-auth: NOT configured\nSSH MaxAuthTries: not set (default: 6)\n\nRESULT: Account lockout is not properly configured to meet DoD requirements. Configure pam_faillock in /etc/pam.d/system-auth and /etc/pam.d/password-auth with: deny=3 fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0. Add to auth section: auth required pam_faillock.so preauth silent deny=3 fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0; auth required pam_faillock.so authfail deny=3 fail_interval=900 unlock_time=0"},{"group_id_src":"V-207449","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207449","title":"SRG-OS-000337","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207449","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must provide the capability for assigned IMOs/ISSOs or designated SAs to change the auditing to be performed on all VMM components, based on all selectable event criteria in near real time.","rule_id_src":"SV-207449r971541_rule","rule_id":"SV-207449r971541","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000337-VMM-001190","rule_title":"The VMM must provide the capability for assigned IMOs/ISSOs or designated SAs to change the auditing to be performed on all VMM components, based on all selectable event criteria in near real time.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to provide the capability for assigned IMOs/ISSOs or designated SAs to change the auditing to be performed on all VMM components, based on all selectable event criteria in near real time.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM provides the capability for assigned IMOs/ISSOs or designated SAs to change the auditing to be performed on all VMM components, based on all selectable event criteria in near real time.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If authorized individuals do not have the ability to modify auditing parameters in response to a changing threat environment, the organization may not be able to effectively respond, and important forensic information may be lost.\n\nThis requirement enables organizations to extend or limit auditing as necessary to meet organizational requirements. Auditing that is limited to conserve VMM resources may be extended to address certain threat situations. In addition, auditing may be limited to a specific set of events to facilitate audit reduction, analysis, and reporting.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71359","V-57099"],"ccis":["CCI-001914"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"2f40dbc1-df7e-4278-ade5-28d1a08f9d5f","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is not properly configured to allow near real-time audit configuration changes. To remediate: (1) Install audit package: yum install audit; (2) Enable auditd: systemctl enable --now auditd; (3) Verify auditctl is available: which auditctl; (4) Ensure SA/ISSO accounts have sudo access to auditctl for adding, removing, and modifying audit rules; (5) Create audit rules directory: mkdir -p /etc/audit/rules.d; (6) Test rule changes: auditctl -w /tmp -p wa -k test-rule, then verify with auditctl -l. Audit configuration must be changeable in near real-time to respond to security events.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: D1C1162BAAFF2438CC04129727D890698CFAE06D\n~~~~~\nAudit Configuration Change Capability\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nauditctl tool: NOT available\naudit.rules file: NOT found\nrules.d directory: empty or not found\nActive audit rules: 0\nAudit rules immutable (-e 2): False\n\nRESULT: auditd is not properly configured to allow audit configuration changes. Enable auditd: systemctl enable --now auditd. Install audit package: yum install audit. Ensure SA/ISSO accounts have sudo access to auditctl for near real-time audit configuration changes."},{"group_id_src":"V-207452","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207452","title":"SRG-OS-000341","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207452","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must allocate audit record storage capacity to store at least one weeks worth of audit records when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.","rule_id_src":"SV-207452r958752_rule","rule_id":"SV-207452r958752","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000341-VMM-001220","rule_title":"The VMM must allocate audit record storage capacity to store at least one weeks worth of audit records when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to allocate audit record storage capacity to store at least one week's worth of audit records when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM allocates audit record storage capacity to store at least one week's worth of audit records when audit records are not immediately sent to a central audit record storage facility.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"In order to ensure VMMs have a sufficient storage capacity in which to write the audit logs, VMMs need to be able to allocate audit record storage capacity. \n\nThe task of allocating audit record storage capacity is usually performed during initial installation of the VMM and should be based upon anticipated audit record volume.\n\nIf a central audit record storage facility is available, the local storage capacity should be sufficient to hold audit records that would accumulate during anticipated interruptions in delivery of records to the facility.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71365","V-57105"],"ccis":["CCI-001849"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"d88b5eba-f54d-4a96-802b-e999c61174b5","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that audit record storage capacity is insufficient or auditd is not active. The check examines auditd.conf for max_log_file, num_logs, and max_log_file_action settings and calculates total capacity. A minimum of 40 MB total capacity is required for the automated check to pass, though actual requirements depend on audit volume. To remediate: (1) Enable auditd if not active: systemctl enable --now auditd. (2) Configure adequate storage in /etc/audit/auditd.conf: set max_log_file to at least 50 MB, num_logs to at least 10, and max_log_file_action to ROTATE. (3) Ensure the /var/log/audit partition has sufficient free space. (4) Monitor audit log growth over one week to calibrate storage requirements. The system administrator should work with the ISSO to determine appropriate retention capacity based on the organization's audit policy and the hypervisor's typical audit event volume.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 3762D5167D5B10A616B921B83334246EFBD5C96F\n~~~~~\nAudit Record Storage Capacity\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nmax_log_file: NOT configured\nnum_logs: NOT configured\nmax_log_file_action: NOT configured\n\nRESULT: Audit storage capacity may not be sufficient for one week of records. Enable auditd: systemctl enable --now auditd. Review and increase max_log_file and num_logs in /etc/audit/auditd.conf to ensure at least one week of audit records can be stored. Recommended: max_log_file = 50, num_logs = 10 (500 MB total)."},{"group_id_src":"V-207453","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207453","title":"SRG-OS-000342","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207453","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must off-load audit records onto a different system or media than the system being audited.","rule_id_src":"SV-207453r958754_rule","rule_id":"SV-207453r958754","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000342-VMM-001230","rule_title":"The VMM must off-load audit records onto a different system or media than the system being audited.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to off-load audit records onto a different system or media than the system being audited.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM off-loads audit records onto a different system or media than the system being audited.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOff-loading is a common process in VMMs with limited audit storage capacity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71367","V-57107"],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"c05c23bb-dd48-4f7d-89f4-009a8c10fb7a","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that no remote audit off-loading is configured. Neither rsyslog remote forwarding nor the audisp au-remote plugin is active. To remediate: (1) Configure rsyslog for remote forwarding by adding a line such as '*.* @@logserver.domain:514' to /etc/rsyslog.conf (use @@ for TCP, @ for UDP). (2) Alternatively, install audispd-plugins (yum install audispd-plugins), enable the au-remote plugin in /etc/audisp/plugins.d/au-remote.conf (set active = yes), and configure the remote server in /etc/audisp/audisp-remote.conf. (3) Restart the appropriate service: systemctl restart rsyslog or systemctl restart auditd. The system administrator must ensure audit records are forwarded to a centralized log management system that is separate from the XCP-ng hypervisor, as required by NIST AU-4(1) and organizational audit policy.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: EE6838309599214DBDE48373A66C1851FF12EB54\n~~~~~\nAudit Record Off-Loading\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nrsyslog service: active\nRemote rsyslog targets: 0\naudisp au-remote plugin: not configured\n\nRESULT: No remote audit off-loading is configured. Configure rsyslog to forward to a central log server (e.g., add '*.* @@logserver:514' to /etc/rsyslog.conf) or enable the audisp au-remote plugin to forward audit records to a remote system."},{"group_id_src":"V-207454","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207454","title":"SRG-OS-000343","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207454","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must provide an immediate warning to the SA and ISSO, at a minimum, when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75% of repository maximum audit record storage capacity.\n","rule_id_src":"SV-207454r971542_rule","rule_id":"SV-207454r971542","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000343-VMM-001240","rule_title":"The VMM must provide an immediate warning to the SA and ISSO, at a minimum, when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75% of repository maximum audit record storage capacity.\n","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to provide an immediate warning to the SA and ISSO, at a minimum, when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75% of repository maximum audit record storage capacity.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM provides an immediate warning to the SA and ISSO, at a minimum, when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75% of repository maximum audit record storage capacity.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If security personnel are not notified immediately when storage volume reaches 75%, they are unable to plan for audit record storage capacity expansion.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71369","V-57109"],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"22e2ebc9-ec5d-4de3-b2ed-90e997324c38","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that auditd is not properly configured to warn when audit storage reaches 75% capacity. Either space_left is not configured or space_left_action is set to an unacceptable value (ignore or suspend). To remediate: (1) Calculate 25% of the /var/log/audit partition size. (2) Set space_left to that value in /etc/audit/auditd.conf. (3) Set space_left_action to 'email' (requires configured mail system) or 'exec' (to run a custom notification script). (4) Optionally set admin_space_left to a smaller value and admin_space_left_action to 'halt' or 'single' for critical-level warnings. (5) Restart auditd: systemctl restart auditd. The system administrator must work with the ISSO to ensure notification reaches designated personnel when storage reaches the 75% threshold.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 19A25A1956925A89700D06684F8100CA56F572BF\n~~~~~\nAudit Storage Warning at 75%\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nspace_left: NOT configured\nspace_left_action: NOT configured\nadmin_space_left: NOT configured\nadmin_space_left_action: NOT configured\n\nRESULT: auditd is not configured to provide storage capacity warnings. Set space_left to 25% of total audit partition size in /etc/audit/auditd.conf. Set space_left_action to 'email' or 'exec' (currently: not set). This ensures SA/ISSO receive immediate warning when audit storage reaches 75% capacity."},{"group_id_src":"V-207455","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207455","title":"SRG-OS-000344","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207455","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must provide an immediate real-time alert to the SA and ISSO, at a minimum, of all audit failure events requiring real-time alerts.","rule_id_src":"SV-207455r958758_rule","rule_id":"SV-207455r958758","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000344-VMM-001250","rule_title":"The VMM must provide an immediate real-time alert to the SA and ISSO, at a minimum, of all audit failure events requiring real-time alerts.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to provide an immediate real-time alert to the SA and ISSO, at a minimum, of all audit failure events requiring real-time alerts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM provides an immediate real-time alert to the SA and ISSO, at a minimum, of all audit failure events requiring real-time alerts.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a VMM is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required. Without a real-time alert, security personnel may be unaware of an impending failure of the audit capability, and system operation may be adversely affected. \n\nAlerts provide organizations with urgent messages. Real-time alerts provide these messages immediately (i.e., the time from event detection to alert occurs in seconds or less).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71371","V-57111"],"ccis":["CCI-001858"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"86f4da99-6f04-4eb0-8b33-9b284c7b456c","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that auditd is not fully configured for real-time audit failure alerts. One or more failure event actions (disk_full_action, disk_error_action, admin_space_left_action) are either not configured or set to unacceptable values (ignore or suspend). To remediate, set the following in /etc/audit/auditd.conf: disk_full_action = halt (stops system if audit disk is full, preventing unaudited operations), disk_error_action = halt (stops system on audit I/O errors), admin_space_left_action = email or exec (sends notification when critically low on space). After making changes, restart auditd: systemctl restart auditd. For email alerts, ensure a mail transport agent is configured. For exec alerts, create a notification script that alerts SA/ISSO via the organization's alerting system.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: CAB57505928606ABE158AF289190A8D1BEC5927A\n~~~~~\nAudit Failure Real-Time Alerts\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\ndisk_full_action: NOT configured\ndisk_error_action: NOT configured\nadmin_space_left_action: NOT configured\nspace_left_action: NOT configured\n\ndisk_full_action acceptable: False\ndisk_error_action acceptable: False\nadmin_space_left_action acceptable: False\n\nRESULT: auditd is not fully configured for real-time audit failure alerts. In /etc/audit/auditd.conf, set: disk_full_action = halt (or email/exec), disk_error_action = halt (or email/exec), admin_space_left_action = email (or exec/halt), then restart auditd: systemctl restart auditd."},{"group_id_src":"V-207456","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207456","title":"SRG-OS-000348","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207456","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must provide an audit reduction capability that supports on-demand audit review and analysis.","rule_id_src":"SV-207456r958766_rule","rule_id":"SV-207456r958766","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000348-VMM-001260","rule_title":"The VMM must provide an audit reduction capability that supports on-demand audit review and analysis.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to provide an audit reduction capability that supports on-demand audit review and analysis.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM provides an audit reduction capability that supports on-demand audit review and analysis.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The ability to perform on-demand audit review and analysis, including after the audit data has been subjected to audit reduction, greatly facilitates the organization's ability to generate incident reports as needed to better handle larger-scale or more complex security incidents. \n\nAudit reduction is a technique used to reduce the volume of audit records in order to facilitate a manual review. Audit reduction does not alter original audit records. The report generation capability provided by the application must support on-demand (i.e., customizable, ad hoc, and as-needed) reports.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71373","V-57113"],"ccis":["CCI-001875"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"bbba42fc-4658-44f3-84fb-fbe8139d7964","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that audit reduction tools (ausearch and/or aureport) are not installed. These tools are essential for on-demand review and analysis of audit records. To remediate: install the audit package using yum install audit. This provides ausearch for targeted filtering and searching of audit records and aureport for generating summary analysis reports. After installation, verify the tools are available: which ausearch aureport. The system administrator should ensure auditd is also active (systemctl enable --now auditd) to generate the audit records that these tools analyze. Without audit reduction capability, administrators cannot efficiently review the volume of audit data generated by the hypervisor.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: A9DD5E8AC2830A441ACD9C47F5465AC4CD5A88E8\n~~~~~\nAudit Reduction Capability - On-Demand Review\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nausearch: NOT installed\naureport: NOT installed\naulast: not available\naudit package: package audit is not installed\n\nRESULT: Audit reduction tools are not installed. Install the audit package: yum install audit. This provides ausearch for on-demand filtering/searching of audit records and aureport for summary analysis."},{"group_id_src":"V-207457","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207457","title":"SRG-OS-000349","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207457","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must provide an audit reduction capability that supports after-the-fact investigations of security incidents.","rule_id_src":"SV-207457r958768_rule","rule_id":"SV-207457r958768","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000349-VMM-001270","rule_title":"The VMM must provide an audit reduction capability that supports after-the-fact investigations of security incidents.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to provide an audit reduction capability that supports after-the-fact investigations of security incidents.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM provides an audit reduction capability that supports after-the-fact investigations of security incidents.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":" If the audit reduction capability does not support after-the-fact investigations, it is difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack or identify those responses for one. This capability is also required to comply with applicable Federal laws and DoD policies.\n\nAudit reduction capability must support after-the-fact investigations of security incidents either natively or through the use of third-party tools\n\nThis requirement is specific to VMMs with audit reduction capabilities","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71375","V-57115"],"ccis":["CCI-001877"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"9a63f652-2e31-4a3a-8870-7cf6f6a34d4a","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that audit reduction tools for after-the-fact investigations are not installed. Without ausearch and aureport, incident responders cannot efficiently analyze audit records to investigate security incidents. To remediate: install the audit package (yum install audit) and ensure auditd is running (systemctl enable --now auditd). Configure adequate audit log retention in /etc/audit/auditd.conf (increase num_logs and max_log_file) to ensure sufficient historical data for investigations. The system administrator should also configure audit rules to capture security-relevant events (privilege escalation, authentication, file access) that are typically needed during incident investigations.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: DE3AC2718BB8DF7EF7F24B75B1DC96A945978495\n~~~~~\nAudit Reduction Capability - After-the-Fact Investigations\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nausearch: NOT installed\naureport: NOT installed\nnum_logs: not set\nmax_log_file: not set\nArchived audit log files: 0\n\nRESULT: Audit reduction tools for after-the-fact investigations are not installed. Install the audit package: yum install audit. This provides ausearch for forensic filtering/correlation and aureport for incident analysis reporting."},{"group_id_src":"V-207458","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207458","title":"SRG-OS-000350","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207458","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must provide a report generation capability that supports on-demand audit review and analysis.","rule_id_src":"SV-207458r958770_rule","rule_id":"SV-207458r958770","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000350-VMM-001280","rule_title":"The VMM must provide a report generation capability that supports on-demand audit review and analysis.","fix_text":"Ensure the VMM provides a report generation capability that supports on-demand audit review and analysis.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM provides a report generation capability that supports on-demand audit review and analysis.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The report generation capability must support on-demand review and analysis in order to facilitate the organization's ability to generate incident reports as needed to better handle larger-scale or more complex security incidents. \n\nReport generation must be capable of generating on-demand (i.e., customizable, ad hoc, and as-needed) reports. On-demand reporting allows personnel to report issues more rapidly to more effectively meet reporting requirements. Collecting log data and aggregating it to present the data in a single, consolidated report achieves this objective.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71377","V-57117"],"ccis":["CCI-001878"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"44b8b756-09da-4b31-ae35-19e090841daa","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that report generation tools are not installed. aureport is required for generating structured audit reports for on-demand review. To remediate: install the audit package (yum install audit) which provides aureport along with ausearch and other audit tools. After installation, verify: which aureport. Ensure auditd is active to generate the audit records that aureport analyzes. The system administrator should familiarize themselves with aureport's report categories (logins, files, users, anomalies, etc.) and time-range filtering to support on-demand reporting requirements from the ISSO or auditors.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 728F83AFACC6797A5DACE3229042E2C243FB24F5\n~~~~~\nReport Generation - On-Demand Review and Analysis\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\naureport: NOT installed\nausearch: NOT installed\naudit package: package audit is not installed\nauditd service: inactive\n\nRESULT: Report generation tools are not installed. Install the audit package: yum install audit. This provides aureport for generating on-demand audit reports across multiple event categories (logins, files, users, processes, anomalies)."},{"group_id_src":"V-207459","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207459","title":"SRG-OS-000351","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207459","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must provide a report generation capability that supports on-demand reporting requirements.","rule_id_src":"SV-207459r958772_rule","rule_id":"SV-207459r958772","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000351-VMM-001290","rule_title":"The VMM must provide a report generation capability that supports on-demand reporting requirements.","fix_text":"Ensure the VMM provides a report generation capability that supports on-demand reporting requirements.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM provides a report generation capability that supports on-demand reporting requirements.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The report generation capability must support on-demand reporting in order to facilitate the organization's ability to generate incident reports as needed to better handle larger-scale or more complex security incidents. \n\nReport generation must be capable of generating on-demand (i.e., customizable, ad hoc, and as-needed) reports. On-demand reporting allows personnel to report issues more rapidly to more effectively meet reporting requirements. Collecting log data and aggregating it to present the data in a single, consolidated report achieves this objective.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71379","V-57119"],"ccis":["CCI-001879"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"a0613683-0b79-419d-850e-599f5c2b63ca","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that report generation tools are not installed. aureport is required for generating customizable audit reports. To remediate: install the audit package (yum install audit) to provide aureport and ausearch. Ensure auditd is active (systemctl enable --now auditd). After installation, administrators can generate on-demand reports using aureport with category flags (-l, -f, -x, -u, -p, -s, -a, -m) and time-range filtering (-ts/-te). The system administrator should establish standard operating procedures for generating periodic and on-demand audit reports to meet organizational reporting requirements.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 84ACA2C9DB941D93A0C4AE869AF9086329E7DC6B\n~~~~~\nReport Generation - On-Demand Reporting Requirements\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\naureport: NOT installed\nausearch: NOT installed\nauditd service: inactive\nlast command: available\nlastlog command: available\n\nRESULT: Report generation tools are not installed. Install the audit package: yum install audit. This provides aureport for generating customizable on-demand audit reports."},{"group_id_src":"V-207460","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207460","title":"SRG-OS-000352","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207460","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must provide a report generation capability that supports after-the-fact investigations of security incidents.","rule_id_src":"SV-207460r958774_rule","rule_id":"SV-207460r958774","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000352-VMM-001300","rule_title":"The VMM must provide a report generation capability that supports after-the-fact investigations of security incidents.","fix_text":"Ensure the VMM provides a report generation capability that supports after-the-fact investigations of security incidents.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM provides a report generation capability that supports after-the-fact investigations of security incidents.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the report generation capability does not support after-the-fact investigations, it is difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events leading up to an outage or attack or identify those responses for one. This capability is also required to comply with applicable Federal laws and DoD policies.\n\nThe report generation capability must support after-the-fact investigations of security incidents either natively or through the use of third-party tools.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71381","V-57121"],"ccis":["CCI-001880"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"ab2e0cc5-29ad-4511-af12-731905f5504d","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that report generation tools for incident investigation are not installed. Install the audit package (yum install audit) to provide aureport for generating incident-focused reports and ausearch for forensic data correlation. Ensure auditd is active and configure adequate log retention for historical investigation. The system administrator should ensure audit rules capture security-relevant events and that incident responders have appropriate access to audit tools and log files for generating investigation reports.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 9B9982B91EF5F84F5AC22628330B068967A818C1\n~~~~~\nReport Generation - After-the-Fact Investigations\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\naureport: NOT installed\nausearch: NOT installed\nAudit log files available: 0\nXen log files: 1\n\nRESULT: Report generation tools for incident investigation are not installed. Install the audit package: yum install audit. This provides aureport for generating incident-focused reports and ausearch for forensic data correlation."},{"group_id_src":"V-207461","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207461","title":"SRG-OS-000353","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207461","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM that provides an audit reduction capability must not alter original content or time ordering of audit records.","rule_id_src":"SV-207461r958776_rule","rule_id":"SV-207461r958776","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000353-VMM-001310","rule_title":"The VMM that provides an audit reduction capability must not alter original content or time ordering of audit records.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM that provides an audit reduction capability so that it does not alter original content or time ordering of audit records.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM that provides an audit reduction capability does not alter original content or time ordering of audit records.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":" If the audit reduction capability alters the content or time ordering of audit records, the integrity of the audit records is compromised, and the records are no longer usable for forensic analysis.\n\nAudit reduction is a process that manipulates collected audit information and organizes such information in a summary format that is more meaningful to analysts. Time ordering refers to the chronological organization of records based on time stamps. The degree of time stamp precision can affect this.\n\nThis requirement is specific to VMMs providing audit reduction capabilities. The audit reduction capability can be met either natively or through the use of third-party tools.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71383","V-57123"],"ccis":["CCI-001881"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"85dfee37-0bac-4419-82d7-ab487ddf55dc","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that ausearch is not installed. Install the audit package (yum install audit) to provide ausearch, which operates in read-only mode and preserves original content and time ordering of audit records during reduction operations. The standard Linux audit tools are designed to never modify the original audit log data.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: DD0328EA4962E4E6F63AC12152937B21D5361B73\n~~~~~\nAudit Reduction - Content/Time Ordering Preservation\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nausearch: NOT installed\naudit.log permissions: file not found\naudit package: package audit is not installed\n\nRESULT: Audit reduction tools are not installed. Install the audit package (yum install audit) to provide ausearch, which operates in read-only mode and preserves original content and time ordering of audit records."},{"group_id_src":"V-207462","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207462","title":"SRG-OS-000354","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207462","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM that provides a report generation capability must not alter original content or time ordering of audit records.","rule_id_src":"SV-207462r987795_rule","rule_id":"SV-207462r987795","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000354-VMM-001320","rule_title":"The VMM that provides a report generation capability must not alter original content or time ordering of audit records.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM that provides a report generation capability so that it does not alter original content or time ordering of audit records.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM that provides a report generation capability does not alter original content or time ordering of audit records.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If the report generation capability alters the content or time ordering of audit records, the integrity of the audit records is compromised, and the records are no longer usable for forensic analysis.\n\nTime ordering refers to the chronological organization of records based on time stamps. The degree of time stamp precision can affect this.\n\nThis requirement is specific to VMMs providing report generation capabilities. The report generation capability can be met either natively or through the use of third-party tools.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71385","V-57125"],"ccis":["CCI-001882"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"777832e5-ee82-4f8f-9698-f10f8748345e","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that aureport is not installed. Install the audit package (yum install audit) to provide aureport, which operates in read-only mode and preserves original content and time ordering of audit records when generating reports. The standard Linux audit reporting tools are designed to never modify the original audit log data.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 406E5B7D5F7CA883ACB1672FD7DEB0429B11FACE\n~~~~~\nReport Generation - Content/Time Ordering Preservation\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\naureport: NOT installed\naudit.log permissions: file not found\naudit package: package audit is not installed\n\nRESULT: Report generation tools are not installed. Install the audit package (yum install audit) to provide aureport, which operates in read-only mode and preserves original content and time ordering of audit records when generating reports."},{"group_id_src":"V-207463","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207463","title":"SRG-OS-000355","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207463","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must, for networked systems, compare internal information system clocks at least every 24 hours with an authoritative time source.","rule_id_src":"SV-207463r1038976_rule","rule_id":"SV-207463r1038976","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000355-VMM-001330","rule_title":"The VMM must, for networked systems, compare internal information system clocks at least every 24 hours with an authoritative time source.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM, for networked systems, to compare internal information system clocks at least every 24 hours with an authoritative time source.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM, for networked systems, compares internal information system clocks at least every 24 hours with an authoritative time source.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inaccurate time stamps make it more difficult to correlate events and can lead to an inaccurate analysis. Determining the correct time a particular event occurred on a system is critical when conducting forensic analysis and investigating system events. Sources outside of the configured acceptable allowance (drift) may be inaccurate.\n\nSynchronizing internal VMM clocks provides uniformity of time stamps for VMMs with multiple system clocks and systems connected over a network.\n\nOrganizations should consider endpoints that may not have regular access to the authoritative time server (e.g., mobile, teleworking, and tactical endpoints).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71387","V-57127"],"ccis":["CCI-004923"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"fd8b6166-f46f-406c-b329-544982fc6e34","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified that NTP time synchronization is active (via chronyd or ntpd) with authoritative time sources configured. The check examines service status, configured time servers from chrony.conf or ntp.conf, and current synchronization status. NTP clients poll time servers at intervals ranging from 64 seconds (minpoll 6) to 1024 seconds (maxpoll 10) by default, which far exceeds the 24-hour comparison requirement. Chrony sources and tracking information confirm active synchronization with the configured authoritative time servers. This ensures the XCP-ng hypervisor's internal clock is continuously compared with authoritative time sources well within the required 24-hour interval, satisfying NIST AU-8(1)(a) requirements.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: BECBDE1E23BF9AD6F2E5868170D6D706C7DB7DFF\n~~~~~\nNTP Time Synchronization (24-Hour Comparison)\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nchronyd service: active\nntpd service: inactive\n\nChrony Sources:\n210 Number of sources = 4\nMS Name/IP address         Stratum Poll Reach LastRx Last sample               \n===============================================================================\n^* 68-234-48-70.planet.net       1  10   377   931  +2688us[+2795us] +/- 8005us\n^+ 216-144-228-179-host.col>     2  10   377   721  -5357us[-5357us] +/-   14ms\n^- 139-177-202-26.ip.linode>     2  10   377    24    -10ms[  -10ms] +/-   79ms\n^- hou1.us.ntp.li                2  10   377  1046   +833us[ +940us] +/-   66ms\n\nChrony Tracking:\nReference ID    : 44EA3046 (68-234-48-70.planet.net)\nStratum         : 2\nRef time (UTC)  : Sat Mar 14 20:41:53 2026\nSystem time     : 0.000267852 seconds slow of NTP time\nLast offset     : +0.000107202 seconds\nRMS offset      : 0.000147320 seconds\nFrequency       : 4.327 ppm slow\nResidual freq   : -0.000 ppm\nSkew            : 0.045 ppm\nRoot delay      : 0.010659291 seconds\nRoot dispersion : 0.001257987 seconds\nUpdate interval : 1032.9 seconds\nLeap status     : Normal\n\nConfigured time sources (chrony.conf):\n  server 0.centos.pool.ntp.org iburst\n  server 1.centos.pool.ntp.org iburst\n  server 2.centos.pool.ntp.org iburst\n  server 3.centos.pool.ntp.org iburst\n\nRESULT: NTP time synchronization is active. chronyd is running and configured with 4 authoritative time source(s). By default, NTP clients poll servers at intervals ranging from 64 seconds (minpoll 6) to 1024 seconds (maxpoll 10), far exceeding the 24-hour comparison requirement."},{"group_id_src":"V-207464","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207464","title":"SRG-OS-000356","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207464","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must synchronize internal information system clocks to the authoritative time source when the time difference is greater than one second.","rule_id_src":"SV-207464r984238_rule","rule_id":"SV-207464r984238","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000356-VMM-001340","rule_title":"The VMM must synchronize internal information system clocks to the authoritative time source when the time difference is greater than one second.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to synchronize internal information system clocks to the authoritative time source when the time difference is greater than one second.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM synchronizes internal information system clocks to the authoritative time source when the time difference is greater than one second.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Inaccurate time stamps make it more difficult to correlate events and can lead to an inaccurate analysis. Determining the correct time a particular event occurred on a system is critical when conducting forensic analysis and investigating system events. \n\nSynchronizing internal VMM clocks provides uniformity of time stamps for VMMs with multiple system clocks and systems connected over a network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71389","V-57129"],"ccis":["CCI-004926"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"10389907-ef13-4071-8475-91a850c7211b","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified that NTP time synchronization is active via chronyd or ntpd. The check examines service status, chrony.conf or ntp.conf for the makestep directive, and current time offset from the authoritative source. chronyd uses the makestep directive to enable immediate clock stepping for offsets larger than the configured threshold and continuous slewing for smaller offsets. Both mechanisms ensure the system clock is automatically synchronized when the time difference exceeds one second. The current system time offset and root delay are reported to confirm active synchronization. This satisfies NIST AU-8(1)(b) requirements for automatic clock synchronization when time difference exceeds one second.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 114E87E3736D169A5A89EDEA85157FCAEBA0B3F2\n~~~~~\nClock Synchronization (1-Second Threshold)\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nchronyd service: active\nntpd service: inactive\nmakestep directive: makestep 1.0 3\nCurrent system time offset: 0.000267825 seconds slow of NTP time\nRoot delay: 0.010659291 seconds\n\nRESULT: NTP time synchronization is active and automatically corrects time differences. chronyd continuously adjusts system clock via slewing for small offsets. The makestep directive enables immediate stepping for offsets larger than the configured threshold. Both mechanisms ensure synchronization when the time difference exceeds one second."},{"group_id_src":"V-207465","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207465","title":"SRG-OS-000358","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207465","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must record time stamps for audit records that meet a granularity of one second for a minimum degree of precision.","rule_id_src":"SV-207465r958786_rule","rule_id":"SV-207465r958786","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000358-VMM-001350","rule_title":"The VMM must record time stamps for audit records that meet a granularity of one second for a minimum degree of precision.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to record time stamps for audit records that meet a granularity of one second for a minimum degree of precision.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM records time stamps for audit records that meet a granularity of one second for a minimum degree of precision.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without sufficient granularity of time stamps, it is not possible to adequately determine the chronological order of records. \n\nTime stamps generated by the VMM include date and time. Granularity of time measurements refers to the degree of synchronization between VMM clocks and reference clocks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71391","V-57131"],"ccis":["CCI-001889"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"019b1214-410c-4cab-a8b5-dbd7b6d8b2cf","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that auditd is not active. Without the audit service running, no audit records with timestamps are being generated. Enable the audit service: systemctl enable --now auditd. The Linux audit framework inherently provides sub-second (millisecond) timestamp precision when active, exceeding the one-second granularity requirement. No additional configuration is needed for timestamp precision once auditd is running.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 852B8C342DE0ECBAEE6F4373ECF95B83A14397A2\n~~~~~\nAudit Timestamp Granularity (1-Second Minimum)\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nlog_format: RAW (default)\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Enable the audit service: systemctl enable --now auditd. The Linux audit framework inherently provides sub-second timestamp precision when active."},{"group_id_src":"V-207466","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207466","title":"SRG-OS-000359","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207466","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must record time stamps for audit records that can be mapped to Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) or Greenwich Mean Time (GMT).","rule_id_src":"SV-207466r958788_rule","rule_id":"SV-207466r958788","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000359-VMM-001360","rule_title":"The VMM must record time stamps for audit records that can be mapped to Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) or Greenwich Mean Time (GMT).","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to record time stamps for audit records that can be mapped to Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) or Greenwich Mean Time (GMT).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM records time stamps for audit records that can be mapped to Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) or Greenwich Mean Time (GMT).\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If time stamps are not consistently applied and there is no common time reference, it is difficult to perform forensic analysis.\n\nTime stamps generated by the VMM include date and time. Time is commonly expressed in Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), a modern continuation of Greenwich Mean Time (GMT), or local time with an offset from UTC.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71393","V-57133"],"ccis":["CCI-001890"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"94668671-5580-4190-9848-97691721e629","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that auditd is not active. Without the audit service running, no audit records with UTC-mappable timestamps are being generated. Enable the audit service: systemctl enable --now auditd. The Linux audit framework records timestamps in UTC-based epoch format, which satisfies the UTC/GMT mapping requirement. Optionally, set the system timezone to UTC (timedatectl set-timezone UTC) for consistency with audit timestamps.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 186C14C5411D8E5C94C4E1CF96B3CD16629D15FF\n~~~~~\nAudit Timestamps Mappable to UTC/GMT\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSystem timezone: America/New_York (EDT, -0400)\nUniversal time: Sat 2026-03-14 20:57:26 UTC\nlocaltime: lrwxrwxrwx 1 root root 38 Dec  5  2024 /etc/localtime -> ../usr/share/zoneinfo/America/New_York\nauditd service: inactive\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Enable the audit service: systemctl enable --now auditd. The Linux audit framework records timestamps in UTC-based epoch format, satisfying the UTC/GMT mapping requirement."},{"group_id_src":"V-207467","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207467","title":"SRG-OS-000360","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207467","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must enforce dual authorization for movement and/or deletion of all audit information, when such movement or deletion is not part of an authorized automatic process.","rule_id_src":"SV-207467r958790_rule","rule_id":"SV-207467r958790","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000360-VMM-001370","rule_title":"The VMM must enforce dual authorization for movement and/or deletion of all audit information, when such movement or deletion is not part of an authorized automatic process.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to enforce dual authorization for movement and/or deletion of all audit information, when such movement or deletion is not part of an authorized automatic process.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM enforces dual authorization for movement and/or deletion of all audit information, when such movement or deletion is not part of an authorized automatic process.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"An authorized user may intentionally or accidentally move or delete audit records without those specific actions being authorized.\n\nAll bulk manipulation of audit information must be via authorized automatic processes. Any manual manipulation of audit information must require dual authorization. Dual authorization mechanisms require the approval of two authorized individuals in order to execute.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71395","V-57135"],"ccis":["CCI-000366","CCI-001896"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"278d677b-5e8d-4c5c-b3f1-d1e35fa359ba","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check reports audit log file permissions, directory ownership, audit rule immutability status, and file watches. Dual authorization for movement/deletion of audit information requires organizational policy controls beyond what XCP-ng can enforce technically through its native capabilities. While audit log files are restricted to root ownership with restrictive permissions, and audit rules can be made immutable (-e 2), the dual authorization requirement (two separate individuals must independently authorize) must be enforced through organizational procedures. Recommended organizational controls include: requiring ISSO approval before SA can delete or move audit logs via a formal change request process, implementing ticket-based change control for audit data operations, maintaining a log of all audit data movement and deletion activities, and configuring sudo to require a separate authorization for audit-related commands.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 8A469CEA324A2210EB5613607DE45A570B8CDC96\n~~~~~\nDual Authorization for Audit Data Movement/Deletion\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\naudit.log permissions: file not found\n/var/log/audit/ permissions: directory not found\nAudit rules immutable (-e 2): False\nAudit watches on /var/log/audit: 0\n\nRESULT: Dual authorization for movement/deletion of audit information requires organizational policy controls beyond what XCP-ng can enforce technically. While audit log files are restricted to root ownership () and audit rules can be made immutable (-e 2), the dual authorization requirement (two separate individuals must authorize) must be enforced through organizational procedures such as: requiring ISSO approval before SA can delete/move audit logs, implementing ticket-based change control for audit data operations, and maintaining a log of all audit data movement/deletion activities."},{"group_id_src":"V-207468","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207468","title":"SRG-OS-000362","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207468","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must prohibit user installation of software without explicit privileged status.","rule_id_src":"SV-207468r984239_rule","rule_id":"SV-207468r984239","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000362-VMM-001390","rule_title":"The VMM must prohibit user installation of software without explicit privileged status.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to prohibit user installation of software or guest VMs without explicit privileged status.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM prohibits user installation of software or guest VMs without explicit privileged status.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Allowing regular users to install software or guest VMs, without explicit privileges, creates the risk that untested or potentially malicious software will be installed on the VMM. Explicit privileges (escalated or administrative privileges) provide the regular user with explicit capabilities and control that exceeds the rights of a regular user.\n\nVMM functionality will vary, and while users are not permitted to install unapproved software or guest VMs, there may be instances when the organization allows the user to install approved software packages such as from an approved software repository. \n\nThe VMM or software configuration management utility must enforce control of software installation by users based upon what types of software installations are permitted (e.g., updates and security patches to existing software) and what types of installations are prohibited (e.g., software whose pedigree with regard to being potentially malicious is unknown or suspect) by the organization.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71397","V-57137"],"ccis":["CCI-003980"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"44acfa52-e54f-4ea8-933f-205e4f22630b","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified that XCP-ng enforces privileged access for software and VM installation through multiple mechanisms. RPM/YUM package installation requires root privileges as the binaries are owned by root with standard permissions. XAPI RBAC restricts VM creation and management operations to pool-admin and pool-operator roles. Dom0 SSH access is limited to authorized administrators. The check examines yum and rpm binary permissions, RBAC role availability, configured RBAC subjects, and sudo configuration. Non-privileged users cannot install software packages or create guest VMs without explicit elevated privileges. This multi-layer privilege enforcement satisfies NIST CM-11(2) requirements for prohibiting user software installation without explicit privileged status.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 8426B2ACC4244D6ECA309623C5DF0A50D4B81836\n~~~~~\nSoftware Installation Privilege Restriction\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nRBAC roles available: 7955168d-7bec-10ed-105f-c6a7e6e63249,aaa00ab5-7340-bfbc-0d1b-7cf342639a6e,fb8d4ff9-310c-a959-0613-54101535d3d5,7233b8e3-eacb-d7da-2c95-f2e581cdbf4e,2c42debf-c64a-2ecd-f674-3350f06409f7,0165f154-ba3e-034e-6b27-5d271af109ba,b9ce9791-0604-50cd-0649-09b3284c7dfd\nyum binary permissions: 755 root root\nrpm binary permissions: 755 root root\nsudo rules for package management: 1\nRBAC subjects configured: 0\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng enforces privileged access for software and VM installation through multiple mechanisms: (1) RPM/YUM package installation requires root privileges (owned by root, standard permissions). (2) XAPI RBAC restricts VM creation to pool-admin and pool-operator roles. (3) Dom0 SSH access is limited to authorized administrators. Non-privileged users cannot install software or create guest VMs without explicit elevated privileges."},{"group_id_src":"V-207469","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207469","title":"SRG-OS-000363","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207469","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must notify designated personnel if baseline configurations are changed in an unauthorized manner.","rule_id_src":"SV-207469r958794_rule","rule_id":"SV-207469r958794","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000363-VMM-001400","rule_title":"The VMM must notify designated personnel if baseline configurations are changed in an unauthorized manner.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to notify designated personnel if baseline configurations are changed in an unauthorized manner.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM notifies designated personnel if baseline configurations are changed in an unauthorized manner.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Unauthorized changes to the baseline configuration could make the VMM vulnerable to various attacks or allow unauthorized access to the VMM. Changes to VMM configurations can have unintended side effects, some of which may be relevant to security. \n\nDetecting such changes and providing an automated response can help avoid unintended, negative consequences that could ultimately affect the security state of the VMM. The VMM's IMO/ISSO and SAs must be notified via email and/or monitoring system trap when there is an unauthorized modification of a configuration item.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71399","V-57139"],"ccis":["CCI-001744"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"065104d1-b045-42ed-8964-9b13ac5b71e3","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that no file integrity monitoring tool is configured to detect and notify on unauthorized baseline changes. To remediate: (1) Install AIDE: yum install aide. (2) Configure /etc/aide.conf with baseline paths including /etc/xensource/, /etc/xapi.conf, /etc/audit/, /etc/ssh/sshd_config, and other critical configuration files. (3) Initialize the baseline database: aide --init, then cp /var/lib/aide/aide.db.new.gz /var/lib/aide/aide.db.gz. (4) Configure a daily cron job: echo '0 5 * * * root /usr/sbin/aide --check | mail -s \"AIDE Report\" isso@domain' > /etc/cron.d/aide-check. (5) After any authorized change, update the baseline: aide --update. The system administrator must ensure AIDE reports are reviewed by designated personnel (SA/ISSO).\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 99B6E963F1C394448E2295B127CE8874F7DA8BB3\n~~~~~\nBaseline Configuration Change Notification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nAIDE: NOT installed\nAIDE config: NOT found\nTripwire: not installed\nAudit watches on config files: 0\nAIDE cron jobs: 0\n\nRESULT: No file integrity monitoring tool is configured to detect and notify on unauthorized baseline changes. Install and configure AIDE: yum install aide, configure /etc/aide.conf with baseline paths (including /etc/xensource/, /etc/xapi.conf, /etc/audit/), initialize database (aide --init), and configure cron job for regular scanning with email notification to SA/ISSO."},{"group_id_src":"V-207470","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207470","title":"SRG-OS-000364","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207470","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must enforce access restrictions associated with changes to the system.","rule_id_src":"SV-207470r958796_rule","rule_id":"SV-207470r958796","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000364-VMM-001410","rule_title":"The VMM must enforce access restrictions associated with changes to the system.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to enforce access restrictions associated with changes to the system.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM enforces access restrictions associated with changes to the system.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Failure to provide logical access restrictions associated with changes to system configuration may have significant effects on the overall security of the system. \n\nWhen dealing with access restrictions pertaining to change control, it should be noted that any changes to the hardware, software, and/or firmware components of the VMM can potentially have significant effects on the overall security of the system. \n\nAccordingly, only qualified and authorized individuals should be allowed to obtain access to VMM components for the purposes of initiating changes, including upgrades and modifications. \n\nLogical access restrictions include, for example, controls that restrict access to guest VMs, workflow automation, media libraries, abstract layers (e.g., changes implemented into third-party interfaces rather than directly into VMMs), and change windows (e.g., changes occur only during specified times, making unauthorized changes easy to discover).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71401","V-57141"],"ccis":["CCI-001813"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"512f6d03-505b-45e0-b3f8-1b2741741809","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified that XCP-ng enforces access restrictions for system changes through multiple layers. XAPI RBAC provides a role hierarchy (pool-admin, pool-operator, vm-power-admin, vm-admin, vm-operator, read-only) that restricts management API operations to authorized roles. Linux DAC file permissions restrict access to critical configuration files (/etc/xapi.conf, /etc/xensource/). sudo controls limit which users can execute privileged commands. SSH access to Dom0 is restricted to authorized administrators. Only the pool-admin role can modify pool-level configurations and system settings. The check reports RBAC role availability, configured subjects, sudoers configuration, and file permissions on critical hypervisor configuration files. This multi-layer access control satisfies NIST CM-5 requirements.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: D9602C46B9BD39B2810722E99B98D4B0DCA1168E\n~~~~~\nAccess Restrictions for System Changes\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nRBAC roles: vm-power-admin,vm-admin,vm-operator,read-only,client-cert,pool-admin,pool-operator\nRBAC subjects: 0\nsudoers file: present\nsudoers.d entries: 0\n/etc/xapi.conf permissions: 644 root root\n/etc/xensource permissions: 755 root root\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng enforces access restrictions for system changes through multiple layers: (1) XAPI RBAC with role hierarchy (pool-admin, pool-operator, vm-power-admin, vm-admin, vm-operator, read-only) restricts management API operations. (2) Linux DAC file permissions restrict access to critical configuration files. (3) sudo controls limit which users can execute privileged commands. (4) SSH access to Dom0 is restricted to authorized administrators. Only pool-admin role can modify pool-level configurations and system settings."},{"group_id_src":"V-207471","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207471","title":"SRG-OS-000365","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207471","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must audit the enforcement actions used to restrict access associated with changes to the system.","rule_id_src":"SV-207471r984240_rule","rule_id":"SV-207471r984240","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000365-VMM-001420","rule_title":"The VMM must audit the enforcement actions used to restrict access associated with changes to the system.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to audit the enforcement actions used to restrict access associated with changes to the system.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM audits the enforcement actions used to restrict access associated with changes to the system.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without auditing the enforcement of access restrictions against changes to the VMM configuration, it will be difficult to identify attempted attacks, and an audit trail will not be available for forensic investigation for after-the-fact actions. \n\nEnforcement actions are the methods or mechanisms used to prevent unauthorized changes to configuration settings. Enforcement action methods may be as simple as denying access to a file based on the application of file permissions (access restriction). Audit items may consist of lists of actions blocked by access restrictions or changes identified after the fact.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71403","V-57143"],"ccis":["CCI-003938"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"b137e189-48cb-4aa4-8ba7-d09f36f7fb6d","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check found that auditd is not active. Enable auditd to audit access restriction enforcement: systemctl enable --now auditd. Configure audit rules: (1) sudo monitoring: -w /etc/sudoers -p wa -k actions. (2) su monitoring: -w /usr/bin/su -p x -k priv_esc. (3) Permission changes: -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chmod,chown,setxattr -k perm_mod. (4) Access denials: -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S open -F exit=-EACCES -k access. Add rules to /etc/audit/rules.d/ and reload: augenrules --load. These rules ensure all enforcement actions are audited per NIST CM-5(1).\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 08825B10BBB4450A937145918E7AA31EBD3C2AD7\n~~~~~\nAudit of Access Restriction Enforcement Actions\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nAudit rules for privilege escalation: 0\nAudit rules for access/permission changes: 0\nSecurity log (/var/log/secure): present\nXAPI log: present\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Enable auditd to audit access restriction enforcement: systemctl enable --now auditd. Configure audit rules for sudo (-w /etc/sudoers -p wa), su (-w /usr/bin/su -p x), permission changes (-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chmod,chown,setxattr -k perm_mod), and access denials (-a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S open -F exit=-EACCES -k access)."},{"group_id_src":"V-207472","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207472","title":"SRG-OS-000366","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207472","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must prevent the installation of guest VMs, patches, service packs, device drivers, or VMM components without verification they have been digitally signed using a certificate that is recognized and approved by the organization.","rule_id_src":"SV-207472r984242_rule","rule_id":"SV-207472r984242","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000366-VMM-001430","rule_title":"The VMM must prevent the installation of guest VMs, patches, service packs, device drivers, or VMM components without verification they have been digitally signed using a certificate that is recognized and approved by the organization.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to prevent the installation of guest VMs, patches, service packs, device drivers, or VMM components without verification they have been digitally signed using a certificate that is recognized and approved by the organization.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM prevents the installation of guest VMs, patches, service packs, device drivers, or VMM components without verification they have been digitally signed using a certificate that is recognized and approved by the organization.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Changes to any software components can have significant effects on the overall security of the VMM. This requirement ensures the software has not been tampered with and that it has been provided by a trusted vendor. \n\nAccordingly, guest VMs, patches, service packs, device drivers, or VMM components must be signed with a certificate recognized and approved by the organization. \n\nVerifying the authenticity of the software prior to installation validates the integrity of the patch or upgrade received from a vendor. This ensures the software has not been tampered with and that it has been provided by a trusted vendor. Self-signed certificates are disallowed by this requirement. The VMM should not have to verify the software again. This requirement does not mandate DOD certificates for this purpose; however, the certificate used to verify the software must be from an approved certificate authority (CA).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71405","V-57145"],"ccis":["CCI-003992"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"85ebc773-a315-4d6a-ad59-1b9139e03a39","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified that RPM/YUM GPG signature verification is enabled globally (gpgcheck=1 in /etc/yum.conf) and no repositories have GPG checking disabled. All packages must be signed with an approved GPG key before installation. XCP-ng packages are signed with the Vates/XCP-ng GPG key, and the check confirms installed GPG public keys. The check examines the global yum.conf gpgcheck setting, localpkg_gpgcheck setting, individual repository configurations, and counts repos with gpgcheck disabled. This ensures patches, drivers, and VMM components are cryptographically verified before installation, satisfying NIST CM-14 requirements for digital signature verification of software installations.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: BA199D28CCD3E5682C26951A32E81E2159D19150\n~~~~~\nDigital Signature Verification for Installations\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nyum.conf gpgcheck: 1\nyum.conf localpkg_gpgcheck: NOT configured (defaults to gpgcheck)\nRepos with gpgcheck setting: 5\nRepos with gpgcheck DISABLED: 0\nInstalled GPG keys: 1\n\nRESULT: RPM/YUM GPG signature verification is enabled globally (gpgcheck=1) and no repositories have GPG checking disabled. All packages must be signed with an approved GPG key before installation. XCP-ng packages are signed with the Vates/XCP-ng GPG key. This ensures patches, drivers, and VMM components are verified before installation."},{"group_id_src":"V-207473","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207473","title":"SRG-OS-000368","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207473","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must prevent use of service and helper VMs not required to support proper VMM function.","rule_id_src":"SV-207473r958804_rule","rule_id":"SV-207473r958804","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000368-VMM-001440","rule_title":"The VMM must prevent use of service and helper VMs not required to support proper VMM function.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to prevent use of service and helper VMs not required to support proper VMM function.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM prevents use of service and helper VMs not required to support proper VMM function.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Control of program execution is a mechanism used to prevent execution of unauthorized programs. Some VMMs may provide a capability that runs counter to the mission or provides users with functionality that exceeds mission requirements. This includes functions and services installed at the VMM level.\n\nSome of the service and helper VMs, installed by default, may be harmful or may not be necessary to support essential organizational operations (e.g., key missions, functions). Removal of such VMs is not always possible; therefore, establishing a method of preventing VM activation is critical to maintaining a secure system baseline.\n\nMethods for complying with this requirement include restricting execution of VMs in certain environments, while preventing execution in other environments; or limiting execution of certain VM functionality based on organizationally defined criteria (e.g., privileges, subnets, sandboxed environments, or roles).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71407","V-57147"],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"e3874521-f518-45c3-83af-fd5bf05138ea","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified that XCP-ng does not deploy service or helper VMs as part of its core hypervisor function. Unlike some hypervisors (e.g., VMware vCLS), XCP-ng uses Dom0 (the control domain) for all management operations rather than dedicated service VMs. The check enumerates all guest VMs (non-template, non-control-domain) with their power states and reports the total count. All running VMs are explicitly created by administrators. XAPI RBAC controls restrict VM creation and management to authorized roles (pool-admin, pool-operator). The check also identifies any known service VMs such as XOA Proxy. Administrators should periodically review the VM inventory to ensure no unnecessary service or helper VMs are present beyond those required for authorized management functions.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 9B9017E4EB8837E40BAD9D9D2F00F7F16657129A\n~~~~~\nService and Helper VM Control\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nGuest VMs (non-template, non-control-domain):\nuuid ( RO)           : 850f91ab-bd99-6079-69d8-0ca8aef234ad\n     name-label ( RW): ALMALINUX-10.1-NETBOX-BUILD-VM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 1fa117d5-e8a6-c5ba-1f16-59f1fa11bc59\n     name-label ( RW): RHEL9.6-NETBOX-TEST-VM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : bfb145be-e7a0-3993-f40f-183e46febbe7\n     name-label ( RW): DH01_2024-12-06T19:34:54.531Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 4a2fe109-6005-a95a-a041-06bf22d6f940\n     name-label ( RW): UDS DBserver 4.0.0\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 09573b9d-2c29-0b0a-15c8-c45bddfb47a6\n     name-label ( RW): RUSTDESK01\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : e759ef30-c9f9-03ce-c03e-6cc9b48d964d\n     name-label ( RW): DOCKER01\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : c6dafd34-46a0-3e95-c3b1-b1fa1e60891c\n     name-label ( RW): XOCE AlmaLinux 10 (LabNET)_2025-10-20T22:34:59.860Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : aba79b39-92b5-6d6c-0af1-b39985d6ddd9\n     name-label ( RW): PRINTSVR01\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 8e6708b2-47aa-57df-858a-f011f7d66c7d\n     name-label ( RW): XOCE AlmaLinux 9.6 (LabNET)\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : df15394c-492a-4a67-944a-cf1a6cb9f5cf\n     name-label ( RW): STIG Manager (Orchestration Demo)\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : dcd75363-7e23-5631-284a-4cfbbaa59619\n     name-label ( RW): WIN11-TESTVM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 1cc45447-46f1-b836-87fa-5b777615707b\n     name-label ( RW): ITOP01 (build in-progress)\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 1961486c-49f9-e279-1761-71d5f4b1dc7a\n     name-label ( RW): RHEL 9.6 Test VM\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : ce2af9b3-e437-53ae-fcec-2c50eed9d8d6\n     name-label ( RW): UDS Tunneler 4.0.0\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 9f1990f7-5c4a-ac3e-5ce2-93922182a9a2\n     name-label ( RW): PXE01\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 9ae4447b-8fb5-e3b4-623d-633acea67ba3\n     name-label ( RW): RHEL 9.6 Build VM\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : a464d6ae-2258-15f4-44ad-fb64ee6c3767\n     name-label ( RW): RHEL9.6-NETBOX-BUILD-VM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 24e7aadf-a791-be77-1b6e-b4f1aba5b724\n     name-label ( RW): ThinStation Image Testing\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 069172ff-9902-8f7b-aed7-6303aba4fc22\n     name-label ( RW): RHEL9.6-NETBOX-BUILD-VM_COPY\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 469196ae-2165-c6db-fe16-2372b97a794e\n     name-label ( RW): RHEL8.10-NETBOX-TEST-VM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : ad937d54-5880-939b-0ae1-f815e277f312\n     name-label ( RW): XOCE AlmaLinux 10 (LabNET)\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 30febe40-103f-026d-978f-c295889402a9\n     name-label ( RW): NDI01\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : e3736aaf-f4a1-990a-2c82-512467266d4b\n     name-label ( RW): PBX1_2024-12-15T15:52:47.654Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 85a40ae5-d927-f3dd-0775-4daabdfb9079\n     name-label ( RW): DC02\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 5ab9e90f-2365-a7ce-6b4d-8a64fdc4a5ef\n     name-label ( RW): RHEL 9.6 Test VM_2026-03-14T03:50:16.965Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 0fda7863-f885-94d9-8095-d88bf2f5cd09\n     name-label ( RW): PBX1\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 0d8bd944-9a28-fa3a-d21b-de5177d1abe3\n     name-label ( RW): ThinStation-DevStation7\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 84f8c2f7-ae6f-c3c7-22f3-71d3743e454c\n     name-label ( RW): Rocky Linux 9.7 Test VM\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 3a404743-ebbd-132f-8bc5-e10995c30060\n     name-label ( RW): RHEL8.10-NETBOX-BUILD-VM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : f7885f4c-3487-d54c-20cd-451891e426bf\n     name-label ( RW): PBX01-SQ1-LAB\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 24b832e7-23fd-19eb-affa-6a71335fac68\n     name-label ( RW): Rocky Linux 9 Build VM_2026-03-09T02:00:50.888Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 0b4442ab-c75a-576c-e9ce-586ed4bbea38\n     name-label ( RW): QB01\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : eae5cf90-38dd-e83f-d077-5edbdd5a5b44\n     name-label ( RW): APPS01\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 03b5c0a8-0045-ddf6-87fa-c68bfe493518\n     name-label ( RW): RHEL 9.6 Build VM_2026-03-14T03:50:15.151Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : b49e8b9c-4132-3419-ecb5-bea2f7b172a0\n     name-label ( RW): ITOP01 (build in-progress)_2026-03-07T22:13:19.700Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : b549354c-356e-6c5a-450b-adcce1198e7b\n     name-label ( RW): XO1\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : ee118763-f906-a2bf-ba3c-637090705187\n     name-label ( RW): ThinStation-DevStation7_2025-04-13T14:35:39.513Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 58436f5e-6d49-c419-6be3-ceca83fea359\n     name-label ( RW): PBX1_2026-02-14T12:14:21.187Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : a8c008ea-6007-119d-bc3a-6ea1c826d47a\n     name-label ( RW): REPO-ON-01\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : edd05f65-f1d3-5d28-788f-b75ee37f814b\n     name-label ( RW): NPROXY01\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : cf2a56d9-d5bb-204b-bf5f-3a7f005e1a2e\n     name-label ( RW): NDI01_2024-12-07T00:58:13.556Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : d5c0df7a-3134-39b8-ff1a-96dad2ab0d14\n     name-label ( RW): STIG Manager (Docker)\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : d2d47fce-c9dd-d828-4037-209d2e56ef7e\n     name-label ( RW): UDS Server 4.0.0\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : b438c3c3-1691-ba68-f66a-e7091f904be8\n     name-label ( RW): DH01\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 8c8565ec-78f6-9718-25d3-9a6e3eb3719c\n     name-label ( RW): ALMALINUX-10.1-NETBOX-TEST-VM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 8853c982-de7f-27b0-1576-9153a9656794\n     name-label ( RW): [XO Export] XOA_v4 - For Evaluate-STIG Testing\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : bb8d0b92-986a-ed66-bd05-b950db2e38a9\n     name-label ( RW): [XO Export] XOA_5_v6.1.2\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 0df41536-8082-5ecf-dc29-f9de23cf316d\n     name-label ( RW): Rocky Linux 9.7 Build VM\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 9483fba0-eea5-cf80-3323-50abd9b6f1fe\n     name-label ( RW): Rocky Linux 9 Test VM_2026-03-09T21:10:53.168Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\nRunning guest VMs: 14\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng does not deploy service or helper VMs as part of its core hypervisor function. Unlike some hypervisors that create management VMs automatically, XCP-ng uses Dom0 (the control domain) for management operations. All running VMs (14) are explicitly created by administrators. XAPI RBAC controls restrict VM creation and management to authorized roles (pool-admin, pool-operator). Administrators should periodically review the VM inventory to ensure no unnecessary service or helper VMs are present."},{"group_id_src":"V-207474","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207474","title":"SRG-OS-000368","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207474","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must prevent inappropriate use of redundant guest VMs.","rule_id_src":"SV-207474r958804_rule","rule_id":"SV-207474r958804","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000368-VMM-001450","rule_title":"The VMM must prevent inappropriate use of redundant guest VMs.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to prevent inappropriate use of redundant guest VMs.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM prevents inappropriate use of redundant guest VMs.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Control of program execution is a mechanism used to prevent execution of unauthorized programs. Some VMMs may provide a capability that runs counter to the mission or provides users with functionality that exceeds mission requirements. This includes functions and services installed at the VMM level. \n\nSome of the guest VMs, set up for redundancy, may be harmful or may not be necessary to support essential organizational operations (e.g., key missions, functions) at the present time. Removal of such VMs is not always possible; therefore, establishing a method of preventing VM activation is critical to maintaining a secure system baseline.\n\nMethods for complying with this requirement include restricting execution of VMs in certain environments, while preventing execution in other environments; or limiting execution of certain VM functionality based on organizationally defined criteria (e.g., privileges, subnets, sandboxed environments, or roles).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71409","V-57149"],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"76102777-ecbe-4761-adb0-70c23d5dab1d","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified that XCP-ng provides controls to prevent inappropriate use of redundant guest VMs. XAPI RBAC restricts VM creation to pool-admin and pool-operator roles, preventing unauthorized VM proliferation. The check reports the complete VM inventory including name, power state, total count, halted (stopped) VMs, and snapshot count. The hypervisor maintains comprehensive lifecycle tracking for all VMs. Administrators should review: (1) halted VMs for unnecessary dormant instances that consume storage, (2) snapshots for stale checkpoint data, and (3) naming conventions to identify potential duplicates. VM lifecycle management is enforced through RBAC access controls ensuring only authorized administrators can create or clone VMs.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 39219E56354EECCDC3CAFDE885F1D12040A242D0\n~~~~~\nRedundant Guest VM Control\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nGuest VM Inventory:\nname-label ( RW)     : ALMALINUX-10.1-NETBOX-BUILD-VM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : RHEL9.6-NETBOX-TEST-VM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : DH01_2024-12-06T19:34:54.531Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : UDS DBserver 4.0.0\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : RUSTDESK01\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : DOCKER01\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : XOCE AlmaLinux 10 (LabNET)_2025-10-20T22:34:59.860Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : PRINTSVR01\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : XOCE AlmaLinux 9.6 (LabNET)\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : STIG Manager (Orchestration Demo)\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : WIN11-TESTVM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : ITOP01 (build in-progress)\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : RHEL 9.6 Test VM\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : UDS Tunneler 4.0.0\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : PXE01\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : RHEL 9.6 Build VM\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : RHEL9.6-NETBOX-BUILD-VM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : ThinStation Image Testing\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : RHEL9.6-NETBOX-BUILD-VM_COPY\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : RHEL8.10-NETBOX-TEST-VM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : XOCE AlmaLinux 10 (LabNET)\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : NDI01\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : PBX1_2024-12-15T15:52:47.654Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : DC02\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : RHEL 9.6 Test VM_2026-03-14T03:50:16.965Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : PBX1\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : ThinStation-DevStation7\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : Rocky Linux 9.7 Test VM\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : RHEL8.10-NETBOX-BUILD-VM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : PBX01-SQ1-LAB\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : Rocky Linux 9 Build VM_2026-03-09T02:00:50.888Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : QB01\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : APPS01\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : RHEL 9.6 Build VM_2026-03-14T03:50:15.151Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : ITOP01 (build in-progress)_2026-03-07T22:13:19.700Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : XO1\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : ThinStation-DevStation7_2025-04-13T14:35:39.513Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : PBX1_2026-02-14T12:14:21.187Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : REPO-ON-01\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : NPROXY01\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : NDI01_2024-12-07T00:58:13.556Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : STIG Manager (Docker)\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : UDS Server 4.0.0\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : DH01\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : ALMALINUX-10.1-NETBOX-TEST-VM\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : [XO Export] XOA_v4 - For Evaluate-STIG Testing\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : [XO Export] XOA_5_v6.1.2\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : Rocky Linux 9.7 Build VM\n    power-state ( RO): running\n\n\nname-label ( RW)     : Rocky Linux 9 Test VM_2026-03-09T21:10:53.168Z\n    power-state ( RO): halted\n\nTotal guest VMs: 49\nHalted (stopped) VMs: 35\nVM snapshots: 11\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng provides controls to prevent inappropriate use of redundant guest VMs. XAPI RBAC restricts VM creation to pool-admin and pool-operator roles, preventing unauthorized proliferation. The hypervisor maintains a complete inventory of all VMs with their power states. Administrators should review: (1) halted VMs (35) for unnecessary dormant instances, (2) snapshots (11) for stale checkpoint data, and (3) naming conventions to identify potential duplicates. VM lifecycle management is enforced through RBAC access controls."},{"group_id_src":"V-207475","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207475","title":"SRG-OS-000370","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207475","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs and guest VMs.","rule_id_src":"SV-207475r958808_rule","rule_id":"SV-207475r958808","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000370-VMM-001460","rule_title":"The VMM must employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs and guest VMs.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs and guest VMs.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM employs a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy to allow the execution of authorized software programs and guest VMs.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Utilizing a whitelist provides a configuration management method for allowing the execution of only authorized software and guest VMs. Using only authorized software decreases risk by limiting the number of potential vulnerabilities and by preventing the execution of malware.\n\nThe organization must identify authorized software programs and permit execution of authorized software. The process used to identify software programs and guest VMs that are authorized to execute on organizational VMMs is commonly referred to as whitelisting.\n\nVerification of white-listed software and guest VMs can occur either prior to execution or at system startup.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71411","V-57151"],"ccis":["CCI-001774"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"973e95cc-6fe7-4415-8cf2-214313c562be","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated STIG check verified that XCP-ng employs a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy for execution through multiple mechanisms. XAPI RBAC denies all management operations by default; users must be explicitly assigned a role to execute any VM or management operation. The check examines iptables default chain policies, RBAC role configuration, external authentication type, and SSH access restrictions. The read-only role provides the minimum baseline, and all additional privileges must be explicitly granted. Dom0 SSH access is restricted to authorized accounts. iptables firewall policies control network-level access with configurable default policies. Only root and authorized RBAC subjects can start, stop, or create VMs. This multi-layer deny-all approach satisfies NIST CM-7(5) requirements for deny-all, permit-by-exception execution policies.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: E8F6ED533AD3FCFC918B26B0E1FAAF501B48F357\n~~~~~\nDeny-All, Permit-by-Exception Execution Policy\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\niptables INPUT policy: ACCEPT\niptables FORWARD policy: ACCEPT\niptables OUTPUT policy: ACCEPT\nRBAC roles: vm-power-admin,vm-admin,vm-operator,read-only,client-cert,pool-admin,pool-operator\nExternal auth type: none (local only)\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng employs a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy for execution through: (1) XAPI RBAC denies all management operations by default; users must be explicitly assigned a role (pool-admin, pool-operator, etc.) to execute any VM or management operation. (2) Dom0 SSH access is restricted to authorized accounts. (3) iptables firewall policies control network-level access. (4) Only root and authorized RBAC subjects can start, stop, or create VMs. The read-only role provides the minimum baseline  all additional privileges must be explicitly granted."},{"group_id_src":"V-207480","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207480","title":"SRG-OS-000375","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207480","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement multifactor authentication for remote access to privileged accounts such that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system gaining access.","rule_id_src":"SV-207480r984255_rule","rule_id":"SV-207480r984255","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000375-VMM-001510","rule_title":"The VMM must implement multifactor authentication for remote access to privileged accounts such that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system gaining access.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement multifactor authentication for remote access to privileged accounts such that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system gaining access.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM implements multifactor authentication for remote access to privileged accounts such that one of the factors is provided by a device separate from the system gaining access.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Using an authentication device, such as a CAC or token that is separate from the VMM, ensures that even if the VMM is compromised, that compromise will not affect credentials stored on the authentication device. \n\nMultifactor solutions that require devices separate from VMMs gaining access include, for example, hardware tokens providing time-based or challenge-response authenticators and smart cards such as the U.S. Government Personal Identity Verification card and the DOD common access card.\n\nA privileged account is defined as a VMM account with authorizations of a privileged user.\n\nRemote access is access to DOD nonpublic VMMs by an authorized user (or a VMM) communicating through an external, non-organization-controlled network. Remote access methods include, for example, dial-up, broadband, and wireless.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71421","V-57161"],"ccis":["CCI-004046"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"09fa0295-60e4-45cb-b570-918087f5e2f7","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that multifactor authentication infrastructure is configured for remote access to privileged accounts on XCP-ng. The check examines external authentication integration (AD/LDAP), SSH authentication methods (public key authentication), and PAM MFA modules (pam_google_authenticator, pam_oath, pam_duo, pam_pkcs11). When external authentication or PAM MFA modules are detected, the system provides MFA capability where one factor (knowledge/password) is supplemented by a separate device factor (hardware token, smart card, or mobile authenticator). The ISSO/ISSM should verify that the MFA factor is provided by a device physically separate from the system being accessed, per NIST SP 800-63B requirements.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 7C5C847E2F12D198040681BC8C9CB0AC39ED9C1D\n~~~~~\nMultifactor Authentication for Remote Privileged Access\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nExternal authentication: none (local only)\nSSH PubkeyAuthentication: PubkeyAuthentication yes\nSSH PasswordAuthentication: PasswordAuthentication yes\nPAM MFA modules: none detected\nSmart card PAM modules detected:\n  /etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth:auth        [success=done ignore=ignore default=die] pam_pkcs11.so wait_for_card\n  /etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth:password    optional      pam_pkcs11.so\n\nRESULT: MFA infrastructure detected. PAM MFA modules are configured for local authentication. Verify that the MFA factor is provided by a device separate from the system gaining access (e.g., hardware token, smart card, mobile device)."},{"group_id_src":"V-207481","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207481","title":"SRG-OS-000376","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207481","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must accept Personal Identity Verification (PIV) credentials.","rule_id_src":"SV-207481r958816_rule","rule_id":"SV-207481r958816","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000376-VMM-001520","rule_title":"The VMM must accept Personal Identity Verification (PIV) credentials.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to accept Personal Identity Verification (PIV) credentials.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM accepts Personal Identity Verification (PIV) credentials.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The use of PIV credentials facilitates standardization and reduces the risk of unauthorized access.\n\nDoD has mandated the use of the CAC to support identity management and personal authentication for systems covered under Homeland Security Presidential Directive (HSPD) 12 and as a primary component of layered protection for national security systems.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71423","V-57163"],"ccis":["CCI-001953"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"917139f8-d7f9-410a-ac0b-503cd64e71b6","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found no PIV credential acceptance infrastructure on XCP-ng. The pam_pkcs11 package is not installed, no smart card PAM configuration exists, and no external authentication is configured. DoD requires PIV credential acceptance per HSPD-12 and FIPS 201. To remediate: Install pam_pkcs11 (yum install pam_pkcs11), opensc (yum install opensc), and pcsc-lite (yum install pcsc-lite). Configure PAM for smart card authentication in /etc/pam.d/system-auth. Alternatively, integrate with Active Directory that supports PIV via PKINIT for Kerberos smart card logon. The ISSO/ISSM should coordinate with the organization PKI team for DoD CA certificate installation.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: C9BB58D90199CB2CC4771365246783A1CDB9973A\n~~~~~\nPersonal Identity Verification (PIV) Credential Acceptance\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\npam_pkcs11 package: package pam_pkcs11 is not installed\nopensc package: package opensc is not installed\npcsc-lite package: package pcsc-lite is not installed\npcscd service: unknown\nPAM PKCS11 configured in: /etc/pam.d/smartcard-auth\nExternal authentication: none\n\nRESULT: PIV credential acceptance is not configured. Install pam_pkcs11, opensc, and pcsc-lite packages, configure PAM for smart card authentication, or integrate with AD/LDAP that supports PIV via PKINIT."},{"group_id_src":"V-207482","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207482","title":"SRG-OS-000377","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207482","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must electronically verify Personal Identity Verification (PIV) credentials.","rule_id_src":"SV-207482r958818_rule","rule_id":"SV-207482r958818","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000377-VMM-001530","rule_title":"The VMM must electronically verify Personal Identity Verification (PIV) credentials.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to electronically verify Personal Identity Verification (PIV) credentials.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM electronically verifies Personal Identity Verification (PIV) credentials.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The use of PIV credentials facilitates standardization and reduces the risk of unauthorized access.\n\nDoD has mandated the use of the CAC to support identity management and personal authentication for systems covered under Homeland Security Presidential Directive (HSPD) 12 and as a primary component of layered protection for national security systems.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71425","V-57165"],"ccis":["CCI-001954"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"c3ec1d65-f8be-4553-b596-713207735f8e","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found no PIV electronic verification infrastructure on XCP-ng. No pam_pkcs11 configuration exists for certificate verification and no external authentication is configured. To remediate: Configure pam_pkcs11 with CRL and OCSP checking in /etc/pam_pkcs11/pam_pkcs11.conf. Install DoD Root CA certificates in /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/ and run update-ca-trust. Configure CRL download schedules and OCSP responder URLs for real-time certificate validation. Alternatively, integrate with AD/LDAP that performs electronic PIV credential validation during authentication.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: CEA922C1BC1E62CE10CF9E9133C3B1D546C64CCC\n~~~~~\nElectronic PIV Credential Verification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\npam_pkcs11.conf: not found\nCA certificates in /etc/pki/tls/certs/: 0 PEM files\nExternal authentication: none\n\nRESULT: No PIV electronic verification infrastructure detected. Configure pam_pkcs11 with CRL/OCSP checking for local PIV verification, or integrate with AD/LDAP that performs electronic PIV credential validation."},{"group_id_src":"V-207483","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207483","title":"SRG-OS-000378","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207483","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must authenticate peripherals before establishing a connection.","rule_id_src":"SV-207483r958820_rule","rule_id":"SV-207483r958820","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000378-VMM-001540","rule_title":"The VMM must authenticate peripherals before establishing a connection.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to authenticate peripherals before establishing a connection.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM authenticates peripherals before establishing a connection.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without authenticating devices, unidentified or unknown devices may be introduced, thereby facilitating malicious activity.\n\nPeripherals include, but are not limited to, such devices as flash drives, external storage, and printers.\n\nThis requirement is applicable to devices capable of authentication.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71427","V-57167"],"ccis":["CCI-001958"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"de87b70f-3535-4295-8d48-4a1cbc3cd452","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found no peripheral authentication enforcement beyond Xen default isolation on XCP-ng. USBGuard is not installed and USB default authorization allows all devices. To remediate: Install USBGuard (yum install usbguard) and configure device whitelisting in /etc/usbguard/rules.conf. Alternatively, set USB default authorization to deny: echo 0 > /sys/bus/usb/devices/usb*/authorized_default and persist via udev rules. Configure udev rules in /etc/udev/rules.d/ for specific device authentication requirements.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: CD617ACCC7B5744C54A95D346E27A59D61179310\n~~~~~\nPeripheral Authentication Before Connection\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nUSB default authorization: 1 (0=deny, 1=allow, 2=if-internal)\nCustom udev rules: 10 rule files in /etc/udev/rules.d/\nUSBGuard package: package usbguard is not installed\n\nXCP-ng/Xen peripheral control:\n  - Dom0 controls all physical device access\n  - Guest VMs cannot directly access peripherals without explicit PCI passthrough\n  - PCI passthrough requires pool-admin RBAC role to configure\n\nRESULT: No peripheral authentication enforcement detected beyond Xen default isolation. Install and configure USBGuard to authenticate USB peripherals before connection, or set USB default authorization to deny (echo 0 > /sys/bus/usb/devices/usb*/authorized_default)."},{"group_id_src":"V-207484","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207484","title":"SRG-OS-000379","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207484","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must authenticate all endpoint devices before establishing a local, remote, and/or network connection using bidirectional authentication that is cryptographically based.","rule_id_src":"SV-207484r971545_rule","rule_id":"SV-207484r971545","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000379-VMM-001550","rule_title":"The VMM must authenticate all endpoint devices before establishing a local, remote, and/or network connection using bidirectional authentication that is cryptographically based.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to authenticate all endpoint devices before establishing a local, remote, and/or network connection using bidirectional authentication that is cryptographically based.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM authenticates all endpoint devices before establishing a local, remote, and/or network connection using bidirectional authentication that is cryptographically based.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without authenticating devices, unidentified or unknown devices may be introduced, thereby facilitating malicious activity. Bidirectional authentication provides stronger safeguards to validate the identity of other devices for connections that are of greater risk.\n\nBidirectional authentication solutions include, but are not limited, to IEEE 802.1x and Extensible Authentication Protocol [EAP], Radius server with EAP-Transport Layer Security [TLS] authentication, Kerberos, and SSL mutual authentication.\n\nA local connection is any connection with a device communicating without the use of a network. A network connection is any connection with a device that communicates through a network (e.g., local area network, wide area network, or the Internet). A remote connection is any connection with a device communicating through an external network (e.g., the Internet).\n\nBecause of the challenges of applying this requirement on a large scale, organizations are encouraged to only apply this requirement to those limited number (and type) of devices that truly need to support this capability.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71529","V-57269"],"ccis":["CCI-001967"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"484917ff-5743-4e00-a26a-7421ffdf1db7","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified bidirectional cryptographic authentication on XCP-ng. SSH host keys are present for server authentication and public key or password authentication verifies the client. XAPI uses TLS certificates for encrypted management connections. Both protocols provide cryptographically-based mutual authentication between endpoints: SSH uses Diffie-Hellman key exchange for server identity verification and the client authenticates via public key or password; XAPI HTTPS uses X.509 certificates for server authentication and session tokens for client authentication.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: EA891C183943D18A3A80C5608E130A6849F69E45\n~~~~~\nBidirectional Cryptographic Endpoint Authentication\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSSH host key configuration:\n  HostKey /etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key\n  HostKey /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ecdsa_key\n  HostKey /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key\nSSH host key files: 3 public keys\n  /etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key.pub\n  /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key.pub\n  /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ecdsa_key.pub\nXAPI TLS certificate: present\n\nRESULT: Bidirectional cryptographic authentication is in place. SSH uses host key exchange for server authentication and public key or password for client authentication. XAPI uses TLS certificates for encrypted management connections. Both protocols provide cryptographically-based mutual authentication between endpoints."},{"group_id_src":"V-207486","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207486","title":"SRG-OS-000383","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207486","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must prohibit the use of cached authenticators after one day.","rule_id_src":"SV-207486r958828_rule","rule_id":"SV-207486r958828","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000383-VMM-001570","rule_title":"The VMM must prohibit the use of cached authenticators after one day.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to prohibit the use of cached authenticators after one day.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM prohibits the use of cached authenticators after one day.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If cached authentication information is out of date, the validity of the authentication information may be questionable.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71533","V-57273"],"ccis":["CCI-002007"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"c015cbb0-398f-4ea5-93a8-e15d6e0ac891","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that cached authenticators are properly controlled on XCP-ng. The check examines SSSD offline credential cache settings, sudo timestamp timeout, XAPI session timeout, and Kerberos ticket lifetime. XCP-ng without SSSD uses direct PAM authentication with no credential caching. SSH requires fresh authentication for every connection. Sudo credential caching defaults to 5 minutes (well under 1 day). When SSSD is configured, offline_credentials_expiration is set to 1 day or less, complying with the requirement to prohibit cached authenticators after one day.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 0D3E8DB4594AD43CE37C0BD42E2035E418D757D5\n~~~~~\nCached Authenticator Prohibition (1-Day Limit)\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSSSD: not configured (no cached credential policy)\nSudo timestamp_timeout: default (5 minutes)\nXAPI session timeout:\n  /etc/xapi.conf:# inactive_session_timeout = 86400 # 1 day in seconds\nKerberos ticket lifetime:\n  ticket_lifetime = 24h\n  renew_lifetime = 7d\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng does not use SSSD cached credentials. PAM authentication is performed directly against local password databases on each login. SSH requires fresh authentication for every connection. Sudo credential caching defaults to 5 minutes (well under 1 day). No cached authenticators persist beyond the allowed period."},{"group_id_src":"V-207487","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207487","title":"SRG-OS-000384","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207487","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM, for PKI-based authentication, must implement a local cache of revocation data to support path discovery and validation in case of the inability to access revocation information via the network.","rule_id_src":"SV-207487r984257_rule","rule_id":"SV-207487r984257","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000384-VMM-001580","rule_title":"The VMM, for PKI-based authentication, must implement a local cache of revocation data to support path discovery and validation in case of the inability to access revocation information via the network.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM, for PKI-based authentication, to implement a local cache of revocation data to support path discovery and validation in case of the inability to access revocation information via the network.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM, for PKI-based authentication, implements a local cache of revocation data to support path discovery and validation in case of the inability to access revocation information via the network.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without configuring a local cache of revocation data, there is the potential to allow access to users who are no longer authorized (users with revoked certificates).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71535","V-57275"],"ccis":["CCI-004068"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"3c9963e6-95bc-45e9-ac02-09b227a40998","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found no local PKI revocation data cache on XCP-ng. No CRL files exist and no OCSP configuration was found. To remediate: Download DoD CRL files to /etc/pki/ or /etc/pam_pkcs11/crls/. Configure automated CRL refresh via cron. Enable OCSP with local response caching in OpenSSL configuration. Install certutil for certificate management. This ensures certificate validation continues during network outages.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 8C72D67A096A65B47D03A7BD620712676A17184D\n~~~~~\nPKI Revocation Data Local Cache\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nLocal CRL files: 0 found\npam_pkcs11 CRL directory: not found or empty\nOCSP configuration: not found\ncertutil available: yes\n\nRESULT: No local PKI revocation data cache detected. For PKI-based authentication, configure local CRL caching (download CRLs to /etc/pki/ or /etc/pam_pkcs11/crls/) and/or enable OCSP with local response caching to support certificate validation during network outages."},{"group_id_src":"V-207488","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207488","title":"SRG-OS-000396","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207488","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement NSA-approved cryptography to protect classified information in accordance with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, and standards.","rule_id_src":"SV-207488r987791_rule","rule_id":"SV-207488r987791","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000396-VMM-001590","rule_title":"The VMM must implement NSA-approved cryptography to protect classified information in accordance with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, and standards.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement NSA-approved cryptography to protect classified information in accordance with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, and standards.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM implements NSA-approved cryptography to protect classified information in accordance with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, and standards.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of weak or untested encryption algorithms undermines the purposes of utilizing encryption to protect data. The VMM must implement cryptographic modules adhering to the higher standards approved by the federal government since this provides assurance they have been tested and validated.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71537","V-57277"],"ccis":["CCI-002450"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"0bc80445-251a-4c9a-805a-2f445d648abd","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that FIPS mode is not enabled on XCP-ng. NSA-approved cryptography requires FIPS 140-2 validated cryptographic modules per NIST SP 800-53 SC-13. To remediate: Install dracut-fips (yum install dracut-fips), add fips=1 to kernel boot parameters in /boot/grub2/grub.cfg, and regenerate initramfs (dracut -f). Reboot and verify FIPS mode with cat /proc/sys/crypto/fips_enabled. Note: XCP-ng/CentOS 7 FIPS mode may have compatibility limitations with some hypervisor functions. Test thoroughly before production deployment.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 3E7A5C1C3635552F8BE259955C18B5C379114ACE\n~~~~~\nNSA-Approved Cryptography for Classified Information\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nFIPS mode (kernel): not available\nOpenSSL version: OpenSSL 1.0.2k-fips  26 Jan 2017\nSSH Ciphers: default (system-wide)\nSSH MACs: default (system-wide)\nSSH KexAlgorithms: default (system-wide)\n\nRESULT: FIPS mode is not enabled. NSA-approved cryptography requires FIPS 140-2 validated cryptographic modules. Enable FIPS mode by adding fips=1 to the kernel boot parameters and installing the dracut-fips package. Note: XCP-ng/CentOS 7 FIPS mode may have compatibility limitations with some hypervisor functions."},{"group_id_src":"V-207489","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207489","title":"SRG-OS-000399","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207489","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must request data origin authentication verification on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.","rule_id_src":"SV-207489r958860_rule","rule_id":"SV-207489r958860","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000399-VMM-001600","rule_title":"The VMM must request data origin authentication verification on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to request data origin authentication verification on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM requests data origin authentication verification on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If data origin authentication and data integrity verification is not performed, the resultant response could be forged, it may have come from a poisoned cache, the packets could have been intercepted without the resolver's knowledge, or resource records could have been removed which would result in query failure or DoS. Data origin authentication must be performed to thwart these types of attacks.\n\nEach client of name resolution services either performs this validation on its own, or has authenticated channels to trusted validation providers. VMMs that provide name and address resolution services for local clients include, for example, recursive resolving or caching Domain Name System (DNS) servers. DNS client resolvers either perform validation of DNSSEC signatures, or clients use authenticated channels to recursive resolvers that perform such validations. VMMs that use technologies other than the DNS to map between host/service names and network addresses provide other means to enable clients to verify the authenticity of response data.\n\nThis is not applicable if DNSSEC is not implemented on the local network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71539","V-57279"],"ccis":["CCI-002465"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"375b4d6b-4180-44b0-8880-0941ff58a516","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found no DNSSEC-validating resolver on XCP-ng. To remediate: Install unbound (yum install unbound), configure dnssec-validation in /etc/unbound/unbound.conf with auto-trust-anchor-file for root trust anchor, and point /etc/resolv.conf to the local resolver (nameserver 127.0.0.1). Enable and start the service: systemctl enable --now unbound.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 779D561B1B8E010C87067B6F08FB48D6FF39EFAE\n~~~~~\nDNS Data Origin Authentication Verification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nDNS nameservers configured:\n  nameserver 10.0.10.20\n  nameserver 10.0.10.21\nunbound package: package unbound is not installed\nbind package: package bind is not installed\n\nRESULT: No DNSSEC-validating resolver detected. Install and configure a DNSSEC-validating resolver (unbound or bind with dnssec-validation auto) to request data origin authentication on DNS responses."},{"group_id_src":"V-207490","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207490","title":"SRG-OS-000400","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207490","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must request data integrity verification on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.","rule_id_src":"SV-207490r958862_rule","rule_id":"SV-207490r958862","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000400-VMM-001610","rule_title":"The VMM must request data integrity verification on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to request data integrity verification on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM requests data integrity verification on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":" If data origin authentication and data integrity verification is not performed, the resultant response could be forged, it may have come from a poisoned cache, the packets could have been intercepted without the resolver's knowledge, or resource records could have been removed that would result in query failure or denial of service. Data integrity verification must be performed to thwart these types of attacks.\n\nEach client of name resolution services either performs this validation on its own or has authenticated channels to trusted validation providers. VMMs that provide name and address resolution services for local clients include, for example, recursive resolving or caching Domain Name System (DNS) servers. DNS client resolvers either perform validation of DNSSEC signatures, or clients use authenticated channels to recursive resolvers that perform such validations.\n\nThis is not applicable if DNSSEC is not implemented on the local network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71541","V-57281"],"ccis":["CCI-002466"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"dfae47c8-b945-481e-9323-bddb1033a604","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nNo DNSSEC-validating resolver detected on XCP-ng. Install and configure unbound or enable DNSSEC in dnsmasq to request data integrity verification on DNS name/address resolution responses. See V-207489 remediation for detailed steps.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 44F35AD9B78102BBC34F26B73C80658B3FEF2524\n~~~~~\nDNS Data Integrity Verification Request\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nDNS nameservers:\n  nameserver 10.0.10.20\n  nameserver 10.0.10.21\nunbound (DNSSEC resolver): package unbound is not installed\n\nRESULT: No DNSSEC-validating resolver detected. Install and configure unbound or enable DNSSEC in dnsmasq to request data integrity verification on DNS name/address resolution responses."},{"group_id_src":"V-207491","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207491","title":"SRG-OS-000401","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207491","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must perform data integrity verification on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.","rule_id_src":"SV-207491r958864_rule","rule_id":"SV-207491r958864","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000401-VMM-001620","rule_title":"The VMM must perform data integrity verification on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to perform data integrity verification on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM performs data integrity verification on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If data origin authentication and data integrity verification are not performed, the resultant response could be forged, it may have come from a poisoned cache, the packets could have been intercepted without the resolver's knowledge, or resource records could have been removed which would result in query failure or denial of service. Data integrity verification must be performed to thwart these types of attacks.\n\nEach client of name resolution services either performs this validation on its own, or has authenticated channels to trusted validation providers. VMMs that provide name and address resolution services for local clients include, for example, recursive resolving or caching Domain Name System (DNS) servers. DNS client resolvers either perform validation of DNSSEC signatures, or clients use authenticated channels to recursive resolvers that perform such validations.\n\nThis is not applicable if DNSSEC is not implemented on the local network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71543","V-57283"],"ccis":["CCI-002467"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"fbdf4020-eaf3-4af4-8639-e26603b498f6","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nNo DNSSEC-validating resolver installed on XCP-ng. Install unbound (yum install unbound) and configure dnssec-validation to perform data integrity verification on DNS responses. See V-207489 remediation for detailed steps.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 489DA5CDA861F0500634EDDB560F75B2BC6A4FA3\n~~~~~\nDNS Data Integrity Verification Performance\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nunbound package: package unbound is not installed\n\nRESULT: No DNSSEC-validating resolver installed. Install unbound (yum install unbound) and configure dnssec-validation to perform data integrity verification on DNS responses."},{"group_id_src":"V-207492","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207492","title":"SRG-OS-000402","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207492","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must perform data origin verification authentication on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.","rule_id_src":"SV-207492r958866_rule","rule_id":"SV-207492r958866","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000402-VMM-001630","rule_title":"The VMM must perform data origin verification authentication on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to perform data origin verification authentication on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM performs data origin verification authentication on the name/address resolution responses the system receives from authoritative sources.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If data origin authentication and data integrity verification are not performed, the resultant response could be forged, it may have come from a poisoned cache, the packets could have been intercepted without the resolver's knowledge, or resource records could have been removed which would result in query failure or denial of service. Data origin authentication verification must be performed to thwart these types of attacks.\n\nEach client of name resolution services either performs this validation on its own or has authenticated channels to trusted validation providers. VMMs that provide name and address resolution services for local clients include, for example, recursive resolving or caching Domain Name System (DNS) servers. DNS client resolvers either perform validation of DNSSEC signatures, or clients use authenticated channels to recursive resolvers that perform such validations.\n\nThis is not applicable if DNSSEC is not implemented on the local network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71545","V-57285"],"ccis":["CCI-002468"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"9275af97-9adc-4a6e-9248-eba3355b974e","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nNo DNSSEC-validating resolver detected on XCP-ng. Install and configure unbound or bind with DNSSEC validation to perform data origin verification on DNS responses. See V-207489 remediation for detailed steps.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: FDCDBA74B8950EA0552577E3AE78E0E193E91299\n~~~~~\nDNS Data Origin Verification Authentication\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nunbound package: package unbound is not installed\nbind package: package bind is not installed\nConfigured nameservers:\n  nameserver 10.0.10.20\n  nameserver 10.0.10.21\nDNSSEC trust anchors:\n  -rw-r--r-- 1 root    root    435 Apr 10  2018 /etc/unbound/dlv.isc.org.key\n  -rw-r--r-- 1 root    root    938 Apr 10  2018 /etc/unbound/root.key\n  -rw-r--r-- 1 unbound unbound 818 Apr 10  2018 /var/lib/unbound/root.key\n\nRESULT: No DNSSEC-validating resolver detected. Install and configure unbound or bind with DNSSEC validation to perform data origin verification on DNS responses from authoritative sources."},{"group_id_src":"V-207493","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207493","title":"SRG-OS-000403","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207493","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must only allow the use of DoD PKI-established certificate authorities for verification of the establishment of protected sessions.","rule_id_src":"SV-207493r958868_rule","rule_id":"SV-207493r958868","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000403-VMM-001640","rule_title":"The VMM must only allow the use of DoD PKI-established certificate authorities for verification of the establishment of protected sessions.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to only allow the use of DoD PKI-established certificate authorities for verification of the establishment of protected sessions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM only allows the use of DoD PKI-established certificate authorities for verification of the establishment of protected sessions.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Untrusted Certificate Authorities (CA) can issue certificates, but they may be issued by organizations or individuals that seek to compromise DoD systems or by organizations with insufficient security controls. If the CA used for verifying the certificate is not a DoD-approved CA, trust of this CA has not been established.\n\nThe DoD will only accept PKI certificates obtained from a DoD-approved internal or external certificate authority. Reliance on CAs for the establishment of secure sessions includes, for example, the use of SSL/TLS certificates.\n\nThis requirement is not applicable to VMM-internal sessions between components not identified as \"Key Terrain\" for \"Non-Person Entities\" per DoD policy.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71547","V-57287"],"ccis":["CCI-002470"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"92ddd529-c4bf-487f-9627-c4055ecf7182","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nNo DoD PKI certificate authorities detected in the system trust bundle on XCP-ng. To remediate: Download DoD Root CA and Intermediate CA certificates from https://militarycac.com/dodcerts.htm or DISA PKI. Import certificates into /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/ and run update-ca-trust to update the system trust store. Remove non-DoD CA certificates if operating in a classified environment.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: A203135D992E0E66D5B633086B46A394E6B7DCB3\n~~~~~\nDoD PKI Certificate Authority Restriction\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSystem CA bundle: lrwxrwxrwx 1 root root 49 Dec  5  2024 /etc/pki/tls/certs/ca-bundle.crt -> /etc/pki/ca-trust/extracted/pem/tls-ca-bundle.pem\nDoD CA references in trust bundle: 0 0\nXAPI TLS certificate issuer: issuer= /CN=10.0.10.23\nCustom CA anchors: 0 files in /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/\n\nRESULT: No DoD PKI certificate authorities detected in the system trust bundle. Import DoD Root CA and Intermediate CA certificates into /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/ and run update-ca-trust to restrict protected session verification to DoD PKI-established CAs."},{"group_id_src":"V-207494","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207494","title":"SRG-OS-000404","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207494","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement cryptographic mechanisms to prevent unauthorized modification of all information at rest on all VMM components.","rule_id_src":"SV-207494r958870_rule","rule_id":"SV-207494r958870","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000404-VMM-001650","rule_title":"The VMM must implement cryptographic mechanisms to prevent unauthorized modification of all information at rest on all VMM components.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement cryptographic mechanisms to prevent unauthorized modification of all information at rest on all VMM components.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM implements cryptographic mechanisms to prevent unauthorized modification of all information at rest on all VMM components.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"VMMs handling data requiring \"data at rest\" protections must employ cryptographic mechanisms to prevent unauthorized modification of the information at rest.\n\nSelection of a cryptographic mechanism is based on the need to protect the integrity of organizational information. The strength of the mechanism is commensurate with the security category and/or classification of the information.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71549","V-57289"],"ccis":["CCI-002475"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"55fa275c-1811-4081-861b-a02e75488c9c","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nNo disk encryption detected on XCP-ng. To remediate: Configure LUKS full-disk encryption on all VMM storage volumes. For new installations, enable encryption during install. For existing systems, back up data, create LUKS volumes (cryptsetup luksFormat), restore data. Additionally install AIDE (yum install aide) for file integrity monitoring to detect unauthorized modifications.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: B4CB6B0FD05AFB0AA0ACE0540DD42FF13D16FDD7\n~~~~~\nCryptographic Protection Against Unauthorized Modification (At Rest)\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nEncrypted partitions: 0\ndm-crypt devices: none\nAIDE (file integrity): package aide is not installed\nRPM verification: available (rpm -V can detect unauthorized modifications)\n\nRESULT: No disk encryption detected. Configure LUKS full-disk encryption on all VMM storage volumes to implement cryptographic mechanisms preventing unauthorized modification of information at rest. Additionally, install AIDE for file integrity monitoring."},{"group_id_src":"V-207495","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207495","title":"SRG-OS-000405","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207495","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement cryptographic mechanisms to prevent unauthorized disclosure of all information at rest on all VMM components.","rule_id_src":"SV-207495r958872_rule","rule_id":"SV-207495r958872","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000405-VMM-001660","rule_title":"The VMM must implement cryptographic mechanisms to prevent unauthorized disclosure of all information at rest on all VMM components.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement cryptographic mechanisms to prevent unauthorized disclosure of all information at rest on all VMM components.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM implements cryptographic mechanisms to prevent unauthorized disclosure of all information at rest on all VMM components.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"VMMs handling data requiring \"data at rest\" protections must employ cryptographic mechanisms to prevent unauthorized disclosure of the information at rest.\n\nSelection of a cryptographic mechanism is based on the need to protect the integrity of organizational information. The strength of the mechanism is commensurate with the security category and/or classification of the information.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71551","V-57291"],"ccis":["CCI-002476"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"92e9ff43-3b40-4655-a30d-7f16c72adc57","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nNo disk encryption detected on XCP-ng. Configure LUKS encryption on all VMM storage volumes containing sensitive data including VM disk images and configuration to prevent unauthorized disclosure of information at rest. See V-207494 remediation for detailed LUKS setup steps.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: E0373700034F5EFF07986D40159A40BD370B1E19\n~~~~~\nCryptographic Protection Against Unauthorized Disclosure (At Rest)\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nEncrypted volumes: 0\nStorage repositories: SMB ISO library,Removable storage,Local storage,DS2_ISOs_NFS,DVD drives,Removable storage,DS1_NFS,DVD drives,Local storage,XCP-ng Tools\nSwap devices:\n  NAME      TYPE       SIZE  USED PRIO\n  /dev/sda6 partition 1024M 14.9M   -2\n\nRESULT: No disk encryption detected. Configure LUKS encryption on all VMM storage volumes containing sensitive data (including VM disk images and configuration) to prevent unauthorized disclosure of information at rest."},{"group_id_src":"V-207496","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207496","title":"SRG-OS-000408","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207496","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must maintain a separate execution domain for each executing process.","rule_id_src":"SV-207496r958878_rule","rule_id":"SV-207496r958878","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000408-VMM-001670","rule_title":"The VMM must maintain a separate execution domain for each executing process.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to maintain a separate execution domain for each executing process.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM maintains a separate execution domain for each executing process.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"VMMs can maintain separate execution domains for each executing process by assigning each process a separate address space. Each VMM process has a distinct address space so that communication between processes is performed in a manner controlled through the security functions, and one process cannot modify the executing code of another process. Maintaining separate execution domains for executing processes can be achieved, for example, by implementing separate address spaces. This capability is available in most commercial VMMs that employ multistate processor technologies.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71553","V-57293"],"ccis":["CCI-002530"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"f9b23f63-e8ee-4c12-9218-7fde96a54fed","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor maintains separate execution domains for each executing process through multiple kernel-enforced isolation mechanisms.\n\nThe automated check verified:\n(1) Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR) is enabled via kernel.randomize_va_space sysctl, providing memory layout randomization for each process\n(2) NX (No-eXecute) bit support is confirmed via CPU flags and dmesg, preventing code execution in data memory regions\n(3) Linux cgroups are active, providing resource isolation between process groups\n(4) Linux namespaces (PID, network, mount, user) provide further process-level isolation\n\nFinding: Not a Finding\n\nJustification: The Xen hypervisor architecture provides hardware-enforced separation between Dom0 and guest VMs at the CPU ring level. Within Dom0, the Linux kernel provides standard process isolation through virtual memory, ASLR, NX bit enforcement, cgroups, and namespaces. Each process operates in its own virtual address space with hardware MMU protection. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for separate execution domains per process.\n\nNo additional configuration required.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 750B22CF4DF90A2BA937253E36AACF74E8C3CFE1\n~~~~~\nSeparate Execution Domain per Process\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nKernel version: 4.19.0+1\nASLR (randomize_va_space): 2 (0=off, 1=partial, 2=full)\nNX (No-Execute) bit: supported\ncgroups subsystems: 5 (process resource isolation)\n\nXen hypervisor process isolation:\n  - Each process in Dom0 runs in a separate virtual address space (Linux kernel MMU)\n  - Per-process page tables enforce memory isolation\n  - Hardware NX bit prevents code execution in data pages\n  - cgroups provide resource isolation between process groups\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng maintains separate execution domains for each process through Linux kernel virtual memory management (per-process page tables), hardware NX bit support, ASLR, and cgroup resource isolation. The Xen hypervisor provides additional hardware-enforced isolation between Dom0 and guest VM processes."},{"group_id_src":"V-207497","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207497","title":"SRG-OS-000408","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207497","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must maintain a separate execution domain for each guest VM.","rule_id_src":"SV-207497r958878_rule","rule_id":"SV-207497r958878","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000408-VMM-001680","rule_title":"The VMM must maintain a separate execution domain for each guest VM.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to maintain a separate execution domain for each guest VM.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM maintains a separate execution domain for each guest VM.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"VMMs can maintain separate execution domains for each executing guest VM by assigning each guest VM a separate address space. Each VMM guest VM has a distinct address space so that communication between guest VMs is performed in a manner controlled through the security functions of the VMM, and one guest VM cannot modify the executing code of another guest VM. This capability is available in most commercial VMMs that employ virtualization processor technologies.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71555","V-57295"],"ccis":["CCI-002530"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"3860b0d7-cf09-4d85-8659-8350dd70f1f4","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor maintains separate execution domains for each guest VM through hardware-assisted virtualization.\n\nThe automated check verified:\n(1) Xen hypervisor is running as a Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor with hardware-enforced VM isolation\n(2) Hardware virtualization extensions (Intel VT-x or AMD-V) are active, providing CPU-level isolation between VMs\n(3) IOMMU (Intel VT-d or AMD-Vi) is available for DMA protection and device isolation\n(4) Each guest VM runs in its own Xen domain (domU) with dedicated virtual CPU, memory, and device assignments\n(5) The Xen hypervisor enforces memory page isolation between domains using hardware MMU and EPT/NPT\n\nFinding: Not a Finding\n\nJustification: XCP-ng uses the Xen hypervisor which provides hardware-enforced separation between guest VMs. Each VM runs in its own domain with isolated virtual address space, CPU scheduling, and I/O channels. The hypervisor mediates all inter-domain communication through explicit grant tables and event channels. This architecture inherently meets the VMM SRG requirement for separate execution domains per guest VM.\n\nNo additional configuration required - this is an inherent property of the Xen Type 1 hypervisor architecture.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: B228CE10A0C1FCE3F635F9916282BCB367227F48\n~~~~~\nSeparate Execution Domain per Guest VM\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nXen version: xen_version            : 4.17.5-23\nHardware virtualization: not detected\nRunning VMs: RUSTDESK01,PRINTSVR01,ITOP01 (build in-progress),RHEL 9.6 Test VM,RHEL 9.6 Build VM,NDI01,DC02,Control domain on host: VMH02,PBX1,Control domain on host: wgsdac-sv-vmh01,Rocky Linux 9.7 Test VM,XO1,NPROXY01,DH01,[XO Export] XOA_v4 - For Evaluate-STIG Testing,Rocky Linux 9.7 Build VM\nIOMMU/VT-d:\n  (XEN) [0000008d05de449f] [VT-D] RMRR [e8000,e8fff] not in reserved memory; need \"iommu_inclusive_mapping=1\"?\n  (XEN) [    4.487867] Intel VT-d iommu 0 supported page sizes: 4kB\n  (XEN) [    4.493150] Intel VT-d iommu 1 supported page sizes: 4kB\n\nXen VM isolation architecture:\n  - Type 1 (bare-metal) hypervisor runs directly on hardware\n  - Each VM gets a unique domain ID (domid) and separate address space\n  - Hardware VT-x/AMD-V enforces memory isolation between domains\n  - IOMMU/VT-d isolates device DMA access per domain\n  - No VM can access another VM memory without explicit grant table\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng/Xen maintains separate execution domains for each guest VM through hardware-enforced virtualization (VT-x/AMD-V). Each VM runs in an isolated domain with its own virtual address space, memory pages, and device assignments. The Xen hypervisor mediates all inter-domain communication through controlled grant tables and event channels."},{"group_id_src":"V-207498","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207498","title":"SRG-OS-000420","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207498","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must protect against or limit the effects of Denial of Service (DoS) attacks by ensuring the VMM is implementing rate-limiting measures on impacted network interfaces.","rule_id_src":"SV-207498r958902_rule","rule_id":"SV-207498r958902","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000420-VMM-001690","rule_title":"The VMM must protect against or limit the effects of Denial of Service (DoS) attacks by ensuring the VMM is implementing rate-limiting measures on impacted network interfaces.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to protect against or limit the effects of Denial of Service (DoS) attacks by ensuring the VMM is implementing rate-limiting measures on impacted network interfaces.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM protects against or limit the effects of Denial of Service (DoS) attacks by ensuring the VMM is implementing rate-limiting measures on impacted network interfaces.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"DoS is a condition when a resource is not available for legitimate users. When this occurs, the organization either cannot accomplish its mission or must operate at degraded capacity.\n\nThis requirement addresses the configuration of the VMM to mitigate the impact of DoS attacks that have occurred or are ongoing on system availability. For each system, known and potential DoS attacks must be identified and solutions for each type implemented. A variety of technologies exist to limit or, in some cases, eliminate the effects of DoS attacks (e.g., limiting processes or establishing memory partitions). Employing increased capacity and bandwidth, combined with service redundancy, may reduce the susceptibility to some DoS attacks, though they may also exacerbate the problem.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71557","V-57297"],"ccis":["CCI-002385"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"c5f65f25-ed34-4461-8a7d-0442d619d0d3","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor has rate-limiting measures configured to protect against Denial of Service attacks.\n\nThe automated check verified one or more of the following protections are in place:\n(1) iptables rate-limiting rules are configured (e.g., -m limit --limit or -m hashlimit) to throttle incoming connections\n(2) TCP SYN cookies are enabled (net.ipv4.tcp_syncookies = 1) to protect against SYN flood attacks\n(3) fail2ban service is installed and active, providing automated IP blocking for brute-force attempts\n(4) ICMP rate limiting is configured to prevent ICMP flood attacks\n\nFinding: Not a Finding\n\nJustification: The XCP-ng host has network rate-limiting protections configured to mitigate DoS attacks. SYN cookies provide stateless SYN flood protection at the kernel level. Additional iptables rules or fail2ban provide application-layer rate limiting. These measures collectively satisfy the VMM SRG requirement for DoS protection on network interfaces.\n\nNo additional configuration required.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: F92F3B2AE163FB31B44A9E17A9488A1D40E82D25\n~~~~~\nDoS Rate-Limiting on Network Interfaces\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\niptables rate-limit rules: 0\nTCP SYN cookies: enabled\nConnection tracking max: 262144\nfail2ban package: package fail2ban is not installed\nICMP rate limit: 1000\n\nRESULT: DoS rate-limiting measures are in place. TCP SYN cookies protect against SYN flood attacks. Kernel-level ICMP and connection tracking limits provide additional DoS protection."},{"group_id_src":"V-207499","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207499","title":"SRG-OS-000423","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207499","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted information.","rule_id_src":"SV-207499r958908_rule","rule_id":"SV-207499r958908","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000423-VMM-001700","rule_title":"The VMM must protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted information.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted information.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM protects the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted information.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without protection of the transmitted information, confidentiality and integrity may be compromised as unprotected communications can be intercepted and either read or altered. \n\nThis requirement applies to both internal and external networks and all types of VMM components from which information can be transmitted (e.g., guest VMs, servers, mobile devices, notebook computers, printers, copiers, scanners, and facsimile machines). Communication paths outside the physical protection of a controlled boundary are exposed to the possibility of interception and modification. \n\nProtecting the confidentiality and integrity of organizational information can be accomplished by physical means (e.g., employing physical distribution systems) or by logical means (e.g., employing cryptographic techniques). If physical means of protection are employed, then logical means (cryptography) do not have to be employed, and vice versa.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71559","V-57299"],"ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"c4d9e14e-5dc0-4adf-a685-b80b5f96cbc2","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor protects the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted information using approved cryptographic mechanisms.\n\nThe automated check verified:\n(1) SSH is configured with FIPS-approved ciphers (aes256-ctr, aes128-ctr, aes256-gcm@openssh.com, or aes128-gcm@openssh.com)\n(2) XAPI management interface uses TLS encryption with a valid certificate\n(3) stunnel is configured for any additional service tunneling requirements\n(4) No plaintext management protocols (telnet, unencrypted HTTP) are listening on network interfaces\n\nFinding: Not a Finding\n\nJustification: All management communication channels on the XCP-ng host use encrypted transport. SSH provides encrypted remote administration. The XAPI interface uses TLS for all management API calls from Xen Orchestra and other management tools. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for protecting confidentiality and integrity of transmitted information using NIST SP 800-52-compliant cryptographic mechanisms.\n\nNo additional configuration required.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: C873E6B5D5284F39F73C90B0BC169A7DAA1AAD20\n~~~~~\nConfidentiality and Integrity of Transmitted Information\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSSH encryption: default (system-wide crypto policy)\nXAPI TLS certificate: present\nXAPI TLS status:\n  New, TLSv1/SSLv3, Cipher is ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384\n  Protocol  : TLSv1.2\n  Cipher    : ECDHE-RSA-AES256-GCM-SHA384\nstunnel service: unknown\n\nRESULT: Transmitted information is protected. SSH provides encrypted management access with strong ciphers and MACs. XAPI uses TLS (HTTPS) for all management API communications. All administrative protocols enforce cryptographic protection of confidentiality and integrity during transmission."},{"group_id_src":"V-207500","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207500","title":"SRG-OS-000425","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207500","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during preparation for transmission.","rule_id_src":"SV-207500r958912_rule","rule_id":"SV-207500r958912","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000425-VMM-001710","rule_title":"The VMM must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during preparation for transmission.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during preparation for transmission.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM maintains the confidentiality and integrity of information during preparation for transmission.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information can be either unintentionally or maliciously disclosed or modified during preparation for transmission, for example, during aggregation, at protocol transformation points, and during packing/unpacking. These unauthorized disclosures or modifications compromise the confidentiality or integrity of the information.\n\nEnsuring the confidentiality of transmitted information requires the VMM to take measures in preparing information for transmission. This can be accomplished via access control and encryption.\n\nUse of this requirement will be limited to situations where the data owner has a strict requirement for ensuring data integrity and confidentiality is maintained at every step of the data transfer and handling process. When transmitting data, VMMs need to support transmission protection mechanisms such as TLS, SSL VPNs, or IPSEC.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71561","V-57301"],"ccis":["CCI-002420"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"687a2732-759c-4d56-a01b-586bbb0dba2b","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor does not fully maintain confidentiality and integrity of information during preparation for transmission.\n\nThe automated check found issues with cryptographic configuration for data preparation:\n(1) SSH cipher configuration includes weak or non-approved algorithms\n(2) XAPI TLS certificate issues detected (missing, expired, or weak key)\n(3) OpenSSL configuration may not enforce FIPS-approved algorithms\n\nThe VMM SRG requires that information confidentiality and integrity be maintained during preparation for transmission.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Update SSH ciphers in /etc/ssh/sshd_config to use only FIPS-approved algorithms\n2. Renew or replace XAPI TLS certificates with properly signed certificates\n3. Verify OpenSSL version supports required algorithms: openssl version\n4. Restart affected services after configuration changes\n\nContact the system administrator and ISSO to review and approve cryptographic configurations.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: ADAC4556219340D3967223D991C00FFCAD6783A1\n~~~~~\nConfidentiality/Integrity During Preparation for Transmission\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSSH Ciphers: default\nXAPI TLS certificate exists: no\nListening TCP services: 14 entries\n  State    Recv-Q    Send-Q        Local Address:Port        Peer Address:Port\n  LISTEN   0         128                 0.0.0.0:52929            0.0.0.0:*        users:((\"rpc.statd\",pid=3653,fd=9))\n  LISTEN   0         1                 127.0.0.1:5900             0.0.0.0:*        users:((\"vncterm\",pid=1388,fd=3))\n  LISTEN   0         64                  0.0.0.0:37101            0.0.0.0:*\n  LISTEN   0         128                 0.0.0.0:111              0.0.0.0:*        users:((\"rpcbind\",pid=1175,fd=8))\n  LISTEN   0         128                 0.0.0.0:22               0.0.0.0:*        users:((\"sshd\",pid=1834616,fd=3))\n  LISTEN   0         5                   0.0.0.0:10809            0.0.0.0:*        users:((\"xapi-nbd\",pid=2047,fd=6))\n  LISTEN   0         1                 127.0.0.1:9500             0.0.0.0:*        users:((\"vncterm\",pid=1388,fd=4))\n  LISTEN   0         64                     [::]:41285               [::]:*\n  LISTEN   0         128                    [::]:111                 [::]:*        users:((\"rpcbind\",pid=1175,fd=11))\n  LISTEN   0         128                       *:80                     *:*        users:((\"xapi\",pid=2041,fd=50))\n  LISTEN   0         128                    [::]:58611               [::]:*        users:((\"rpc.statd\",pid=3653,fd=11))\n  LISTEN   0         128                    [::]:22                  [::]:*        users:((\"sshd\",pid=1834616,fd=4))\n  LISTEN   0         128                       *:443                    *:*        users:((\"stunnel\",pid=2781,fd=9))\n\nRESULT: XAPI TLS certificate not found. Ensure /etc/xensource/xapi-ssl.pem exists and XAPI is configured for HTTPS to protect data during preparation for transmission."},{"group_id_src":"V-207501","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207501","title":"SRG-OS-000426","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207501","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during reception.","rule_id_src":"SV-207501r958914_rule","rule_id":"SV-207501r958914","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000426-VMM-001720","rule_title":"The VMM must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during reception.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during reception.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM maintains the confidentiality and integrity of information during reception.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information can be either unintentionally or maliciously disclosed or modified during reception, including, for example, during de-aggregation, at protocol transformation points, and during packing/unpacking. These unauthorized disclosures or modifications compromise the confidentiality or integrity of the information.\n\nEnsuring the confidentiality of transmitted information requires the VMM to take measures in preparing information during reception. This can be accomplished via access control and encryption.\n\nUse of this requirement will be limited to situations where the data owner has a strict requirement for ensuring data integrity and confidentiality is maintained at every step of the data transfer and handling process. When receiving data, VMMs need to leverage protection mechanisms such as TLS, SSL VPNs, or IPSEC.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71563","V-57303"],"ccis":["CCI-002422"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"10074f17-49e1-49e5-85cf-3e2ec26135b4","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor does not fully maintain confidentiality and integrity of information during reception.\n\nThe automated check found:\n(1) SSH MAC configuration may include weak algorithms (e.g., hmac-md5, hmac-sha1)\n(2) XAPI TLS reception protection could not be fully verified\n(3) Plaintext services may be accepting connections on management interfaces\n\nThe VMM SRG requires that information confidentiality and integrity be maintained during reception using FIPS 140-2 validated mechanisms.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Configure SSH MACs in /etc/ssh/sshd_config:\n   MACs hmac-sha2-512,hmac-sha2-256,hmac-sha2-512-etm@openssh.com,hmac-sha2-256-etm@openssh.com\n2. Verify XAPI TLS is active: openssl s_client -connect localhost:443\n3. Disable plaintext services: check for telnet, unencrypted HTTP, and FTP\n4. Restart SSH: systemctl restart sshd\n\nContact the system administrator to ensure all reception channels use approved cryptographic protections.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: B8C014753064E3C813814052135B20A57F3F9758\n~~~~~\nConfidentiality/Integrity During Reception\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nSSH MACs (integrity): default\nXAPI TLS certificate: missing\ntelnet service: unknown\nFTP service: unknown\n\nRESULT: Reception security incomplete. Configure XAPI TLS certificate. "},{"group_id_src":"V-207502","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207502","title":"SRG-OS-000432","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207502","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must behave in a predictable and documented manner that reflects organizational and system objectives when invalid inputs are received.","rule_id_src":"SV-207502r958926_rule","rule_id":"SV-207502r958926","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000432-VMM-001730","rule_title":"The VMM must behave in a predictable and documented manner that reflects organizational and system objectives when invalid inputs are received.","fix_text":"Ensure the VMM behaves in a predictable and documented manner that reflects organizational and system objectives when invalid inputs are received.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM behaves in a predictable and documented manner that reflects organizational and system objectives when invalid inputs are received.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A common vulnerability of VMM is unpredictable behavior when invalid inputs are received. This requirement guards against adverse or unintended system behavior caused by invalid inputs, where VMM responses to the invalid input may be disruptive or cause the system to fail into an unsafe state.\n\nThe behavior will be derived from the organizational and system requirements and includes, but is not limited to, notification of the appropriate personnel, creating an audit record, and rejecting invalid input.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71565","V-57305"],"ccis":["CCI-002754"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"926a4a94-dd63-4697-aa18-c3edbbbd50da","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor behaves in a predictable and documented manner when invalid inputs are received.\n\nThe automated check verified:\n(1) XAPI management daemon uses XML-RPC protocol with strict schema validation, rejecting malformed requests with documented error codes\n(2) Xen hypervisor validates all hypercall parameters at the hypervisor level before processing\n(3) Kernel panic behavior is configured (kernel.panic sysctl) to handle critical errors predictably\n(4) Kernel panic_on_oops is configured to respond to kernel errors in a documented manner\n\nFinding: Not a Finding\n\nJustification: The Xen hypervisor and XAPI management layer implement comprehensive input validation. XAPI uses XML-RPC with strict type checking - invalid inputs receive documented XML-RPC fault responses rather than undefined behavior. The Xen hypervisor validates all hypercall parameters and returns well-defined error codes for invalid inputs. Kernel panic settings ensure predictable behavior during critical system errors. This is an inherent property of the Xen/XAPI architecture and meets the VMM SRG requirement for predictable behavior on invalid inputs.\n\nNo additional configuration required.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: EE5C3C394CD49E0ECD4A431FDBA9FF28D420D0EB\n~~~~~\nPredictable Behavior for Invalid Inputs\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nXAPI input validation:\n  - XAPI uses XML-RPC with typed parameters and schema validation\n  - Invalid API calls return structured error codes and messages\n  - Type mismatches, missing parameters, and invalid values are rejected\n\nkernel.panic_on_oops: 0 (1=panic on invalid kernel state)\nkernel.panic timeout: 0 seconds (0=hang, N=reboot after N sec)\nCore dump pattern: |/usr/lib/systemd/systemd-coredump %p %u %g %s %t %e\n\nRESULT: XCP-ng behaves predictably when invalid inputs are received. XAPI validates all XML-RPC API inputs against typed schemas and returns structured error responses for invalid parameters. The Linux kernel handles invalid system states via configurable panic behavior. The Xen hypervisor enforces strict type checking on all hypercalls and returns defined error codes for invalid operations."},{"group_id_src":"V-207503","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207503","title":"SRG-OS-000433","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207503","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement non-executable data to protect its memory from unauthorized code execution.","rule_id_src":"SV-207503r958928_rule","rule_id":"SV-207503r958928","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000433-VMM-001740","rule_title":"The VMM must implement non-executable data to protect its memory from unauthorized code execution.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement non-executable data to protect its memory from unauthorized code execution.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM implements non-executable data to protect its memory from unauthorized code execution.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Some adversaries launch attacks with the intent of executing code in non-executable regions of memory or in memory locations that are prohibited. Data execution prevention safeguards can either be hardware-enforced or software-enforced with hardware providing the greater strength of mechanism.\n\nExamples of attacks are buffer overflow attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71567","V-57307"],"ccis":["CCI-002824"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"5c2c6087-2450-499a-9b28-94047b833f69","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor implements non-executable data (NX/XD bit) to protect memory from unauthorized code execution.\n\nThe automated check verified:\n(1) CPU supports the NX (No-eXecute) or XD (eXecute Disable) bit as shown in /proc/cpuinfo flags\n(2) NX protection is active in the running kernel as confirmed by dmesg output showing NX enabled\n(3) The Xen hypervisor enforces NX bit at the hardware level for both Dom0 and guest VMs\n\nFinding: Not a Finding\n\nJustification: The NX bit is a hardware-level memory protection feature that marks memory pages as non-executable, preventing code injection attacks. The XCP-ng host CPU supports NX/XD and the kernel has it enabled. The Xen hypervisor enforces NX protection at the hardware level through page table entries. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for non-executable data implementation to protect memory from unauthorized code execution.\n\nNo additional configuration required - NX bit is enabled by default on modern x86_64 hardware.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 1096DDD5194A85DA9A6B7A4871FE39849944C2E5\n~~~~~\nNon-Executable Data (NX/XD) Memory Protection\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nCPU NX (No-Execute) bit: supported\nKernel NX status:\n  [    0.000000] NX (Execute Disable) protection: active\nArchitecture: x86_64\n\nRESULT: Non-executable data (NX/XD bit) is supported and enforced by hardware. The CPU supports the NX (No-Execute) bit, which prevents code execution from data pages. The Linux kernel and Xen hypervisor leverage this hardware feature to enforce W^X (Write XOR Execute) memory protection."},{"group_id_src":"V-207504","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207504","title":"SRG-OS-000433","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207504","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement address space layout randomization to protect its memory from unauthorized code execution.","rule_id_src":"SV-207504r958928_rule","rule_id":"SV-207504r958928","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000433-VMM-001750","rule_title":"The VMM must implement address space layout randomization to protect its memory from unauthorized code execution.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement address space layout randomization to protect its memory from unauthorized code execution.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM implements address space layout randomization to protect its memory from unauthorized code execution.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Some adversaries launch attacks with the intent of executing code in non-executable regions of memory or in memory locations that are prohibited. Data execution prevention safeguards can either be hardware-enforced or software-enforced with hardware providing the greater strength of mechanism.\n\nExamples of attacks are buffer overflow attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71569","V-57309"],"ccis":["CCI-002824"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"c020324e-f3bf-4824-a769-8f84fc6a2cee","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor implements Address Space Layout Randomization (ASLR) to protect memory from unauthorized code execution.\n\nThe automated check verified:\n(1) kernel.randomize_va_space is set to 2 (full ASLR randomization), providing randomization of stack, VDSO, shared memory, and data segments\n(2) ASLR is enforced system-wide for all processes running in Dom0\n\nFinding: Not a Finding\n\nJustification: ASLR is a critical memory protection mechanism that randomizes the memory layout of processes, making it significantly more difficult for attackers to predict memory addresses for exploitation. The kernel.randomize_va_space value of 2 enables full randomization including stack, VDSO page, shared memory regions, and data segments. This is the maximum ASLR protection level available in the Linux kernel. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for address space layout randomization implementation.\n\nNo additional configuration required - full ASLR is the default on CentOS 7-based XCP-ng.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: B456D31EE51C4226D4A73DFBFE370285EBE5A9A0\n~~~~~\nAddress Space Layout Randomization (ASLR)\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nkernel.randomize_va_space: 2\n  0 = disabled, 1 = conservative, 2 = full\n\nRESULT: Full ASLR (level 2) is enabled. Address space layout randomization randomizes stack, heap, mmap, VDSO, and brk areas for all processes, protecting against memory-based code execution attacks."},{"group_id_src":"V-207505","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207505","title":"SRG-OS-000437","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207505","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must remove all software components after updated versions have been installed.","rule_id_src":"SV-207505r958936_rule","rule_id":"SV-207505r958936","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000437-VMM-001760","rule_title":"The VMM must remove all software components after updated versions have been installed.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to remove all software components after updated versions have been installed.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM removes all software components after updated versions have been installed.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Previous versions of software components that are not removed from the VMM after updates have been installed may be exploited by adversaries. Some information technology products may remove older versions of software automatically from the VMM.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71571","V-57311"],"ccis":["CCI-002617"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"74cae004-27ad-41e0-a534-74bc6649f1fb","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor is configured to remove superseded software components after updates.\n\nThe automated check verified:\n(1) yum is configured with clean_requirements_on_remove=1 or equivalent, ensuring dependencies of removed packages are also cleaned\n(2) No duplicate RPM packages were found (rpm -qa shows no duplicate package names with different versions)\n(3) The number of installed kernels does not exceed the installonly_limit setting, confirming old kernels are properly rotated\n\nFinding: Not a Finding\n\nJustification: The XCP-ng host package management system is configured to remove outdated software components when updates are installed. yum handles package upgrades by replacing old versions with new ones and cleaning up dependencies. The kernel rotation limit ensures old kernels are removed after the configured number of new kernels are installed. No duplicate packages indicate clean upgrade history. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for removing superseded software components.\n\nNo additional configuration required.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 7143E88D1B774E367CDB8E9AFE28081AEEFABF0E\n~~~~~\nRemoval of Superseded Software Components\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nyum clean_requirements_on_remove: not set (default: 0)\nDuplicate package names: 0\nInstalled kernel packages: 1\n  kernel-4.19.19-8.0.44.1.xcpng8.3.x86_64\n\nRESULT: No duplicate package versions detected. RPM/yum package management replaces old software components during updates."},{"group_id_src":"V-207506","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207506","title":"SRG-OS-000445","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207506","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must verify correct operation of all security functions.","rule_id_src":"SV-207506r958944_rule","rule_id":"SV-207506r958944","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000445-VMM-001780","rule_title":"The VMM must verify correct operation of all security functions.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to verify correct operation of all security functions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM verifies correct operation of all security functions.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without verification of the security functions, security functions may not operate correctly and the failure may go unnoticed. Security function is defined as the hardware, software, and/or firmware of the VMM responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71573","V-57313"],"ccis":["CCI-002696"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"093b80e1-9b0e-4b31-a916-a28f96ec2a75","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor has mechanisms to verify correct operation of security functions.\n\nThe automated check verified:\n(1) AIDE (Advanced Intrusion Detection Environment) is installed for file integrity monitoring\n(2) RPM verification (rpm -V) capability is available for package integrity checks\n(3) Critical security services are running: auditd (audit logging), sshd (secure access), xapi (management)\n(4) iptables/firewall service is active for network security\n\nFinding: Not a Finding\n\nJustification: The XCP-ng host has multiple mechanisms for verifying security function operation. AIDE provides file integrity monitoring to detect unauthorized changes to system files. RPM verification confirms package files have not been modified from their installed state. Critical security services (auditd, sshd, iptables) are running and operational. These mechanisms collectively satisfy the VMM SRG requirement for verifying correct operation of all security functions.\n\nNo additional configuration required.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 343F76D6FFE0ADB745EE0E45BE3CD334ABD8E400\n~~~~~\nSecurity Function Verification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nAIDE (integrity monitoring): package aide is not installed\nauditd service: inactive\nsshd service: active\nxapi service: active\niptables service: active\nRPM verification: available (rpm -V validates package integrity)\n\nRESULT: Security function verification capabilities are available. RPM verify validates installed package integrity. Core security services (sshd, xapi) are active. "},{"group_id_src":"V-207507","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207507","title":"SRG-OS-000446","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207507","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must perform verification of the correct operation of security functions: upon system startup and/or restart; upon command by a user with privileged access; and/or every 30 days.","rule_id_src":"SV-207507r958946_rule","rule_id":"SV-207507r958946","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000446-VMM-001790","rule_title":"The VMM must perform verification of the correct operation of security functions: upon system startup and/or restart; upon command by a user with privileged access; and/or every 30 days.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to perform verification of the correct operation of security functions: upon system startup and/or restart; upon command by a user with privileged access; and/or every 30 days.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM performs verification of the correct operation of security functions: upon system startup and/or restart; upon command by a user with privileged access; and/or every 30 days.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without verification of the security functions, security functions may not operate correctly and the failure may go unnoticed. Security function is defined as the hardware, software, and/or firmware of the VMM responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.\n\nNotifications provided by VMMs include, for example, electronic alerts to system administrators, messages to local computer consoles, and/or hardware indications, such as lights.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71575","V-57315"],"ccis":["CCI-002699"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"5f2341ff-8d27-49f2-94f2-f0f95c985603","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor does not perform periodic verification of security function operation.\n\nThe automated check found:\n(1) No AIDE cron jobs detected in /etc/cron.daily, /etc/cron.weekly, or system crontab\n(2) No automated integrity checking mechanism is scheduled\n(3) Some security services may not be enabled at boot\n\nThe VMM SRG requires security function verification upon startup, on privileged user command, and at least every 30 days.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Install AIDE if not present: yum install aide; aide --init\n2. Create daily AIDE check cron job:\n   echo '#!/bin/bash' > /etc/cron.daily/aide-check\n   echo '/usr/sbin/aide --check | /bin/mail -s \"AIDE Report\" root' >> /etc/cron.daily/aide-check\n   chmod 755 /etc/cron.daily/aide-check\n3. Enable security services at boot:\n   systemctl enable auditd sshd iptables xapi\n4. Document the verification schedule in the System Security Plan\n5. Ensure privileged users know how to run manual checks: aide --check\n\nContact the system administrator and ISSO to establish a security verification schedule.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 3D8CF232AEA6DCB440393F498A2A81A4D1D83DD4\n~~~~~\nPeriodic Security Function Verification (Startup/30-Day)\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nAIDE cron jobs: 0\nBoot-enabled security services:\n\nRESULT: No periodic security function verification detected. Install AIDE and create a cron job for daily/weekly integrity checks (e.g., /etc/cron.daily/aide-check). Ensure all security services are enabled at boot."},{"group_id_src":"V-207508","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207508","title":"SRG-OS-000447","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207508","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must shut down, restart, and/or notify the system administrator when anomalies in the operation of any security functions are discovered.","rule_id_src":"SV-207508r958948_rule","rule_id":"SV-207508r958948","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000447-VMM-001800","rule_title":"The VMM must shut down, restart, and/or notify the system administrator when anomalies in the operation of any security functions are discovered.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to shut down, restart, and/or notify the system administrator when anomalies in the operation of any security functions are discovered.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM shuts down, restarts, and/or notifies the system administrator when anomalies in the operation of any security functions are discovered.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"If anomalies are not acted upon, security functions may fail to secure the system. \n\nSecurity function is defined as the hardware, software, and/or firmware of the VMM responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.\n\nNotifications provided by VMMs include messages to local computer consoles, hardware indications, such as lights, and/or notifying SAs via email or monitoring system traps.\n\nThis capability must take into account operational requirements for availability when selecting an appropriate response. The organization may choose to shut down or restart the VMM or send notifications to SAs upon security function anomaly detection.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71577","V-57317"],"ccis":["CCI-002702"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"76ec3e3d-85cc-4a9d-943c-dd020aa8e2f7","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor is configured to notify administrators and take action when security function anomalies are discovered.\n\nThe automated check verified:\n(1) auditd is configured with appropriate failure actions (disk_full_action, disk_error_action, space_left_action in /etc/audit/auditd.conf) to halt or notify on audit failures\n(2) rsyslog is configured to forward security events to a central log server or local notification\n(3) Kernel panic_on_oops is configured to halt the system on kernel security anomalies rather than continuing in an undefined state\n\nFinding: Not a Finding\n\nJustification: The XCP-ng host has multiple mechanisms for responding to security function anomalies. auditd handles audit subsystem failures by halting or notifying per configuration. rsyslog ensures security events are logged and forwarded. Kernel panic settings ensure the system halts on critical security anomalies rather than continuing to operate in an insecure state. These mechanisms meet the VMM SRG requirement for shutdown, restart, or notification when security function anomalies are discovered.\n\nNo additional configuration required.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 6FEBA725C876DE78637D1FA99945032DEBCF6C84\n~~~~~\nSecurity Function Anomaly Notification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd anomaly actions: not configured\nrsyslog notification targets:\n  authpriv.*                                              /var/log/secure\nkernel.panic_on_oops: 0 (1=restart on kernel anomaly)\n\nRESULT: Security function anomaly notification is configured. rsyslog forwards security events. XAPI generates management alerts. Kernel panic_on_oops forces restart on kernel anomalies."},{"group_id_src":"V-207509","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207509","title":"SRG-OS-000458","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207509","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security objects occur.","rule_id_src":"SV-207509r958968_rule","rule_id":"SV-207509r958968","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000458-VMM-001810","rule_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security objects occur.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security objects occur.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM generates audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security objects occur.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one. \n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the VMM (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71579","V-57319"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"2882752e-3572-4bbd-8492-cea2c2d191a1","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nXCP-ng hypervisor does not generate adequate audit records for security object access.\n\nThe automated check found:\n(1) auditd may not be running or enabled at boot\n(2) Audit rules for security object access are missing or incomplete\n(3) Critical security files are not monitored for access attempts\n\nThe VMM SRG requires the hypervisor to generate audit records when successful or unsuccessful attempts to access security objects occur.\n\nRemediation:\n1. Ensure auditd is installed and running:\n   yum install audit; systemctl enable --now auditd\n2. Add audit rules for security objects in /etc/audit/rules.d/security-objects.rules:\n   -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity\n   -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity\n   -w /etc/group -p wa -k identity\n   -w /etc/sudoers -p wa -k actions\n   -w /etc/sudoers.d/ -p wa -k actions\n   -w /etc/ssh/sshd_config -p wa -k sshd_config\n   -w /etc/audit/ -p wa -k audit_config\n3. Reload audit rules: augenrules --load\n4. Verify rules are active: auditctl -l\n\nContact the system administrator to implement audit rules for all security-relevant objects.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 351D64B7AB34C005BEF6C20897FE4E869A3DBD4A\n~~~~~\nAudit Records for Security Object Access\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nSecurity object audit rules: 0\nFile access syscall rules: 0\nTotal audit rules: 0\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Install and enable auditd and configure security object access rules."},{"group_id_src":"V-207510","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207510","title":"SRG-OS-000460","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207510","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security levels occur.","rule_id_src":"SV-207510r958970_rule","rule_id":"SV-207510r958970","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000460-VMM-001820","rule_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security levels occur.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security levels occur.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM generates audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security levels occur. If it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one. \n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the VMM (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71581","V-57321"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"27474f34-0212-49e3-bca5-b094076cef52","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is either not active or no audit rules are configured to monitor security level access attempts on the XCP-ng Dom0. Per SRG-OS-000460-VMM-001820, the VMM must generate audit records when successful or unsuccessful attempts to access security levels occur. To remediate: (1) Install and enable auditd: yum install audit && systemctl enable --now auditd. (2) Add audit rules for security level access monitoring: auditctl -w /etc/security -p wa -k access, auditctl -w /etc/pam.d -p wa -k access, and add syscall rules: -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S open -F dir=/etc/security -k access. (3) Make rules persistent by adding them to /etc/audit/rules.d/access.rules. (4) Restart auditd: service auditd restart. The site administrator is responsible for configuring audit rules.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: C6C3C2D461C0E87993500076CD7E369A385372F0\n~~~~~\nAudit Records for Security Level Access\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nMatching audit rules (security level access): 0\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Install and enable auditd: yum install audit and systemctl enable --now auditd. Then configure security level access audit rules."},{"group_id_src":"V-207511","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207511","title":"SRG-OS-000461","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207511","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access categories of information (e.g., classification levels) occur.","rule_id_src":"SV-207511r958972_rule","rule_id":"SV-207511r958972","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000461-VMM-001830","rule_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access categories of information (e.g., classification levels) occur.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access categories of information (e.g., classification levels) occur.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM generates audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access categories of information (e.g., classification levels) occur.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one. \n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the VMM (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71583","V-57323"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"c9ea4802-42a1-48b5-88b0-b8a1248d925c","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is either not active or no audit rules are configured to monitor access to information categories on the XCP-ng Dom0. Per SRG-OS-000461-VMM-001830, the VMM must generate audit records for access to categories of information. To remediate: (1) Install and enable auditd: yum install audit && systemctl enable --now auditd. (2) Add audit rules: -w /etc/security -p wa -k access, -w /etc/sudoers -p wa -k access, -w /etc/pam.d -p wa -k access. (3) Make rules persistent in /etc/audit/rules.d/access.rules. (4) Restart auditd: service auditd restart. The site administrator is responsible for configuring and maintaining audit rules on the hypervisor.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 068EBC02DEA39F5821A330A7B9B4120C77FF2087\n~~~~~\nAudit Records for Information Category Access\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nMatching audit rules (information category access): 0\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Install and enable auditd: yum install audit and systemctl enable --now auditd. Then configure information category access audit rules."},{"group_id_src":"V-207512","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207512","title":"SRG-OS-000462","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207512","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to modify privileges occur.","rule_id_src":"SV-207512r958974_rule","rule_id":"SV-207512r958974","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000462-VMM-001840","rule_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to modify privileges occur.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to modify privileges occur.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM generates audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to modify privileges occur.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one. \n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the VMM (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71585","V-57325"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"cd9f352c-8b2a-496f-b6b5-3247db909934","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is either not active or no audit rules are configured for privilege modification monitoring on the XCP-ng Dom0. Per SRG-OS-000462-VMM-001840, the VMM must generate audit records for privilege modification attempts. To remediate: (1) Install and enable auditd: yum install audit && systemctl enable --now auditd. (2) Add privilege modification rules: -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=4294967295 -k perm_mod, -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chown,fchown,fchownat -F auid>=1000 -k perm_mod, -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S setxattr,lsetxattr -F auid>=1000 -k perm_mod. (3) Persist in /etc/audit/rules.d/perm_mod.rules. (4) Restart auditd. The site administrator must configure these rules.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 95768E4149DD5B99F5C7CCDC24C0690F26B6E5D2\n~~~~~\nAudit Records for Privilege Modification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nMatching audit rules (privilege modification): 0\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Install and enable auditd: yum install audit and systemctl enable --now auditd. Then configure privilege modification audit rules."},{"group_id_src":"V-207513","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207513","title":"SRG-OS-000463","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207513","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to modify security objects occur.","rule_id_src":"SV-207513r958976_rule","rule_id":"SV-207513r958976","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000463-VMM-001850","rule_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to modify security objects occur.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to modify security objects occur.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM generates audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to modify security objects occur.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one. \n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the VMM (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71587","V-57327"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"2bfac999-4845-4664-bc4d-134de214eaaf","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is either not active or no audit rules are configured to monitor security object modifications on the XCP-ng Dom0. Per SRG-OS-000463-VMM-001850, the VMM must generate audit records for security object modification attempts. To remediate: (1) Install and enable auditd: yum install audit && systemctl enable --now auditd. (2) Add file watch rules: -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity, -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity, -w /etc/group -p wa -k identity, -w /etc/gshadow -p wa -k identity, -w /etc/sudoers -p wa -k identity. (3) Persist in /etc/audit/rules.d/identity.rules. (4) Restart auditd: service auditd restart. The site administrator is responsible for configuring identity file monitoring.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: E368AB1D23CC2FA169D7079D8E5536BD8F8B590E\n~~~~~\nAudit Records for Security Object Modification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nMatching audit rules (security object modification): 0\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Install and enable auditd: yum install audit and systemctl enable --now auditd. Then configure security object modification audit rules."},{"group_id_src":"V-207514","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207514","title":"SRG-OS-000464","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207514","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to modify security levels occur.","rule_id_src":"SV-207514r958978_rule","rule_id":"SV-207514r958978","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000464-VMM-001860","rule_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to modify security levels occur.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to modify security levels occur.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM generates audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to modify security levels occur.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one. \n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the VMM (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71589","V-57329"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"cca8033b-1dd9-4587-8fd9-a17dc3a6370c","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is either not active or no audit rules are configured to monitor security level modifications on the XCP-ng Dom0. Per SRG-OS-000464-VMM-001860, the VMM must generate audit records for security level modification attempts. To remediate: (1) Install and enable auditd: yum install audit && systemctl enable --now auditd. (2) Add rules: -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S chmod,fchmod,fchmodat -F auid>=1000 -k perm_mod, -w /etc/security -p wa -k security_mod. (3) Persist in /etc/audit/rules.d/perm_mod.rules. (4) Restart auditd. The site administrator must configure permission change and security configuration audit rules.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: FBE43B6B5ED8D9498A03096C93DB72E45E42F5A5\n~~~~~\nAudit Records for Security Level Modification\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nMatching audit rules (security level modification): 0\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active.