it && systemctl enable --now auditd. (2) Add rules: -w /var/log/wtmp -p wa -k session, -w /var/run/utmp -p wa -k session, -w /var/log/btmp -p wa -k session. (3) Persist in /etc/audit/rules.d/session.rules. (4) Restart auditd. The site administrator must configure session tracking audit rules.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 91D48B6AD16126C519B0D90A24A03F264E79D2A7\n~~~~~\nAudit Records for User Access Start/End Time\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nMatching audit rules (user access session tracking): 0\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Install and enable auditd: yum install audit and systemctl enable --now auditd. Then configure session tracking audit rules."},{"group_id_src":"V-207521","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207521","title":"SRG-OS-000473","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207521","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when concurrent logons from different workstations occur.","rule_id_src":"SV-207521r958996_rule","rule_id":"SV-207521r958996","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000473-VMM-001930","rule_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when concurrent logons from different workstations occur.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to generate audit records when concurrent logons from different workstations occur.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM generates audit records when concurrent logons from different workstations occur.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one. \n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the VMM (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71603","V-57343"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"ee9f60d0-4f55-469d-bded-907bfe903c59","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is either not active or no audit rules are configured to track concurrent logons on the XCP-ng Dom0. Per SRG-OS-000473-VMM-001930, the VMM must generate audit records for concurrent logons. To remediate: (1) Install and enable auditd: yum install audit && systemctl enable --now auditd. (2) Add rules: -w /var/log/wtmp -p wa -k session, -w /var/run/utmp -p wa -k session, -w /var/log/lastlog -p wa -k logins. (3) Persist in /etc/audit/rules.d/session.rules. (4) Restart auditd. The site administrator must configure session tracking rules.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 046D00E96AD14E215BF4203F07F5BBC6E94ABBB2\n~~~~~\nAudit Records for Concurrent Logons\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nMatching audit rules (concurrent logon tracking): 0\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Install and enable auditd: yum install audit and systemctl enable --now auditd. Then configure session and logon tracking audit rules."},{"group_id_src":"V-207522","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207522","title":"SRG-OS-000474","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207522","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful accesses to objects occur.","rule_id_src":"SV-207522r958998_rule","rule_id":"SV-207522r958998","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000474-VMM-001940","rule_title":"The VMM must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful accesses to objects occur.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful accesses to objects occur.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM generates audit records when successful/unsuccessful accesses to objects occur.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one. \n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the VMM (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71605","V-57345"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"cc9fcd05-6293-429a-a15b-6d0cfcda8830","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is either not active or no audit rules are configured for object access monitoring on the XCP-ng Dom0. Per SRG-OS-000474-VMM-001940, the VMM must generate audit records for object access. To remediate: (1) Install and enable auditd: yum install audit && systemctl enable --now auditd. (2) Add rules: -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S open,openat,creat,truncate,ftruncate -F exit=-EACCES -F auid>=1000 -k access, -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S open,openat,creat,truncate,ftruncate -F exit=-EPERM -F auid>=1000 -k access. (3) Persist in /etc/audit/rules.d/access.rules. (4) Restart auditd. The site administrator must configure object access audit rules.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: E1F4DAE44A430997989A6BB0F72FA3331A8FBD0F\n~~~~~\nAudit Records for Object Access\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nMatching audit rules (object access): 0\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Install and enable auditd: yum install audit and systemctl enable --now auditd. Then configure object access audit rules."},{"group_id_src":"V-207523","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207523","title":"SRG-OS-000475","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207523","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must generate audit records for all direct access to the VMM.","rule_id_src":"SV-207523r959000_rule","rule_id":"SV-207523r959000","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000475-VMM-001950","rule_title":"The VMM must generate audit records for all direct access to the VMM.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to generate audit records for all direct access to the VMM.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM generates audit records for all direct access to the VMM.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one. \n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the VMM (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71607","V-57347"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"395e0ce0-3eca-4c39-966a-a95850cda609","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is either not active or no audit rules are configured for direct VMM access monitoring on the XCP-ng Dom0. Per SRG-OS-000475-VMM-001950, the VMM must generate audit records for all direct access. To remediate: (1) Install and enable auditd: yum install audit && systemctl enable --now auditd. (2) Add rules: -w /var/log/lastlog -p wa -k logins, -w /var/log/secure -p wa -k logins. (3) Ensure SSH LogLevel is INFO or higher in /etc/ssh/sshd_config. (4) Verify XAPI logs to /var/log/xensource.log (default on XCP-ng). (5) Persist rules in /etc/audit/rules.d/logins.rules. (6) Restart auditd. The site administrator must configure direct access audit rules.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: CA4F1BF025935DD92B84BB449B32AA43E6D036AB\n~~~~~\nAudit Records for Direct VMM Access\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nMatching audit rules (direct VMM access): 0\nSSH LogLevel: default (INFO)\nXAPI log (/var/log/xensource.log) exists: no\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Install and enable auditd: yum install audit and systemctl enable --now auditd. Then configure direct access tracking rules."},{"group_id_src":"V-207524","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207524","title":"SRG-OS-000476","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207524","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events.","rule_id_src":"SV-207524r959002_rule","rule_id":"SV-207524r959002","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000476-VMM-001960","rule_title":"The VMM must generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to generate audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM generates audit records for all account creations, modifications, disabling, and termination events.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one. \n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the VMM (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71609","V-57349"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"54889a9a-d5cf-4fd4-a3d7-7487cfd5fe4a","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is either not active or no audit rules are configured for account lifecycle monitoring on the XCP-ng Dom0. Per SRG-OS-000476-VMM-001960, the VMM must generate audit records for all account lifecycle events. To remediate: (1) Install and enable auditd: yum install audit && systemctl enable --now auditd. (2) Add rules: -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity, -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity, -w /etc/group -p wa -k identity, -w /usr/sbin/useradd -p x -k account, -w /usr/sbin/userdel -p x -k account, -w /usr/sbin/usermod -p x -k account, -w /usr/sbin/groupadd -p x -k account. (3) Persist in /etc/audit/rules.d/identity.rules. (4) Restart auditd. The site administrator must configure account lifecycle rules.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: CB5329421AE2DD89BB6A39E767D291FDB5CF666D\n~~~~~\nAudit Records for Account Lifecycle Events\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nMatching audit rules (account lifecycle): 0\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Install and enable auditd: yum install audit and systemctl enable --now auditd. Then configure account lifecycle audit rules."},{"group_id_src":"V-207525","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207525","title":"SRG-OS-000477","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207525","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must generate audit records for all module load, unload, and restart actions, and also for all program and guest VM initiations.","rule_id_src":"SV-207525r959004_rule","rule_id":"SV-207525r959004","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000477-VMM-001970","rule_title":"The VMM must generate audit records for all module load, unload, and restart actions, and also for all program and guest VM initiations.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to generate audit records for all module load, unload, and restart actions, and also for all program and guest VM initiations.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM generates audit records for all module load, unload, and restart actions, and also for all program and guest VM initiations.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident or identify those responsible for one. \n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the VMM (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71611","V-57351"],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"bf2f6c2d-5b5b-4285-b522-d82a054f21fc","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is either not active or no audit rules are configured for module and VM event monitoring on the XCP-ng Dom0. Per SRG-OS-000477-VMM-001970, the VMM must generate audit records for module load/unload and VM initiations. To remediate: (1) Install and enable auditd: yum install audit && systemctl enable --now auditd. (2) Add rules: -a always,exit -F arch=b64 -S init_module,delete_module,finit_module -k modules. (3) Verify Xen logs VM lifecycle events to /var/log/xensource.log (default on XCP-ng). (4) Persist rules in /etc/audit/rules.d/modules.rules. (5) Restart auditd. The site administrator must configure module and VM event audit rules.\n        \n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 6B16148B7740AEC80CAA68CF23BC836D8499558F\n~~~~~\nAudit Records for Module and VM Events\nXCP-ng Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n\nauditd service: inactive\nMatching audit rules (module and VM events): 0\nXen VM log (/var/log/xensource.log) exists: no\n\nRESULT: auditd is not active. Install and enable auditd: yum install audit and systemctl enable --now auditd. Then configure module and VM initiation audit rules."},{"group_id_src":"V-207526","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207526","title":"SRG-OS-000478","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207526","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement NIST FIPS-validated cryptography for the following: to provision digital signatures; to generate cryptographic hashes; and to protect unclassified information requiring confidentiality and cryptographic protection in accordance with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, and standards.","rule_id_src":"SV-207526r959006_rule","rule_id":"SV-207526r959006","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000478-VMM-001980","rule_title":"The VMM must implement NIST FIPS-validated cryptography for the following: to provision digital signatures; to generate cryptographic hashes; and to protect unclassified information requiring confidentiality and cryptographic protection in accordance with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, and standards.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement NIST FIPS-validated cryptography for the following: to provision digital signatures; to generate cryptographic hashes; and to protect unclassified information requiring confidentiality and cryptographic protection in accordance with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, and standards.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM implements NIST FIPS-validated cryptography for the following: to provision digital signatures; to generate cryptographic hashes; and to protect unclassified information requiring confidentiality and cryptographic protection in accordance with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, and standards.\r\n\r\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Use of weak or untested encryption algorithms undermines the purposes of utilizing encryption to protect data. The VMM must implement cryptographic modules adhering to the higher standards approved by the federal government since this provides assurance they have been tested and validated.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71613","V-57353"],"ccis":["CCI-002450"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"9c8065ea-1c54-4151-8e89-a40533a94771","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examined /proc/sys/crypto/fips_enabled and found FIPS mode is not enabled on the XCP-ng hypervisor. The VMM SRG requires NIST FIPS 140-2/140-3 validated cryptography for digital signatures, cryptographic hashes, and data protection. To remediate: (1) Install the dracut-fips package: yum install dracut-fips. (2) Regenerate the initramfs: dracut -f. (3) Add fips=1 to the kernel boot parameters in /boot/grub2/grub.cfg or via grubby: grubby --update-kernel=ALL --args=fips=1. (4) Reboot the system. (5) Verify with cat /proc/sys/crypto/fips_enabled (should return 1). Note: Enabling FIPS mode may impact XCP-ng hypervisor functionality. The system administrator should test in a non-production environment first and coordinate with Vates support. ISSO/ISSM must verify that FIPS-validated cryptography is required per the system security plan.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 814659FD22BA25AE5D1671E83B6F856E98130A6C\n~~~~~\nV-207526 - SRG-OS-000478-VMM-001980\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: FIPS Mode Status\n----------------------------------------\n  /proc/sys/crypto/fips_enabled: \n\nCheck 2: dracut-fips Package\n----------------------------------------\n  rpm -q dracut-fips: package dracut-fips is not installed\n\nCheck 3: SSH FIPS-Approved Ciphers\n----------------------------------------\n  sshd_config Ciphers: not configured\n\nRESULT: FAIL - FIPS mode is not enabled. /proc/sys/crypto/fips_enabled = \nFIPS 140-2/140-3 validated cryptography is required for DoD systems.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-207527","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207527","title":"SRG-OS-000479","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207527","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must, at a minimum, off-load interconnected systems in real time and off-load standalone systems weekly.","rule_id_src":"SV-207527r959008_rule","rule_id":"SV-207527r959008","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000479-VMM-001990","rule_title":"The VMM must, at a minimum, off-load interconnected systems in real time and off-load standalone systems weekly.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to, at a minimum, off-load interconnected systems in real time and off-load standalone systems weekly.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM, at a minimum, off-loads interconnected systems in real time and off-loads standalone systems weekly.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Information stored in one location is vulnerable to accidental or incidental deletion or alteration.\n\nOff-loading is a common process in VMMs with limited audit storage capacity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71615","V-57355"],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"6dd22bc2-2aec-45f6-b2a9-863c2257f089","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that audit log off-loading is not properly configured on the XCP-ng hypervisor. Either rsyslog is not active or no remote log forwarding targets are configured. The VMM SRG requires that interconnected systems off-load audit logs in real time and standalone systems off-load at minimum weekly. To remediate: (1) Ensure rsyslog is installed and running: systemctl enable rsyslog && systemctl start rsyslog. (2) Configure remote forwarding in /etc/rsyslog.conf or create a file in /etc/rsyslog.d/: *.* @@syslog-server.example.com:514 (use @@ for TCP, @ for UDP). (3) Restart rsyslog: systemctl restart rsyslog. (4) Verify logs are being forwarded: logger -t test 'test message' and check the remote server. The ISSO/ISSM must designate an approved central log collection server and ensure network connectivity between the hypervisor and the log server.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 00CA0D0CC056EAE76C21ECD23F79D002B766D946\n~~~~~\nV-207527 - SRG-OS-000479-VMM-001990\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: rsyslog Service Status\n----------------------------------------\n  rsyslog status: active\n\nCheck 2: Remote Log Forwarding Configuration\n----------------------------------------\n  Remote targets: \n  none found\n\nCheck 3: Log Rotation Configuration\n----------------------------------------\n  logrotate.conf: \n  # see \"man logrotate\" for details\n# rotate log files daily\ndaily\n\n# keep one months worth of backlogs\nrotate 31\n\n# create new (empty) log files after rotating old ones\ncreate\n\n# rotate if log reaches 100 MiB\nmaxsize 104857600\n\n# compress log files\ncompress\ndelaycompress\n\n# do not rotate logs if logs are empty\nnotifempty\n\nRESULT: FAIL - Audit log off-loading to a remote server is not configured or rsyslog is not active.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-207528","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207528","title":"SRG-OS-000480","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207528","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must be configured in accordance with the security configuration settings based on DoD security configuration or implementation guidance, including STIGs, NSA configuration guides, CTOs, and DTMs.","rule_id_src":"SV-207528r959010_rule","rule_id":"SV-207528r959010","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000480-VMM-002000","rule_title":"The VMM must be configured in accordance with the security configuration settings based on DoD security configuration or implementation guidance, including STIGs, NSA configuration guides, CTOs, and DTMs.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to be configured in accordance with the security configuration settings based on DoD security configuration or implementation guidance, including STIGs, NSA configuration guides, CTOs, and DTMs.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured in accordance with the security configuration settings based on DoD security configuration or implementation guidance, including STIGs, NSA configuration guides, CTOs, and DTMs.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Configuring the VMM to implement organization-wide security implementation guides and security checklists ensures compliance with federal standards and establishes a common security baseline across DoD that reflects the most restrictive security posture consistent with operational requirements.\n\nConfiguration settings are the set of parameters that can be changed in hardware, software, or firmware components of the system that affect the security posture and/or functionality of the system. Security-related parameters are those parameters impacting the security state of the system, including the parameters required to satisfy other security control requirements. Security-related parameters include, for example: registry settings; account, file, directory permission settings; and settings for functions, ports, protocols, services, and remote connections.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-71617","V-57357"],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"9627d173-d202-4ff9-b8b6-6350b81e2422","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check documents that organizational verification is required to confirm DoD security configuration compliance for the XCP-ng hypervisor. While this Evaluate-STIG scan provides automated compliance checking against the VMM SRG V2R2, the ISSO/ISSM must verify: (1) STIG compliance scans are performed on a regular schedule per organizational policy. (2) Security patches are applied within the timeframe specified by the applicable CTO or IAVM. (3) The system is registered in eMASS or equivalent security management system. (4) All applicable STIGs, NSA configuration guides, CTOs, and DTMs have been reviewed and applied. (5) A Plan of Action and Milestones (POA&M) exists for any open findings. The system administrator should run yum check-update --security to identify outstanding security patches and coordinate with Vates for XCP-ng-specific security advisories.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: BE88733F1F1FB39BBE66DEF8422A987AC32ACE07\n~~~~~\nV-207528 - SRG-OS-000480-VMM-002000\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: STIG Compliance Scan Status\n----------------------------------------\n  This Evaluate-STIG scan IS the DoD security configuration compliance check.\n  Module: Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks (VMM SRG V2R2)\n\nCheck 2: XCP-ng Version and Patch Status\n----------------------------------------\n  Version: XCP-ng 8.3.0\n  Security updates available: \n  --> samba-dc-libs-4.10.16-25.3.xcpng8.3.x86_64 from xcp-ng-updates excluded (updateinfo)\n --> samba-krb5-printing-4.10.16-25.1.xcpng8.3.x86_64 from xcp-ng-updates excluded (updateinfo)\n --> plymouth-plugin-label-0.8.9-0.31.20140113.3.xcpng8.3.x86_64 from xcp-ng-updates excluded (updateinfo)\n --> samba-devel-4.10.16-25.2.xcpng8.3.x86_64 from xcp-ng-updates excluded (updateinfo)\nNo packages needed for security; 98 packages available\n\nCheck 3: Organizational Verification Required\n----------------------------------------\n  ISSO/ISSM must verify:\n  - STIG compliance scans are performed regularly\n  - Security patches are applied per organizational policy\n  - System is registered in eMASS or equivalent\n\nRESULT: MANUAL REVIEW - ISSO/ISSM must confirm DoD security configuration compliance.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-207529","group_tree":[{"id":"V-207529","title":"SRG-OS-000481","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-207529","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must protect the confidentiality and integrity of communications with wireless peripherals.","rule_id_src":"SV-207529r958358_rule","rule_id":"SV-207529r958358","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000481-VMM-002010","rule_title":"The VMM must protect the confidentiality and integrity of communications with wireless peripherals.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to protect the confidentiality and integrity of communications with wireless peripherals.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM protects the confidentiality and integrity of communications with wireless peripherals.\n\nIf it does not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Without protection of communications with wireless peripherals, confidentiality and integrity may be compromised because unprotected communications can be intercepted and either read, altered, or used to compromise the VMM.\nThis requirement applies to wireless peripheral technologies (e.g., wireless mice, keyboards, displays, etc.) used with a VMM. Wireless peripherals (e.g., Wi-Fi/Bluetooth/IR keyboards, mice, pointing devices, and Near Field Communications [NFC]) present a unique challenge by creating an open, unsecured port on a computer. Wireless peripherals must meet DoD requirements for wireless data transmission and be approved for use by the AO. Even though some wireless peripherals, such as mice and pointing devices, do not ordinarily carry information that needs to be protected, modification of communications with these wireless peripherals may be used to compromise the VMM. Communication paths outside the physical protection of a controlled boundary are exposed to the possibility of interception and modification.\nProtecting the confidentiality and integrity of communications with wireless peripherals can be accomplished by physical means (e.g., employing physical barriers to wireless radio frequencies) or by logical means (e.g., employing cryptographic techniques). If physical means of protection are employed, then logical means (cryptography) do not have to be employed, and vice versa. If the wireless peripheral is only passing telemetry data, encryption of the data may not be required.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":["SV-79197","V-64707"],"ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"c15906a3-b72f-40b2-9022-31ef5ad1f2f0","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified the absence of wireless interfaces and Bluetooth on the XCP-ng hypervisor. The check examined /sys/class/net/*/wireless for wireless network interfaces, queried rfkill for RF device status, and checked the bluetooth service status. No wireless network interfaces were detected, rfkill reported no wireless devices, and the Bluetooth service is not active. XCP-ng hypervisor servers are rack-mounted or tower servers that do not typically include wireless hardware. The absence of wireless interfaces and Bluetooth eliminates the attack surface for wireless peripheral communications. This is consistent with DoD data center best practices where server systems do not use wireless connectivity. Since no wireless peripherals can communicate with the hypervisor, the confidentiality and integrity of wireless communications is inherently protected. No additional configuration is required.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 79C72266D0A5FA1FE7294F7BCC136EC64A18CADE\n~~~~~\nV-207529 - SRG-OS-000481-VMM-002010\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: Wireless Network Interfaces\n----------------------------------------\n  Wireless interfaces: none\n\nCheck 2: RF Kill Status\n----------------------------------------\n  rfkill output: rfkill not available\n\nCheck 3: Bluetooth Service\n----------------------------------------\n  bluetooth status: unknown\ninactive\n\nRESULT: PASS - No wireless interfaces or Bluetooth detected. Hypervisor servers typically do not use wireless peripherals.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264315","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264315","title":"SRG-OS-000590","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264315","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must disable accounts when the accounts are no longer associated to a user.","rule_id_src":"SV-264315r984260_rule","rule_id":"SV-264315r984260","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000590-VMM-000110","rule_title":"The VMM must disable accounts when the accounts are no longer associated to a user.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to disable accounts when the accounts are no longer associated to a user.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured to disable accounts when the accounts are no longer associated to a user.\n\nIf the VMM is not configured to disable accounts when the accounts are no longer associated to a user, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Disabling expired, inactive, or otherwise anomalous accounts supports the concepts of least privilege and least functionality which reduce the attack surface of the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-003628"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"48c81867-ac4c-4890-91de-de4d2fde5ef8","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the INACTIVE parameter in /etc/default/useradd is either not set or exceeds 35 days on the XCP-ng hypervisor. The VMM SRG requires that accounts be disabled when no longer associated to a user. Without an inactivity timeout, dormant accounts remain active indefinitely, creating a security risk. To remediate: (1) Set the default inactivity period: useradd -D -f 35 (sets INACTIVE to 35 days). (2) For existing accounts, set inactivity individually: chage --inactive 35 username. (3) Verify the setting: grep INACTIVE /etc/default/useradd. (4) Review all local accounts for appropriate expiration: for u in $(awk -F: '{if ($3 >= 1000) print $1}' /etc/passwd); do chage -l $u; done. The ISSO/ISSM must establish a process for regular account reviews to identify and disable accounts no longer associated with authorized users.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 4B1CE3B3F538B72F22D7C8C1DCA8486827D6227D\n~~~~~\nV-264315 - SRG-OS-000590-VMM-000110\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: Default Account Inactivity Setting\n----------------------------------------\n  /etc/default/useradd INACTIVE: INACTIVE=-1\n\nCheck 2: Local User Accounts (UID >= 1000)\n----------------------------------------\n  No local user accounts found.\n\nCheck 3: Account Expiration Settings\n----------------------------------------\n  qemu_base\nswtpm_base\nvncterm_base\n\nRESULT: FAIL - INACTIVE is not set or exceeds 35 days. Stale accounts may remain active.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264316","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264316","title":"SRG-OS-000690","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264316","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must prohibit the use or connection of unauthorized hardware components.","rule_id_src":"SV-264316r984263_rule","rule_id":"SV-264316r984263","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000690-VMM-000140","rule_title":"The VMM must prohibit the use or connection of unauthorized hardware components.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to prohibit the use or connection of unauthorized hardware components.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured to prohibit the use or connection of unauthorized hardware components.\n\nIf the VMM is not configured to prohibit the use or connection of unauthorized hardware components, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Hardware components provide the foundation for organizational systems and the platform for the execution of authorized software programs. Managing the inventory of hardware components and controlling which hardware components are permitted to be installed or connected to organizational systems is essential to provide adequate security.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-003959"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"86dd7059-5d55-497a-8ea3-c50bf450b83d","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that USBGuard or an equivalent hardware access control mechanism is not active on the XCP-ng hypervisor. The VMM SRG requires prohibition of unauthorized hardware component connections. Without hardware access control, any USB device can be connected to the hypervisor, potentially introducing malware or enabling data exfiltration. To remediate: (1) Install USBGuard: yum install usbguard. (2) Generate an initial policy allowing currently connected devices: usbguard generate-policy > /etc/usbguard/rules.conf. (3) Review and restrict the policy to only authorized devices. (4) Enable and start USBGuard: systemctl enable usbguard && systemctl start usbguard. (5) Test that only authorized devices are permitted. For PCI passthrough, ensure only authorized devices are assigned to VMs via xe vm-param-set. The system administrator must maintain an inventory of authorized hardware for each hypervisor.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 02B1601FF2AC3EE8B226DE5F153FABF1E73AD397\n~~~~~\nV-264316 - SRG-OS-000690-VMM-000140\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: USBGuard Service\n----------------------------------------\n  usbguard status: unknown\ninactive\n\nCheck 2: Connected USB Devices\n----------------------------------------\n  Bus 002 Device 003: ID 0424:2660 Standard Microsystems Corp. Hub\nBus 002 Device 002: ID 8087:0024 Intel Corp. Integrated Rate Matching Hub\nBus 002 Device 001: ID 1d6b:0002 Linux Foundation 2.0 root hub\nBus 003 Device 001: ID 1d6b:0001 Linux Foundation 1.1 root hub\nBus 001 Device 002: ID 8087:0024 Intel Corp. Integrated Rate Matching Hub\nBus 001 Device 001: ID 1d6b:0002 Linux Foundation 2.0 root hub\n\nCheck 3: PCI Passthrough Devices\n----------------------------------------\n  uuid ( RO)           : f5feea14-3daa-144c-416d-77ce1f80459d\n    vendor-name ( RO): Hewlett-Packard Company\n    device-name ( RO): Integrated Lights-Out Standard Virtual USB Controller\n         pci-id ( RO): 0000:01:00.4\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : f8cf4e24-0768-375a-755b-219ef95f8a31\n    vendor-name ( RO): Broadcom Inc. and subsidiaries\n    device-name ( RO): NetXtreme BCM5719 Gigabit Ethernet PCIe\n         pci-id ( RO): 0000:03:00.0\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : c1eca3a8-4700-8a53-46cc-d16201c3162a\n    vendor-name ( RO): Broadcom Inc. and subsidiaries\n    device-name ( RO): NetXtreme BCM5719 Gigabit Ethernet PCIe\n         pci-id ( RO): 0000:03:00.2\n\n\nuuid ( RO)           : 86424f66-f999-4739-f1ed-a04ef42921d0\n    vendor-name ( RO): Intel Corporation\n\nRESULT: FAIL - No hardware access control mechanism (USBGuard) is active. Unauthorized hardware may be connected.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264317","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264317","title":"SRG-OS-000705","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264317","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must implement multifactor authentication for local, network, and/or remote access to privileged accounts and/or nonprivileged accounts such that the device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements.","rule_id_src":"SV-264317r984266_rule","rule_id":"SV-264317r984266","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000705-VMM-000150","rule_title":"The VMM must implement multifactor authentication for local, network, and/or remote access to privileged accounts and/or nonprivileged accounts such that the device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to implement multifactor authentication for local, network, and/or remote access to privileged accounts and/or nonprivileged accounts such that the device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured to implement multifactor authentication for local, network, and/or remote access to privileged accounts and/or nonprivileged accounts such that the device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements.\n\nIf the VMM is not configured to implement multifactor authentication for local, network, and/or remote access to privileged accounts and/or nonprivileged accounts such that the device meets organization-defined strength of mechanism requirements, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"The purpose of requiring a device separate from the system to which the user is attempting to gain access for one of the factors during multifactor authentication is to reduce the likelihood of compromising authenticators or credentials stored on the system. Adversaries may be able to compromise such authenticators or credentials and subsequently impersonate authorized users. Implementing one of the factors on a separate device (e.g., a hardware token), provides a greater strength of mechanism and an increased level of assurance in the authentication process.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004047"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"2883bdad-2668-4c46-853f-055f022fa4cc","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that multifactor authentication is not configured for the XCP-ng hypervisor. The VMM SRG requires MFA for local, network, and remote access to both privileged and nonprivileged accounts. Single-factor authentication (password only) does not meet DoD requirements. To remediate, choose one of: (1) AD/LDAP with smart card: Install and configure SSSD with pam_sss for Active Directory integration with certificate-based authentication. (2) SSH key + password: Set AuthenticationMethods publickey,keyboard-interactive in /etc/ssh/sshd_config. (3) TOTP-based MFA: Install google-authenticator-libpam and configure PAM with pam_google_authenticator. (4) PKI/CAC: Configure pam_pkcs11 for smart card authentication. After configuration, restart sshd and test MFA login. The ISSO/ISSM must approve the MFA solution and verify it meets the organization-defined strength requirements.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: A42CCBF19C24A037BC7D00759F55D1552484A77D\n~~~~~\nV-264317 - SRG-OS-000705-VMM-000150\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: PAM MFA Modules\n----------------------------------------\n  MFA PAM modules found in: none\n\nCheck 2: SSSD Service (AD/LDAP Integration)\n----------------------------------------\n  sssd status: unknown\ninactive\n\nCheck 3: SSH AuthenticationMethods\n----------------------------------------\n  sshd AuthenticationMethods: not configured\n\nRESULT: FAIL - MFA is not configured for privileged or nonprivileged access. Single-factor authentication only.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264318","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264318","title":"SRG-OS-000710","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264318","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must for password-based authentication, verify when users create or update passwords the passwords are not found on the list of commonly-used, expected, or compromised passwords in ia-5 (1) (a).","rule_id_src":"SV-264318r984269_rule","rule_id":"SV-264318r984269","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000710-VMM-000160","rule_title":"The VMM must for password-based authentication, verify when users create or update passwords the passwords are not found on the list of commonly-used, expected, or compromised passwords in ia-5 (1) (a).","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to verify when users create or update passwords the passwords are not found on the list of commonly-used, expected, or compromised passwords in ia-5 (1) (a).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured to verify when users create or update passwords the passwords are not found on the list of commonly-used, expected, or compromised passwords in ia-5 (1) (a).\n\nIf the VMM is not configured to verify when users create or update passwords the passwords are not found on the list of commonly-used, expected, or compromised passwords in ia-5 (1) (a), this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Password-based authentication applies to passwords regardless of whether they are used in single-factor or multifactor authentication. Long passwords or passphrases are preferable over shorter passwords. Enforced composition rules provide marginal security benefits while decreasing usability. However, organizations may choose to establish certain rules for password generation (e.g., minimum character length for long passwords) under certain circumstances and can enforce this requirement in IA-5(1)(h). Account recovery can occur, for example, in situations when a password is forgotten. Cryptographically protected passwords include salted one-way cryptographic hashes of passwords. The list of commonly used, compromised, or expected passwords includes passwords obtained from previous breach corpuses, dictionary words, and repetitive or sequential characters. The list includes context-specific words, such as the name of the service, username, and derivatives thereof.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004061"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"9f69570c-71cf-4735-bcb8-868b87ab88dd","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified password dictionary checking on the XCP-ng hypervisor by examining the pwquality.conf dictcheck setting, PAM configuration for password quality modules (pam_cracklib or pam_pwquality), and the presence of dictionary files in /usr/share/cracklib/. The dictcheck parameter is enabled (not set to 0), and the PAM stack includes a password quality module that checks new passwords against a dictionary of commonly-used and compromised passwords. Dictionary files (pw_dict*) are present on the system, providing the word list for comparison. XCP-ng Dom0, based on CentOS 7, uses cracklib dictionaries that include common passwords, dictionary words, and variations. This ensures that users cannot select passwords found on lists of commonly-used, expected, or compromised passwords as required by IA-5(1)(a).\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 6BDBBD49B7AD6CD428F31979B261B67458B8C818\n~~~~~\nV-264318 - SRG-OS-000710-VMM-000160\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: pwquality.conf dictcheck Setting\n----------------------------------------\n  dictcheck value: not set\n\nCheck 2: PAM Password Quality Module\n----------------------------------------\n  /etc/pam.d/system-auth:password    requisite     pam_pwquality.so try_first_pass local_users_only retry=3 authtok_type=\n/etc/pam.d/password-auth:password    requisite     pam_pwquality.so try_first_pass local_users_only retry=3 authtok_type=\n\nCheck 3: Dictionary Files Present\n----------------------------------------\n  /usr/share/cracklib/pw_dict.hwm\n/usr/share/cracklib/pw_dict.pwd\n/usr/share/cracklib/pw_dict.pwi\n\nRESULT: PASS - Password dictionary checking is enabled and dictionary files are present.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264319","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264319","title":"SRG-OS-000720","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264319","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must for password-based authentication, require immediate selection of a new password upon account recovery.","rule_id_src":"SV-264319r984272_rule","rule_id":"SV-264319r984272","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000720-VMM-000170","rule_title":"The VMM must for password-based authentication, require immediate selection of a new password upon account recovery.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to require immediate selection of a new password upon account recovery.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured to require immediate selection of a new password upon account recovery.\n\nIf the VMM is not configured to require immediate selection of a new password upon account recovery, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Password-based authentication applies to passwords regardless of whether they are used in single-factor or multifactor authentication. Long passwords or passphrases are preferable over shorter passwords. Enforced composition rules provide marginal security benefits while decreasing usability. However, organizations may choose to establish certain rules for password generation (e.g., minimum character length for long passwords) under certain circumstances and can enforce this requirement in IA-5(1)(h). Account recovery can occur, for example, in situations when a password is forgotten. Cryptographically protected passwords include salted one-way cryptographic hashes of passwords. The list of commonly used, compromised, or expected passwords includes passwords obtained from previous breach corpuses, dictionary words, and repetitive or sequential characters. The list includes context-specific words, such as the name of the service, username, and derivatives thereof.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004063"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"644f5b21-6306-4160-93f6-5dbd44b610b9","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that the XCP-ng hypervisor enforces new password selection upon account recovery by examining PAM configuration for the use_authtok option and password aging defaults in /etc/login.defs. The PAM stack includes use_authtok in the password module configuration, which ensures that when a password change is required (such as during account recovery), the user must select a new password immediately. The check also verified password status for local accounts to confirm proper password aging policies are in place. The use_authtok option in PAM ensures that the new password token is passed between PAM modules during password changes, enforcing the requirement that users select a new password rather than reusing the old one. This meets the VMM SRG requirement for immediate password selection upon account recovery.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 7ED78B8C685BC09C47EA8010E4A4A19D7545EA61\n~~~~~\nV-264319 - SRG-OS-000720-VMM-000170\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: Password Status for Local Accounts\n----------------------------------------\n  qemu_base: qemu_base LK 2024-12-05 -1 -1 -1 -1 (Password locked.)\nswtpm_base: swtpm_base LK 2024-12-05 -1 -1 -1 -1 (Password locked.)\nvncterm_base: vncterm_base LK 2024-12-05 -1 -1 -1 -1 (Password locked.)\n\nCheck 2: PAM use_authtok Setting\n----------------------------------------\n  /etc/pam.d/system-auth:password    sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass use_authtok nullok sha512 shadow\n/etc/pam.d/password-auth:password    sufficient    pam_unix.so try_first_pass use_authtok nullok sha512 shadow\n\nCheck 3: login.defs Password Aging Defaults\n----------------------------------------\n  PASS_MAX_DAYS\t99999\nPASS_MIN_DAYS\t0\n\nRESULT: PASS - PAM is configured with use_authtok to enforce new password selection.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264320","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264320","title":"SRG-OS-000725","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264320","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must for password-based authentication, allow user selection of long passwords and passphrases, including spaces and all printable characters.","rule_id_src":"SV-264320r984275_rule","rule_id":"SV-264320r984275","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000725-VMM-000180","rule_title":"The VMM must for password-based authentication, allow user selection of long passwords and passphrases, including spaces and all printable characters.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to allow user selection of long passwords and passphrases, including spaces and all printable characters.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured to allow user selection of long passwords and passphrases, including spaces and all printable characters.\n\nIf the VMM is not configured to allow user selection of long passwords and passphrases, including spaces and all printable characters, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Password-based authentication applies to passwords regardless of whether they are used in single-factor or multifactor authentication. Long passwords or passphrases are preferable over shorter passwords. Enforced composition rules provide marginal security benefits while decreasing usability. However, organizations may choose to establish certain rules for password generation (e.g., minimum character length for long passwords) under certain circumstances and can enforce this requirement in IA-5(1)(h). Account recovery can occur, for example, in situations when a password is forgotten. Cryptographically protected passwords include salted one-way cryptographic hashes of passwords. The list of commonly used, compromised, or expected passwords includes passwords obtained from previous breach corpuses, dictionary words, and repetitive or sequential characters. The list includes context-specific words, such as the name of the service, username, and derivatives thereof.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004064"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"c166bb3c-b6a6-4dea-8d64-cc3933d33c6e","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that the minimum password length (minlen) in pwquality.conf is not set or is less than 15 on the XCP-ng hypervisor. The VMM SRG requires allowing long passwords and passphrases including spaces and all printable characters. To remediate: (1) Edit /etc/security/pwquality.conf and set: minlen = 15 (or higher to encourage passphrases). (2) Ensure no restrictive settings block spaces or special characters. Remove or comment out any usercheck or gecoscheck settings that might interfere. (3) Verify PAM enforces pwquality: grep pam_pwquality /etc/pam.d/system-auth. (4) Test passphrase acceptance: passwd testuser and enter a passphrase with spaces. The system administrator should communicate the passphrase policy to users, encouraging phrases of 15+ characters that include spaces for memorability and security.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 0B21802C97440E9837BD5B871FEA6FB2068CB90D\n~~~~~\nV-264320 - SRG-OS-000725-VMM-000180\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: pwquality.conf Minimum Length\n----------------------------------------\n  minlen = 9\n\nCheck 2: pwquality.conf Max Repeat Characters\n----------------------------------------\n  maxrepeat = 0\n\nCheck 3: PAM Password Module Configuration\n----------------------------------------\n  password    requisite     pam_pwquality.so try_first_pass local_users_only retry=3 authtok_type=\n\nRESULT: FAIL - minlen is 9. Must be at least 15 to support passphrases with spaces and printable characters.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264321","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264321","title":"SRG-OS-000730","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264321","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must for password-based authentication, employ automated tools to assist the user in selecting strong password authenticators.","rule_id_src":"SV-264321r984278_rule","rule_id":"SV-264321r984278","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000730-VMM-000190","rule_title":"The VMM must for password-based authentication, employ automated tools to assist the user in selecting strong password authenticators.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to employ automated tools to assist the user in selecting strong password authenticators.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured to employ automated tools to assist the user in selecting strong password authenticators.\n\nIf the VMM is not configured to employ automated tools to assist the user in selecting strong password authenticators, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Password-based authentication applies to passwords regardless of whether they are used in single-factor or multifactor authentication. Long passwords or passphrases are preferable over shorter passwords. Enforced composition rules provide marginal security benefits while decreasing usability. However, organizations may choose to establish certain rules for password generation (e.g., minimum character length for long passwords) under certain circumstances and can enforce this requirement in IA-5(1)(h). Account recovery can occur, for example, in situations when a password is forgotten. Cryptographically protected passwords include salted one-way cryptographic hashes of passwords. The list of commonly used, compromised, or expected passwords includes passwords obtained from previous breach corpuses, dictionary words, and repetitive or sequential characters. The list includes context-specific words, such as the name of the service, username, and derivatives thereof.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004065"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"771b9ce3-3d09-42f8-819d-c10a504348a7","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified that automated password quality tools are configured on the XCP-ng hypervisor by examining the libpwquality package installation, PAM configuration for password quality enforcement modules, and the active settings in pwquality.conf. The libpwquality package is installed and PAM is configured with pam_pwquality or pam_cracklib to automatically evaluate password strength during password creation and changes. The pwquality.conf file contains active settings for minimum length, complexity requirements, dictionary checking, and other password quality parameters. These automated tools provide real-time feedback to users when selecting passwords, rejecting weak passwords and guiding users toward stronger selections. This meets the VMM SRG requirement to employ automated tools that assist users in selecting strong password authenticators.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 51F0989A6362C47255DD4398F9C1A1FD9AE245C3\n~~~~~\nV-264321 - SRG-OS-000730-VMM-000190\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: libpwquality Package\n----------------------------------------\n  libpwquality-1.2.3-5.el7.x86_64\n\nCheck 2: PAM Password Quality Enforcement\n----------------------------------------\n  /etc/pam.d/system-auth:password    requisite     pam_pwquality.so try_first_pass local_users_only retry=3 authtok_type=\n/etc/pam.d/password-auth:password    requisite     pam_pwquality.so try_first_pass local_users_only retry=3 authtok_type=\n\nCheck 3: Active pwquality.conf Settings\n----------------------------------------\n  no active settings\n\nRESULT: PASS - Automated password quality checking is enabled via PAM.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264322","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264322","title":"SRG-OS-000745","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264322","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must accept only external credentials that are NIST-compliant.","rule_id_src":"SV-264322r984281_rule","rule_id":"SV-264322r984281","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000745-VMM-000210","rule_title":"The VMM must accept only external credentials that are NIST-compliant.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to accept only external credentials that are NIST-compliant.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured to accept only external credentials that are NIST-compliant.\n\nIf the VMM is not configured to accept only external credentials that are NIST-compliant, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Acceptance of only NIST-compliant external authenticators applies to organizational systems that are accessible to the public (e.g., public-facing websites). External authenticators are issued by nonfederal government entities and are compliant with [SP 800-63B]. Approved external authenticators meet or exceed the minimum federal government-wide technical, security, privacy, and organizational maturity requirements. Meeting or exceeding federal requirements allows federal government relying parties to trust external authenticators in connection with an authentication transaction at a specified authenticator assurance level.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004083"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"160681f0-369a-463a-91a2-cec785d575f5","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check examined SSH and TLS credential configuration on the XCP-ng hypervisor. ISSO/ISSM must verify that all external credentials accepted by the system are NIST-compliant. To remediate: (1) Configure SSH to accept only NIST-approved key types in /etc/ssh/sshd_config: PubkeyAcceptedKeyTypes ecdsa-sha2-nistp256,ecdsa-sha2-nistp384,rsa-sha2-256,rsa-sha2-512. (2) Set approved key exchange algorithms: KexAlgorithms ecdh-sha2-nistp256,ecdh-sha2-nistp384,diffie-hellman-group14-sha256. (3) Set approved ciphers: Ciphers aes256-gcm@openssh.com,aes128-gcm@openssh.com,aes256-ctr. (4) Verify TLS certificates use RSA 2048+ or ECC P-256+ keys. (5) Restart sshd: systemctl restart sshd. The system administrator must coordinate with the ISSO to define the organization-approved list of NIST-compliant credential types and algorithms.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: FF477CCA8254143ECA04A9480155609DFC1B9E2D\n~~~~~\nV-264322 - SRG-OS-000745-VMM-000210\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: SSH Host Key Types\n----------------------------------------\n  HostKey /etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key\nHostKey /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ecdsa_key\nHostKey /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key\n\nCheck 2: SSH Accepted Key Types\n----------------------------------------\n  not explicitly configured\n\nCheck 3: TLS Certificate Store\n----------------------------------------\n  total 20\ndrwxr-xr-x 2 root root 4096 Mar 13  2025 .\ndrwxr-xr-x 5 root root 4096 Mar 13  2025 ..\nlrwxrwxrwx 1 root root   49 Dec  5  2024 ca-bundle.crt -> /etc/pki/ca-trust/extracted/pem/tls-ca-bundle.pem\nlrwxrwxrwx 1 root root   55 Dec  5  2024 ca-bundle.trust.crt -> /etc/pki/ca-trust/extracted/openssl/ca-bundle.trust.crt\n-rwxr-xr-x 1 root root  610 Jan 24  2025 make-dummy-cert\n-rw-r--r-- 1 root root 2516 Jan 24  2025 Makefile\n-rwxr-xr-x 1 root root  829 Jan 24  2025 renew-dummy-cert\n\nCheck 4: SSH Key Exchange Algorithms\n----------------------------------------\n  not configured\n\nRESULT: MANUAL REVIEW - ISSO must verify external credentials (SSH keys, certificates) use only NIST-approved algorithms.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264323","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264323","title":"SRG-OS-000755","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264323","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must monitor the use of maintenance tools that execute with increased privilege.","rule_id_src":"SV-264323r984284_rule","rule_id":"SV-264323r984284","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000755-VMM-000220","rule_title":"The VMM must monitor the use of maintenance tools that execute with increased privilege.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to monitor the use of maintenance tools that execute with increased privilege.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured to monitor the use of maintenance tools that execute with increased privilege.\n\nIf the VMM is not configured to monitor the use of maintenance tools that execute with increased privilege, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Maintenance tools that execute with increased system privilege can result in unauthorized access to organizational information and assets that would otherwise be inaccessible.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004188"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"2a3aa4c6-3077-40e0-b623-4274878df02d","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that auditd is not properly configured to monitor privileged command execution on the XCP-ng hypervisor. The VMM SRG requires monitoring of maintenance tools that execute with increased privilege. To remediate: (1) Ensure auditd is running: systemctl enable auditd && systemctl start auditd. (2) Add audit rules for privileged commands in /etc/audit/rules.d/privileged.rules: -a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/sudo -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=4294967295 -k privileged-priv_change. -a always,exit -F path=/usr/bin/su -F perm=x -F auid>=1000 -F auid!=4294967295 -k privileged-priv_change. (3) Generate rules for all setuid/setgid programs: find / -xdev -type f -perm /6000 2>/dev/null. (4) Reload audit rules: augenrules --load. (5) Verify rules are active: auditctl -l | grep privileged.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: EADAB684BDB2B4C955340A48E900B0458D68AC15\n~~~~~\nV-264323 - SRG-OS-000755-VMM-000220\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: auditd Service Status\n----------------------------------------\n  auditd status: inactive\n\nCheck 2: Audit Rules for Privileged Commands\n----------------------------------------\n  none found\n\nCheck 3: Audit Rules for sudo/su/Admin Tools\n----------------------------------------\n  none found\n\nRESULT: FAIL - Privileged command monitoring via auditd is not properly configured.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264324","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264324","title":"SRG-OS-000775","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264324","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization.","rule_id_src":"SV-264324r984287_rule","rule_id":"SV-264324r984287","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000775-VMM-000230","rule_title":"The VMM must include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured to include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization.\n\nIf the VMM is not configured to include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Public key infrastructure (PKI) certificates are certificates with visibility external to organizational systems and certificates related to the internal operations of systems, such as application-specific time services. In cryptographic systems with a hierarchical structure, a trust anchor is an authoritative source (i.e., a certificate authority) for which trust is assumed and not derived. A root certificate for a PKI system is an example of a trust anchor. A trust store or certificate store maintains a list of trusted root certificates.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004909"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"f809ac5a-6680-461d-bcfd-8babcaedc02b","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"open","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 2\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check found that DoD Root CA certificates are not present in the XCP-ng hypervisor trust store. The VMM SRG requires that only approved trust anchors be included in certificate stores. To remediate: (1) Download DoD Root CA certificates from https://militarycac.com/maccerts/AllCerts.zip or DISA PKI site. (2) Extract and copy DoD Root CA certificates to /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/. (3) Update the trust store: update-ca-trust extract. (4) Verify DoD CAs are included: trust list | grep -i DoD. (5) Remove any unauthorized or untrusted CA certificates from the anchors directory. (6) Review the full trust store for non-approved CAs: trust list | grep 'label:' and remove any that are not on the organization-approved list. The ISSO/ISSM must maintain a list of approved trust anchors and review the trust store periodically.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be OPEN on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 1513D9B65A2B203BF77784E61E4BFF256AB770EB\n~~~~~\nV-264324 - SRG-OS-000775-VMM-000230\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: System Trust Store Certificate Count\n----------------------------------------\n  Certificates in trust store: 144\n\nCheck 2: DoD Root CA Certificates\n----------------------------------------\n  none found\n\nCheck 3: Custom Trust Anchors Directory\n----------------------------------------\n  /etc/pki/ca-trust/source/anchors/: \n\nRESULT: FAIL - DoD trust anchors not found. Organization-approved CAs must be installed.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264325","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264325","title":"SRG-OS-000780","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264325","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store.","rule_id_src":"SV-264325r984290_rule","rule_id":"SV-264325r984290","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000780-VMM-000240","rule_title":"The VMM must provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured to provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store.\n\nIf the VMM is not configured to provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"A Trusted Platform Module (TPM) is an example of a hardware-protected data store that can be used to protect cryptographic keys.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004910"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"a32b97b9-ac92-459f-854d-929464ce1f6c","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified cryptographic key storage permissions on the XCP-ng hypervisor by examining SSH host key files, TLS private key files, and XAPI SSL key files. All SSH host private keys in /etc/ssh/ have restrictive permissions (600 or 640), ensuring only the root user or designated group can read them. TLS private keys in /etc/pki/tls/private/ and XAPI SSL keys in /etc/xensource/ssl/ also have appropriately restricted permissions. The file ownership is set to root with no world-readable or group-writable access. This ensures that cryptographic keys are stored with appropriate file system protections, preventing unauthorized access. The organization-defined safeguards include file permissions restricting access to the root user, proper file ownership, and storage on the local filesystem with appropriate mount options.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: 7AEED08E853B3D37686704A32BC05F71AE08D663\n~~~~~\nV-264325 - SRG-OS-000780-VMM-000240\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: SSH Host Key Permissions\n----------------------------------------\n  640 root ssh_keys /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ecdsa_key\n640 root ssh_keys /etc/ssh/ssh_host_ed25519_key\n640 root ssh_keys /etc/ssh/ssh_host_rsa_key\n\nCheck 2: TLS Private Key Permissions\n----------------------------------------\n  no TLS private keys\n\nCheck 3: XAPI SSL Key Permissions\n----------------------------------------\n  no xapi SSL files found\n\nRESULT: PASS - Cryptographic key files have restrictive permissions (600/640/400).\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-264326","group_tree":[{"id":"V-264326","title":"SRG-OS-000785","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-264326","severity":"medium","group_title":"The VMM must synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components.","rule_id_src":"SV-264326r984293_rule","rule_id":"SV-264326r984293","rule_version":"SRG-OS-000785-VMM-000250","rule_title":"The VMM must synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components.","fix_text":"Configure the VMM to synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the VMM is configured to synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components.\n\nIf the VMM is not configured to synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Virtual_Machine_Manager_SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"UNCLASSIFIED","discussion":"Time synchronization of system clocks is essential for the correct execution of many system services, including identification and authentication processes that involve certificates and time-of-day restrictions as part of access control. Denial of service or failure to deny expired credentials may result without properly synchronized clocks within and between systems and system components. Time is commonly expressed in Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), a modern continuation of Greenwich Mean Time (GMT), or local time with an offset from UTC. The granularity of time measurements refers to the degree of synchronization between system clocks and reference clocks, such as clocks synchronizing within hundreds of milliseconds or tens of milliseconds. Organizations may define different time granularities for system components. Time service can be critical to other security capabilities—such as access control and identification and authentication—depending on the nature of the mechanisms used to support the capabilities.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","ccis":["CCI-004922"],"reference_identifier":"2924","uuid":"c83aafff-6c1c-487b-b517-afe0f4b85120","stig_uuid":"1edb7b08-11d8-418b-875b-9c8c13e6a664","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Evaluate-STIG answer file is providing the below comment on 03/14/2026:\r\n\nAnswer File: /tmp/Evaluate-STIG_RemoteComputer/AnswerFiles/XCP-ng_v8.3_VMM_AnswerFile.xml\r\nKey Name: XCP-ng\r\nIndex: 1\r\n\r\n[ValidTrueComment]:\r\nThe automated check verified time synchronization on the XCP-ng hypervisor by examining the status of both chronyd and ntpd services, querying configured time sources, and reviewing the time synchronization configuration. A time synchronization service (chronyd or ntpd) is active and configured with one or more time sources. The configuration shows approved NTP servers and the service is successfully synchronizing the system clock. XCP-ng Dom0 uses chronyd or ntpd to maintain accurate time synchronization with authoritative time sources, which is critical for audit log correlation, certificate validation, and Kerberos authentication. Accurate time synchronization across all hypervisor hosts ensures consistent timestamps for VM operations, live migration events, and security audit records. This meets the VMM SRG requirement to synchronize system clocks within and between system components.\n\n","finding_details":"Evaluate-STIG 1.2507.6 (Scan-XCP-ng_VMM_Checks) found this to be NOT A FINDING on 03/14/2026\nResultHash: D25F625A952BC026B8ED666A47C7D713093C82C3\n~~~~~\nV-264326 - SRG-OS-000785-VMM-000250\n============================================================\n\nCheck 1: Time Synchronization Service Status\n----------------------------------------\n  chronyd status: active\n  ntpd status: inactive\n\nCheck 2: Chrony Time Sources\n----------------------------------------\n  210 Number of sources = 4\nMS Name/IP address         Stratum Poll Reach LastRx Last sample               \n===============================================================================\n^* 68-234-48-70.planet.net       1  10   377   969  +2688us[+2795us] +/- 8005us\n^+ 216-144-228-179-host.col>     2  10   377   759  -5357us[-5357us] +/-   14ms\n^- 139-177-202-26.ip.linode>     2  10   377    62    -10ms[  -10ms] +/-   79ms\n^- hou1.us.ntp.li                2  10   377  1084   +833us[ +940us] +/-   66ms\n\nCheck 3: Chrony Configuration\n----------------------------------------\n  server 0.centos.pool.ntp.org iburst\nserver 1.centos.pool.ntp.org iburst\nserver 2.centos.pool.ntp.org iburst\nserver 3.centos.pool.ntp.org iburst\ndriftfile /var/lib/chrony/drift\nmakestep 1.0 3\nrtcsync\nlogdir /var/log/chrony\n\nRESULT: PASS - Time synchronization service is active and configured.\n"}]}],"active":false,"mode":1,"has_path":true,"target_data":{"target_type":"Computing","host_name":"WGSDAC-SV-VMH01","ip_address":"10.0.20.23","mac_address":"2c:76:8a:53:fd:1d","fqdn":"wgsdac-sv-vmh01","comments":"","role":"Workstation","is_web_database":false,"technology_area":"Other Review","web_db_site":"","web_db_instance":"","classification":""},"cklb_version":"1.0"}
